<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Ford'sTheater     06-24 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Ford's Theater,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Helps Theater Mark 20th Anniversary of Restoration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LaToya Jackson rode a motorcycle onto the
stage and dazzled President Reagan and the audience with a gaudy
demonstration of modern rock 'n' roll song and dance Friday night
to mark the 20th anniversary of the restoration of Ford's Theater.
   An array of celebrities _ including yesteryear rock 'n' roll
stars Fabian, Frankie Avalon and Bobby Rydell _ took part in the
gala benefit performance to help raise money for the theater's
endowment fund.
   Among the other performers were singer Rosemary Clooney, actress
Shirley Jones and comedian Sid Caesar.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, came onto the stage at the end of
the show, and Reagan talked about the theater that was closed in
1865 after President Abraham Lincoln was assassinated.
   The theater remained closed for over a century until it was
reopened, after renovation, in 1968.
   Reagan said the theater long has represented a place ``to
refresh, to uplift, to give joy.''
</TEXT>
