<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoundtrackSuit     06-24 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soundtrack Suit,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Sues Actor-Movie Maker Spike Lee for $350,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor-director Spike Lee has been sued by the
actress who played the female lead in his movie ``School Daze,''
who says she has not received artistic credit or money for singing
in the film.
   Tisha Campbell, 19, said in the $350,000 suit filed Thursday in
state Supreme Court that her career was damaged because Lee and
others refused to give her the singing credit.
   Lee's lawyer, Arthur Klein, said he had no comment on the suit,
which also names as defendants EMI Records, Columbia Pictures and
Lee's company, 40 Acres and a Mule Productions Inc.
   Miss Campbell has a solo on the ``School Daze'' soundtrack album
and performs a song with someone else, said Jules Kurz, one of her
attorneys. The Screen Actors Guild contract requires that she get a
separate contract for her singing, Kurz said.
   ``All we really wanted was a fair royalty,'' Kurz said, ``but
Lee basically refused to negotiate that point.''
   The soundtrack album has been on the Billboard magazine Top 100
albums list since April, and a single from the album has been in
the Top 100 about three weeks, said another Campbell attorney,
Bruce Colfin.
   Miss Campbell has appeared on television in ``The Cosby Show''
and ``Rags to Riches.'' Her stage work includes ``Little Shop of
Horrors'' and ``Mama I Want to Sing.''
</TEXT>
