<DOCNO> AP880624-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Women'sLaw     06-24 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Women's Law,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Fight for Women's Rights in China</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of lawyers working out of a two-room
office behind gray brick walls in central Beijing has come to the
defense of the rising number of Chinese women who seek legal means
to redress wrongs.
   According to the law, women in China have equal status with men,
but in reality women traditionally are often looked down upon.
   They increasingly face discrimination at work, particularly in
hiring and promotions. Supervisors frequently reject women
applicants on the grounds they are not as efficient or skillful as
men.
   Accounts of wife beatings appear regularly in the Chinese press,
and cases of arranged marriages and girls being sold into marriage
have resurfaced in the countryside.
   The 18 lawyers at the Beijing 8th Lawyer Office _ 17 of whom are
women _ exclusively help women facing such problems. In the past
three years, they have counseled more than 3,000 women and handled
nearly 400 cases in court.
   On the walls of their small office near Tiananmen Square are
reminders of some of their victories.
   A set of calligraphy scrolls, commissioned by a grateful client
who won her case against a bigamist husband, hangs just inside the
door.
   ``Upright for life, your spirit lives as long as heaven and
earth,'' it says in praise of the lawyers.
   Established in 1985 by the All-China Women's Federation, the
legal center is the first and largest of its kind in China.
   Similar legal aid offices for women have opened in the southern
city of Canton (Guangzhou) and in Sichuan province, but none has as
big a staff or case load as the Beijing office.
   ``Everyone has the same goal,'' the deputy chief lawyer, Zhang
Xiaoqing, said of her colleagues. ``We want to use our legal
knowledge for the benefit of women and children.''
   In the cramped and badly lit office, Yu Lin, in her 60s,
conducted an interview one recent day with a 47-year-old divorced
woman who was fighting for custody of her 6-year-old son.
   Nearby, Tian Hui, a 24-year-old lawyer, sat at a narrow, wooden
desk carefully taking notes as a 39-year-old factory worker from
the countryside talked about her dissatisfaction with a recent
divorce settlement.
   The client fought back tears as she related how her second
husband asked for a divorce because his two children by a previous
marraige were grown and he no longer needed her.
   The district court had already granted the divorce, but she was
unhappy with the financial settlement, which awarded her husband
their six joint bank accounts, their apartment and furnishings and
bicycle.
   Women like these have a hard time getting legal aid, because
China has a shortage of lawyers _ only 20,000 to 30,000 for a
country of more than 1 billion people, Zhang said.
   The 8th Lawyer's Office is open mornings for walk-in
consultations. In the afternoons, the lawyers work on cases.
   Fees start at 50 fen (13 cents) for consultations and are never
more than 2 yuan (54 cents). The basic fee is 1 yuan (27 cents),
but about one-third of the women are too poor to pay even that.
   To represent a client in a divorce case, the lawyers charge 30
to 50 yuan ($8 to $13), based on rates set by the state, but again
about 30 percent of the women pay less or nothing.
   Some women learn of the office from a notice in the Beijing
Intermediate People's Court while others are referred by the
Women's Federation.
   ``We only take on those cases that are reasonable,'' Zhang said.
``If they have no (legal) reason for bringing up a case, we try to
explain the law to them. That's part of our work too.''
   One of their more interesting cases involved a 60-year-old
deaf-mute woman whose husband was branded a counter-revolutionary
during the ultra-leftist 1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
   Out of concern for his wife and two children, the man divorced
the wife and told her they would remarry if his perilous situation
improved.
   After the Cultural Revolution, he was rehabilitated, received
back pay and given compensation for his home and household goods
that were confiscated.
   The man, however, married someone else, moved to another
province and never paid child support or gave any kind of financial
assistance to his first wife for the years she reared their
children on her own.
   The 8th Lawyer's Office took her case to court, which ruled that
the man had to pay the woman 1,500 yuan ($405).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
