<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A khaki-clad Princess Diana fired two powerful
guns, detonated a dud charge and drove an armored vehicle in a mock
battle with the British Army.
   The wife of the heir to Britain's throne was so enthusiastic
about her half day on the ``front'' Thursday that soldiers said
they'd love to have her join their ranks.
   ``She seemed to thoroughly enjoy the number of bangs and noises
going off everywhere,'' said Maj. Willy Peto, an escort to the
princess during the Bridge Over the River Avon battle. ``I think
she would make an extremely good soldier.''
   The battle took place on army land on the Salisbury Plain
southwest of London.
   Diana, wearing khaki overalls and pink high-top sneakers,
laughed as she operated a 76mm cannon on a Scorpion armored vehicle
and a 30mm cannon on a Scimitar armored vehicle.
   Later, she sat in a trench as small-arms fire rang out, and
pressed a button to detonate a fake charge simulating the blowing
up of a bridge.
   She then climbed into an armored reconnaissance vehicle equipped
with air defense missiles and drove two miles across the
battlefield to a lunch of army ration steak-and-kidney pie.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable mogul Ted Turner said Soviet
citizens have the same major concerns as Americans: death, tasty
food, good drinks and sex.
   ``The Soviet people are a lot like you and me ... They don't
want to die,'' the founder of Cable News Network told the Marshall
Management Association.
   ``They like to go to the beach. They like to be warm in the
winter and cool in the summer. They like to have a good meal. They
like to have a good drink. They like to'' have sex, Turner said
Wednesday night.
   Turner, whose Atlanta-based Superstation WTBS televised the
Goodwill Games from Moscow and recently aired a series on life in
the Soviet Union, said the arms race has gone on too long.
   ``It's time to bring that part of mankind's history to a close.
We ended slavery 135 years ago. We gave women the right to vote and
educated them 85 years ago and we ended segregation 25 years ago,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No matter what family or friends think, Barbara
Bush says she'll never dye her hair _ well, maybe once.
   ``If it were St. Patrick's Day and I wasn't running for office,
I might do it green for a day,'' said the white-haired wife of Vice
President George Bush, the probable Republican nominee for
president. ``But other than that, never.''
   In the July 26 issue of Woman's Day, Mrs. Bush, 63, confides
that her family and friends once discussed whether she needed to
change her hair color.
   ``They decided I should, and then nobody had the nerve to bring
it up. It hurt me when I heard that, actually,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedians George Burns and Red Skelton are
among the eight TV greats being inducted into the Television Hall
of Fame this fall along with their late colleagues Jack Benny and
Gracie Allen.
   The other inductees are David Brinkley and the late Chet
Huntley, one of the top television news teams of the 1950s and
1960s, and producers David Wolper and the late David Susskind, it
was announced Thursday.
   Burns and Allen, who were married, appeared on radio and
television for many years until Allen's death, and Burns continues
to make movies and TV appearances. Susskind and Wolper were
responsible for some of television's most memorable programs.
   The Nov. 19 induction will be telecast in a two-hour special on
the Fox network Nov. 28.
   Burns, Brinkley, Skelton and Wolper are expected to be at the
ceremonies. The others will be honored posthumously.
   The Hall of Fame was established five years ago by the Academy
of Television Arts & Sciences.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Kenny Rogers will host a daily
television talk show, and plans to make another TV special, a
production company says.
   The one-hour talk show will be syndicated for telecast this
fall, Jon Peters, co-managing director of Guber-Peters-Barris, told
a news conference Thursday.
   The prime-time special, ``Kenny Rogers' Classic Weekend,'' will
be taped on his Georgia farm, Peters said.
</TEXT>
