<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Italy-Bomb     06-24 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Italy-Bomb,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Damages Building In Bolzano</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-pound bomb exploded in front of a
government office building in the center of this regional capital,
causing property damage but no casualties, investigators said.
   It was the third blast in recent days in Italy's Alto Adige
province, torn by ethnic tensions between its German-speaking and
Italian-speaking inhabitants.
   The investigators said Thursday that the explosion Wednesday
broke windows and damaged cars in a parking lot.
   An official of the local government said German-speaking
separatists were suspected in the attack. Since January over 20
bombings have claimed four lives in the province.
   The violence stems from tensions between the region's 300,000
ethnic Germans and 125,000 Italians. The region, also known as
South Tyrol, was stripped from Austria at the end of World War I.
   The German-speaking majority wants priority in obtaining
government jobs and more control over local broadcasting.
Extremists want an independent Tyrolian state.
</TEXT>
