<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietNovelist-Rybakov     06-24 1076</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Novelist-Rybakov,1107</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author Remained Patient Through Publishing Delays</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly N. Rybakov, author of ``Children of the
Arbat,'' is in the front rank of those struggling to reform the
Soviet system, a system which sent him to Siberia in the 1930s and
blocked publication of his novel for 21 years. His book, finally
published in Russian last year, has recently appeared in English
and his been critically acclaimed.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEREDELKINO, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly Naumovich Rybakov, still
energetic at 77, jumped up and pulled a bundle of papers from one
of the shelves that line the study of his cottage in the forested
writers' colony outside Moscow.
   Carefully, lovingly, the novelist laid the bundle on the desk
next to the window, untied the string and pulled out two covers of
the largest Soviet literary magazine, Novy Mir, one from 1966 and
the other from 1978.
   In the soft light, filtered through the trees, Rybakov held up
first one and then the other of the blue sheets of stiff paper,
tracing with his gnarled finger the underlined announcement that
the journal would soon publish ``Children of the Arbat,'' his novel
of the Great Terror waged by dictator Josef V. Stalin in the 1930s.
   Both times, in 1966 and 1978, publication was blocked by the men
in the Kremlin, men who rose to power under Stalin.
   Rybakov's patience paid off.
   More than 21 years after it was written, ``Children of the
Arbat'' was published last year in the literary journal Druzhba
Narodov (Friendship of Peoples), as part of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
campaign to reform the tyrannical system created by Stalin.
   The novel has since appeared in hardback editions, and was
published in English in the United States last month by Little,
Brown & Co.
   The book probes more deeply than any other yet published in the
Soviet Union into Stalin's mind and methods, the pettiness and
arbitrariness that guided his followers, the innocence of his
victims and the terror he created.
   It tells the story of Sasha Pankratov, a young man of 23 who,
like Rybakov, was sentenced without trial for a crime he never
committed and sent to Siberia for three years of cold and lonely
exile.
   Rybakov grew up in the apartment building inhabited by most of
the book's characters, No. 51 Arbat Street, an old shopping street
in downtown Moscow that was at once popular among the Communist
Party elite and among fashionable young people.
   Rybakov is working on the sequel, ``1935 and Other Years,''
which will continue the story, and like ``Children of the Arbat,''
will give intimate portraits of Stalin and his lieutenants and
describe how he terrorized his deputies and the country.
   ``The entire nation lived in fear,'' said Rybakov, his craggy
features grim beneath a balding pate and gray hair. ``Only one
person thought for himself. Everyone else abandoned free thought.''
   Gorbachev and his supporters have concluded that a nation based
on such a system cannot survive in the technological age.
   During the years Rybakov waited for his blockbuster to appear in
print, he lived and worked at his peaceful dacha, or cottage, at
Peredelkino, the wooded village where the Nobel Prize-winning poet
and novelist Boris Pasternak wrote and is buried. Rybakov earned a
comfortable living by writing 11 other novels, as well as
screenplays for television and movies.
   He resisted the temptation to publish his works abroad, as
Pasternak, Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn and others had done. Pasternak
was ostracized, his works banned until recently, and Solzhenitsyn
was exiled to the West.
   ``I wanted to publish it in this country,'' said Rybakov. ``I
wanted to change my country. That is why I have been so patient.''
   Hardback and paperbound editions of the book are expected to
reach 3.5 million copies, he said, a phenomenal circulation in the
Soviet Union , where a run of 100,000 is considered generous for
works of fiction.
   The book disappears from stores before it reaches the shelves.
The only places it can be found in Moscow are in hotel shops open
only to foreigners and at a special store on Kropotkin Street that
accepts no rubles, only Western currency. On the black market, it
sells for 30 rubles ($51.40), more than 10 times its retail price.
   Inside the Kropotkin store, a saleswoman told an American
visitor, ``I'm sorry. We don't have `Children of the Arbat.' It
hasn't come in yet.''
   Then she lowered her voice. ``I'll get you a copy. But just
one.'' She disappeared, returning a few minutes later with the
volume.
   The written word has played a huge role in Russia since the 19th
century, when works by writers such as Pushkin and Tolstoy were a
moral and spiritual counterbalance to the authoritarian rule of the
Czars. The influence of writers in the Soviet Union is immensely
greater than that of any American author in the United States.
   ``I don't think that fiction is as important in the United
States in shaping the image of a country in the minds of the
people,'' said Rybakov, just back from a month-long trip to
America, his third visit in as many years.
   In reforming the Soviet system, said Rybakov, ``the first step
is to change the psychology of the people. Perestroika
(restructuring) started in literature, films, the mass media, the
fields that shape people's spiritual lives and thinking.''
   ``We need to reshape people's minds, and that will inevitably
lead us to economic freedom,'' said Rybakov.
   ``Children of the Arbat'' deals largely with the purges within
the Communist Party, and only mentions in passing a far bloodier
episode _ the 1929-32 collectivization of agriculture _ which
caused a famine and, according to estimates by Western scholars,
claimed 8 million lives.
   Rybakov said he will explore this in greater depth in his next
novel.
   ``My figures are even higher,'' he said.
   Although food shortages persist, six decades later Soviet
authors have only tentatively touched on the collectivization
issue. Any detailed discussion might lead to calls to return the
land to private farmers, a step reformers in China have taken.
   Rybakov lets a grin crease his leathery face: ``I am no expert
on decollectivization, but we need greater freedom in the village.''
   The smile gives way again to a look of grim determination. ``Who
will take land and cultivate it if he fears that someone will take
it away from him?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Restaurants     06-24 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Restaurants,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurants Tackle No-Shows, Some Single Out Americans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The party of five from the advertising agency was
not unusual, says restaurant owner Neville Blech. They reserved a
table for 1 p.m. and called at 1:40 p.m. to cancel.
   But for Blech, ``it was the last straw.'' He sued the agency in
small claims court and won, demonstrating how some British
restaurants are beginning to fight back against the problem of
no-show diners.
   ``These people are messing about with my livelihood. It's bad
news,'' says Blech, who won about $140 _ or the average gross
profit from a lunch for five at Mijanou, his posh 30-seat French
eatery.
   While few choose to sue, many are casting off customary British
reserve to fight what they say is a growing lack of consideration
among modern diners. Some say American tourists are among the worst
offenders.
   But this in turn has caused divisions, with other restaurateurs
saying no-shows are an inescapable fact of life.
   The Restaurateurs Association of Great Britain, representing 500
dining spots mostly in London, is compiling a list of repeat
offenders for its members.
   ``Certain people have already come to light'' after six weeks of
collecting information, association Chairman Roy Ackerman said in
an interview.
   He denied it was a blacklist, saying the association lets the
restaurant decide whether it wants to refuse a booking or ask for a
deposit in advance.
   Ackerman acknowledges the tactic may scare away customers or be
dodged by using a false name. But he believes the mere existence of
the list may be a deterrent.
   ``We're there to serve people, so we don't want to put people
off booking or eating out,'' he says. ``But we're trying to ask for
courtesy in exchange for our hospitality.''
   The association took action because ``it seemed to be a practice
which was growing. We had complaints from a lot of our members,''
who suspect some people double- or triple-book.
   Blech estimates he loses $8,850 annually from no-shows and
places some blame on trans-Atlantic visitors.
   ``Judging by their accents, I have to say some of the worst
offenders are American tourists,'' he says. ``They come over, pick
your name out of a guide, shop late at Harrods and decide they're
too tired to go out to eat.''
   Ackerman, however, says ``people from all walks of life'' are
guilty, adding: ``Who's going to say anything about the Americans?
We need them.''
   He says the spread of the problem is ``a natural phenomenon
because more and more people are eating out ... Competition to get
a good table at a restaurant is that much more competitive.''
   Restaurateurs say customers don't realize that when they book a
table, they are entering into a contract _ a fact of British law
that won Blech his court case.
   No-shows also don't understand how much they can hurt a
restaurant. A 40-seat eatery may not break even on a night when a
table of four or six fails to show up, says Ackerman.
   The rival 15,000-member British Hotels, Restaurants and Caterers
Association also worries about the problem, but disagrees with
drawing up a list.
   ``We don't believe it's easy to operate,'' said Robin Lees,
chief executive of the association. ``The only way to make sure is
that when the contract is made ... (the owner) has sufficient
information to come back _ either in small claims court or on the
telephone _ to say look, we had a contract.''
   Others say even that sounds too strong.
   ``If you lose a table once every few days it doesn't matter so
much,'' says Aron Misan, the French owner of Keat's eatery. ``It's
part of the business.''
   He says he calls no-shows the next day, says ``You've been a
naughty boy,'' and then this ``chap has respect for you, you keep
friends ... the other way you make enemies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrainDerailment 3rdLd-Writethru a0843 06-24 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0843,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phosphorus Reignites In Derailed Train</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to CORRECT that authorities urged, sted
ordered, evacuation; UPDATES quotes; picks up 6th graf: `Earlier
Thursday ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OWB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROFTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phosphorus inside a derailed tank car
reignited Thursday night as workers tried the right the car, and
authorities urged a second nighttime evacuation because of a
wind-blown, toxic cloud, officials said.
   ``The intensity of the smoke has diminished significantly. It's
not without its problems, but it now appears to be taking a better
direction,'' Don Armstrong, a spokesman for the state Department of
Disaster and Emergency Services, said late Thursday night.
   Phosphorus spilled from the ruptured tanker in Wednesday night's
34-car derailment, formed a cloud and then burst into flames in the
99-degree heat, burning for more than 12 hours.
   The toxic cloud forced residents in five western Kentucky
counties to evacuate, and about 50 familes living in the immediate
area were advised to stay away from their homes Thursday.
   The new cloud, 100 yards wide and 400 feet high, was moving
southeast toward the tiny community of Apex in northeast Christian
County, where officials warned residents but evacuations were
voluntary, Armstrong said.
   He said officials believe the fire will burn itself out, but,
``We're still cautioning people to stay upwind from the smoke.''
   Earlier Thursday, officials said the crew of the derailed
freight train might have avoided the accident had it seen a 10 mph
speed limit sign.
   The speed limit was posted because of a track problem. The train
was traveling 35 mph, Tim Hensley, a spokesman for CSX
Transportation Corp., said Thursday.
   ``This probably is a factor, but we are not saying that this is
a cause,'' Hensley said. ``And it has not been developed whether it
was human error on the part of the crew, or whether they were not
provided with the information with regards to that slow order.''
   Hensley said the safety order was issued because of a
one-block-long stretch of rough track, possibly caused by heat
extension of the rails.
   Hensley said the track was supposed to have been posted with a
warning sign one mile before the rough section, but the crew
reported that they didn't see it. The only sign they said they saw
was at the point of the rough track, he said. It was too late then
to avoid the derailment.
   Residents evacuated from the path of the toxic vapor began
returning to their homes Thursday. Officials asked about 50
families in the immediate vicinity of the derailment to stay out of
the area.
   The evacuations included towns in five counties with a combined
population of about 2,500. But Red Cross workers were unable to say
immediately how many people left their homes.
   No serious injuries were reported but several people were
treated for throat and lung irritations caused by the smoke, which
blanketed the rural area 80 miles northwest of Nashville, Tenn.
   Randy Looney and his wife, Tricia, were roused by firefighters,
scooped up their infant son and headed for a shelter set up at the
Crofton Elementary School.
   Their house trailer less than two miles from the derailment was
filled with acrid smoke, Looney said.
   ``It smelled like sulfur and burned your lungs,'' he said.
``When we went outside, you could hardly see anything.''
   The chemical burst into flames when the 34 cars derailed in a
steep ravine about two miles north of Crofton, a town of about 900
people.
   The Federal Aviation Administration restricted air traffic over
the site until about dawn Thursday and safety workers temporarily
sealed off roads in the vicinity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
