<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-University-Gays     06-24 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-University-Gays,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Finds in Favor of Homosexual Groups at Arkansas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Arkansas violated the
constitutional rights of a homosexual group by denying it funds, a
federal appeals court has ruled.
   A three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
overturned a lower court ruling Wednesday and ordered appropriate
relief to the school's Gay and Lesbian Students Association (GSLA).
   The GSLA filed suit after the university's Student Senate, which
decides on funding for student organizations, denied the group's
request for funds because of the content of its message, a
violation of the First Amendment.
   ``In brief,'' the appeals court said, ``we hold that a public
body that chooses to fund speech or expression must do so
even-handedly, without discriminating among recipients on the basis
of their ideology.
   ``The university need not supply funds to student organizations,
but once having decided to do so, it is bound by the First
Amendment to act without regard to the content of the ideas being
expressed.
   ``This will mean ... that the taxpayers will occasionally be
obligated to support not only the thought of which they approve,
but also the thought that they hate. This is one of the fundamental
premises of American law.''
   The appeals court rejected the school's claims that the case was
moot and that it does not have the final say over the Student
Senate's funding decisions.
   In elaborating on it's decision, the appeals court said: ``True,
sodomy is illegal in Arkansas. However, the GLSA does not advocate
sodomy, and, even if it did, its speech about an illegal activity
would still be protected by the First Amendment. People may extol
the virtues of arson or even cannibalism. They simply may not
commit the acts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
