<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SwindallProbe Bjt   06-24 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall Probe, Bjt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Ethics Committee Launches Investigation Of Swindall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee has launched a
preliminary investigation to determine if Georgia Rep. Pat Swindall
violated the law or House rules in pursuing a loan after being told
it likely would be financed by drug money he would be helping to
launder.
   After a closed-door meeting Thursday, the committee issued a
statement saying it had received evidence ``reasonably indicating''
that Swindall, a second-term Republican, may have violated laws or
acceptable standards in his negotiations for an $850,000 loan.
   Swindall, who represents a suburban Atlanta district, asked the
committee last week to review his actions in the negotiations last
fall for the loan he was seeking to finance construction of his
$1.2 million home in Stone Mountain, Ga.
   Swindall left Washington for Georgia on Thursday. Arriving at
Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport, he said he had asked for
and welcomed the investigation.
   ``Basically, I've turned it over to them,'' he said. ``If
anything unethical's been done, I want to know.''
   A preliminary inquiry is the first step in an ethics committee
investigation. If the panel finds reason to believe that the
alleged violation in fact occurred, it makes a formal statement of
the violation and can ultimately recommend disciplinary action
ranging from reprimand to expulsion.
   Swindall asked for the investigation one day after The Atlanta
Journal and The Atlanta Constitution reported details of the loan
negotiations that came from conversations secretly recorded during
a federal money laundering investigation.
   The taped conversations involved discussions between Swindall
and two other men _ Charles LeChansey, who later was indicted on
money laundering charges, and Michael Mullaney, an undercover
Internal Revenue Service agent posing as a money broker for
underworld figures.
   The newspaper said the tapes show that Swindall continued to
pursue the loan for several weeks after Mullaney had advised him
that it might be financed with illegal drug or gambling profits.
   Swindall at one point accepted a $150,000 check from LeChansey
but returned it uncashed several days later. The tapes show that he
broke off the negotiations after Mullaney told him he would have to
accept the loan proceeds in cash and sign a receipt for them.
   ``The only reason I can't do that is I would then be essentially
laundering y'all's money,'' Swindall told Mullaney, according to
the newspapers' account of the tapes. ``In other words, if Charles
(LeChasney) wants to launder y'all's money, fine, but I can't do
that, and to sign a receipt of cash would be to do that.''
   At a news conference last week, Swindall apologized for his role
in the negotiations, saying he was wrong and ashamed but would
continue to seek re-election.
   ``I was wrong to have ever considered such a proposal, to have
discussed it,'' he said. ``I was wrong not to have gone to
authorities before I did.''
   Swindall said, however, that he eventually ``made the right
decision'' in walking away from the deal and insisted that he ``did
not break the law nor do anything unethical.''
   Swindall is the only candidate in the Aug. 9 Republican primary
for his 4th District seat. Since qualifying for the primary has
ended, his name is the only one that can appear on the Republican
primary ballot under state law.
   Three Democrats are competing in their party's primary for the
right to challenge Swindall in the November general election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-VeteransRecords Bjt   06-24 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veterans Records, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duplicate Records Could Reopen Thousands of Veterans' Disability
Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veterans Administration is launching a
massive review of rejected disability claims following the
discovery of 10 million military medical records that duplicate
some lost in a 1973 fire.
   Veterans groups say thousands of veterans from World War II and
the Korean War could be affected by the discovery. They say the
newfound records would provide verification for claims denied
because there were no records to substantiate them.
   Thomas K. Turnage, the VA administrator, announced the discovery
on Thursday and called it a ``very important'' development.
   ``It opens up new vistas for us. It means that these people who
before had difficulty establishing a basis for their disability
compensation, or the degree of it ... it means we can have another
chance to look at it and, in effect, may come up with a different
result,'' Turnage said.
   The VA said that it would immediately begin going through the
new data and reviewing claims rejected because of lost records. The
agency urged veterans seeking information about their claims to
contact their VA regional offices.
   Turnage said the VA had become aware of the information last
week, and it was too early to say how many people would be
affected. He also did not have figures on how many claims were
denied because of lost records.
   Officials cautioned against overestimating the impact of the
discovery. R.J. Vogel, the VA's benefits director, said that most
veterans who made disability claims did so during their initial
years after service and would likely have filed claims before 1973.
   But John Sommer, director of the American Legion Veterans
Affairs and Rehabilitation Commission, whose office helps veterans
with their disability claims, said there was no doubt the
development could affect thousands.
   ``You'd be amazed at the number of people, World War II veterans
in particular, who waited until they retired to file a claim with
the VA, and then found the records had been destroyed,'' he said.
``Many of them felt they just didn't want to take anything from the
government. ... Then, as they aged, they decided to file a claim
and discovered their records had been burned.''
   Others likely to be affected include people with an injury or
disease suffered during active duty that became more pronounced
over the years, such as a back or heart ailments, officials said.
   Eighteen million military personnel records were destroyed or
seriously damaged in the July 12, 1973, fire at the National
Personnel Record Center in St. Louis. The lost records were from
the years 1912 through 1959 for Army personnel, and 1947 through
1963 for Air Force personnel with the surnames of Hubbard and
through the letter Z.
   The duplicate records cover the years 1942 to 1945 and 1950 to
1954, and so will primarily affect veterans of World War II and the
Korean War.
   The records were collected by the National Research Council, a
private research organization, during the 1950s as part of its
analysis of Army hospital records. A researcher at the council came
across the records and notified the National Archives, said Jill
Brett, an archives spokeswoman.
   Ms. Brett said that the records are on computer magnetic tapes
created by the council from hospital admissions punch cards
prepared by the office of the surgeon general. She said the
archives paid the council $8,662 for the tapes and will reformat
them for cross-referencing against other files.
   She said they were not listed by the military officer's name,
but included the officer's serial number, grade and rank, age, date
and place of admission as well as disease and diagnosis.
   Of the 10 million files, there were 3.5 million files for the
year 1944 alone, Turnage said, covering about 2.4 million people.
For 1945, 2 million files were discovered, covering about 1.4
million people. He said the agency still was trying to compile the
breakdown for the other years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0023 </DOCNO>
