<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FairHousing     06-24 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Housing,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Vote on Fair Housing Bill Could Come Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House is close to approval of legislation
to strengthen enforcement of the nation's fair housing law after
defeating a proposal to eliminate the ban on discrimination against
families with children.
   Final approval in the House should come sometime next week,
although no specific time has been set because leaders want to
complete action on remaining appropriation bills before the end of
the month.
   ``Fair housing is a top priority item,'' said House Majority
Whip Tony Coehlo, D-Calif., on Thursday before the House recessed
so members could attend the funeral of Rep. John J. Duncan,
R-Tenn., in Knoxville.
   The Senate is expected to act quickly after the House vote, thus
sending the measure to the White House before the end of the summer.
   Rep. Peter W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J., chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, said, ``This legislation to finally make fair
housing a reality for so many Americans is another significant step
forward for our nation in eliminating discrimination and providing
equal opportunity for all in one of our most basic human needs _
housing.''
   The bill would give the Department of Housing and Urban
Development the power to bring actions on behalf of individual
victims of discrimination, would ban discrimination against the
disabled and forbid limitations on renting to families with
children, except in clearly defined retirement communities.
   The House eliminated the last controversial amendment on
Thursday, when members voted 289-116 to defeat a proposal by Rep.
E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., that would have eliminated the provisions
protecting families with children under age 18 from housing
discrimination.
   Shaw said that the bill's language was confusing, unenforceable
and would ``wipe out every senior citizen community in this
country.'' Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chief sponsor, argued that
the provision had been drafted in consultation with groups
representing senior citizens and had received their full support.
   Since enactment of the first federal law to ban discrimination
in the sale and rental of housing in 1968, the homebuilding and
sales industries have staved off repeated efforts to toughen
enforcement rules. The recurring battles have embittered civil
rights advocates and denied millions of families equal access to
decent housing.
   However, a crucial compromise was reached late last week and
announced on Tuesday that set the stage for quick passage of the
bill.
   Originally, the bill would have created a system of
administrative law judges who would hear cases against alleged
housing violators when conciliation failed. The judges could award
actual damages to a plaintiff and impose fines. Any ruling could be
appealed to the federal court.
   The Reagan administration and the National Association of
Realtors opposed the bill because they believed that administrative
law judges would create constitutional problems. They argued that
an accused party could be forced to pay fines and damages without a
jury trial, in violation of the Constitution's Seventh Amendment.
   Under the compromise, however, either the plaintiff or the
defendant can elect to go to federal court first, thus satisfying
the objections of the administration and the Realtors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0025 </DOCNO>
