<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PentagonConsultants     06-24 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon Consultants,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Defends Its Use of Consultants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's chief spokesman says it has
never tried to disguise the amount of money it spends on
consultants, particularly since a lot of the work they perform is
demanded by Congress.
   Dan Howard, in a lengthy rebuttal Thursday to complaints by Sen.
David H. Pryor, D-Ark., said the Pentagon will spend $3.87 billion
on all types of consulting services during the current fiscal year.
   Pryor, the chairman of a Senate Governmental Affairs
subcommittee that has been investigating the government's use of
private consultants, accused the Pentagon on Tuesday of keeping a
``shadow government under wraps.''
   Citing a General Accounting Office review, the senator said the
Pentagon claimed it spent only $155 million on outside consultants
in fiscal 1987 when in reality it had spent $2.8 billion.
   Howard used his regular Pentagon briefing on Thursday to counter
the assertions, saying Pryor's figures were wrong. He said the $155
million figure came not from the Defense Department, but from a GAO
information-gathering system that Howard said demonstrates the
maxim ``garbage in, garbage out.''
   Of the total the Pentagon will spend this year, the spokesman
continued, $254 million will go for ``studies, analyses and
evaluation.''
   ``One of the things it includes is a number of studies mandated
by the Congress. Since 1970, the number of annual studies required
of the Department of Defense by the Congress has increased 1,900
percent. It has gone from 36 reports in 1970 to 719 reports this
year,'' Howard said.
   ``Were it not for the contracting of these reports (to
consultants), we estimate that it would have required ... an
additional 29,000 DoD employees to do the reports.''
   Howard said the Pentagon this fiscal year will spend $11.4
million on individual experts and consultants; $970 million on
``management support'' studies such as developing a computer model
to predict future aircraft costs; $379.7 million on engineering and
technical support to teach military personnel how to operate and
repair new weapon systems, and $583.8 million on ``information
technology,'' meaning the maintenance and acquisition of computer
data bases.
   ``All told, that is $2.199 billion in the fiscal 1988 budget,''
the spokesman said.
   In addition to those programs, the Pentagon will spend $943
million on outside systems engineering contracts, he continued.
   ``Systems engineering people are those who, for example, when
you install a new complex system in an aircraft, an existing
aircraft, ensure that the systems all fit together; that they all
work together,'' he said.
   A final category totals $725 million and involves federal
funding for certain key research and development centers that
perform dozens of military studies every year, such as the Rand
Corp. and the Institute for Defense Analysis, Howard said.
   ``So if you combine the two categories _ the contracted advisory
and assistance services at $2.199 billion, and these other contract
services, you get a grand total of $3.87 billion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
