<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HousePhones     06-24 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Phones,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phone Problems Put Congress on Hold; Was AT&T `The Right Choice?'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frustrated House members are calling a new $16
million telephone system ``a failure'' after its third outage in as
many days, and some are beginning to wonder whether selecting AT&T
was ``the right choice.''
   The House of Representatives system was out of order for more
than two hours on Thursday, bringing howls from members unable to
communicate with constituents or with their home district offices.
   The outage also forced House leaders to resort to hand signals
to communicate with their floor organizers.
   ``It's like returning to the 19th century,'' said one leadership
aide.
   One lawmaker, Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., went to the floor and
held up two styrofoam coffee cups linked by a piece of wire.
   ``If I get the contract for $10 million or so to install this in
the House of Representatives, I promise that it will work just as
well as the phone system we have here now,'' he said.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. flew in top management and
technical executives from around the country in an attempt to
ferret out the mystery bug in the balky computer switching system.
   The system, called System 85, controls some 17,000 telephones in
three House office buildings, two annexes and the House side of the
Capitol. It was installed last August after AT&T won in a
competitive bidding process held by the House Administration
Committee.
   The problems began last week, when the system shut down for
nearly an hour. Substantial outages have occurred at least three
times since then, and Thursday's was the longest yet.
   AT&T officials met with the chairman of the panel's office
systems subcommittee, Rep. Charles Rose, D-N.C., late Thursday.
Rose later went to the House floor to implore members ``to be as
indulgent and patient as they can'' and promised that if the system
isn't working by the July Fourth weekend, ``the whole blooming
thing will be replaced.''
   Ray Colley, the deputy House clerk, said the system is one of
the largest in the country and the problems are atypical. ``It's a
flukey sort of thing,'' he said. ``We're losing a lot of calls,
obviously. ... Believe me, we have total attention from AT&T.''
   Technicians suspected a computer software problem, perhaps
exacerbated by an unusually high volume of calls coming through the
system. But they were examining everything, including the
possibility of computer hackers tampering with the system from
outside, Colley said.
   Congressional offices reported everything from totally dead
telephones to intermittent service on some lines. In some offices,
all the phones suddenly rang at once.
   Kolbe said the communications glitch reminded him of the AT&T
television commercials showing distraught employees bemoaning their
choice of a competing phone system and discussing how their
businesses had been ruined. The commercials end by proclaiming AT&T
``the right choice.''
   ``Well, in the interest of ... truth in advertising, I think we
ought to admit that the same source of that advertising is the one
that has the telephone system here in the House,'' Kolbe said.
   ``I don't know what motivated this installation of the new
system, but it's certainly proven to be a failure,'' complained
Rep. Walter Jones, D-N.C. If Alexander Graham Bell, the inventor of
the telephone, had been around the House the past two weeks, he
``would have been most depressed and despondent, to say nothing of
being embarrassed,'' Jones said.
   Herb Linnen, an AT&T spokesman, said the company was trying to
replicate the House calling patterns in its Denver laboratories to
help isolate the problem, but had been unable so far to do so.
   ``We are totally empathetic'' with the frustration of lawmakers,
Linnen said. ``We are frustrated. We have a commitment to get the
... problem fixed as quickly as possible,'' he said.
</TEXT>
