<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Koop-Health     06-24 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koop-Health,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koop Calls For More Emphasis on Preventing All Diseases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, stepping
beyond his role as a chieftain in the fight against AIDS and
smoking, says the nation should lend additional emphasis to
prevention of all diseases.
   ``It is a strange paradox in our health system,'' Koop told a
congressional panel Thursday. ``We recognize that the promotion of
good health and the prevention of disease is the way to go. We
recognize that it is every effective and we recognize that it is
very cheap.
   ``But we tend not to pay for it.''
   Appearing before the health subcommittee of the Joint Economic
Committee, Koop said there are three ``overarching issues'' dealing
with the long-range future of health care in America:
   _The evolving relationship between technology and health care.
   _The emerging changes in the way the public relates to organized
medicine.
   _The potential changes in how society's values may hamper the
historic financial support for a broad-based health care system.
   He said that Americans are ``preoccupied with health'' and drawn
to glamorous high-tech solutions.
   ``The things such as prevention of disease, promotion of health,
good counseling ... are very effective, very cheap, but have no
glamour whatsoever. I think we have to face the fact that you can
have glamour as long as it is cheap, but when glamour gets as
expensive as it is, you have to sort of trim your sails.''
   On the second point, he said the new mobility of American
society makes it much less likely ``the average patient will be
known and served by the same physician and same hospital staff for
a lifetime.''
   He said that an estimated 15 million Americans have turned to
self-help because they have lost a sense of personal contact with
doctors and other health professionals.
   ``My only concern _ and it's a major concern _ is that some
people who need the help of experts with medical training aren't
getting it or are avoiding it and their health and possibly their
lives may be in peril as a consequence,'' he said.
   A third major concern, he said, is that the public might seek
retribution in the future against people with certain illnesses
that may be associated with lifestyle.
   He said the American people are generous in supporting, through
taxes and personal donations, the goal of good health for everyone
in society.
   ``But they can also become impatient,'' he said. ``For example,
most Americans disapprove of smoking and would like to see all
smokers stop. ... Hence, the non-smoking public is asking for new
and stronger state and local laws to curb cigarette smoking in the
work place and in all public governmental and commercial
buildings.''
   Calling this an example of ``public retribution directed against
smokers,'' Koop cautioned that such movements should be kept in
perspective.
   He expressed concern that such trends toward retribution could
result in a backlash against health care spending on people with
illnesses that probably could have been prevented with healthier
lifestyles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
