<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     06-24 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Signs One Tax Measure, Backs Another</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis' move to help
balance his state budget with $115 million in new taxes immediately
spilled over into the presidential campaign, with the campaign of
Republican George Bush pouncing on the plan.
   In addition to announcing his support of tax measures, Dukakis
faced a barrage of questions Thursday about an FBI investigation of
the siting of a Massachusetts prison and the indictment of his
former top education adviser for alleged corruption.
   Dukakis was heading to the island of Nantucket today for a
four-day vacation.
   Before traveling to Washington for a unity dinner Thursday
night, Dukakis signed a $40 million state cigarette tax and said he
supported raising another $75 million by bringing the Massachusetts
tax code in line with federal tax changes.
   He downplayed the political ramifications, saying his immediate
concern was to ``make sure that the state's fiscal base is solid
and strong.''
   But the Bush camp immediately labeled Dukakis a tax-raiser.
   ``It's obvious that his reaction is to tax,'' said Bush
spokeswoman Sheila Tate. ``Instead of cutting (spending), he raised
taxes. It seems to speak for itself.''
   Dukakis disagreed.
   ``I think the people of this state and the people of this
country can recognize when someone is talking about fiscal
responsibility and someone who is doing it,'' Dukakis told a
Statehouse news conference.
   ``Gov. Dukakis has balanced nine budgets and is about to balance
a 10th, which stands in stark contrast to eight years of a
Reagan-Bush administration that has left us with more red ink than
all the previous administrations combined,'' the Dukakis campaign
said in response to Tate's remarks.
   The Massachusetts Constitution requires the governor to balance
the budget although Dukakis has twice inherited deficits.
   Dukakis had to decide by today whether to sign the legislation
authorizing the 5 percent sales tax on cigarettes and other tobacco
products. The tax is effective in 90 days.
   House-passed legislation to raise about $75 million by
conforming state tax codes with federal tax laws, which is awaiting
approval in the Senate, would affect about 15 percent of the
state's 4 million taxpayers. The ``coupling'' tightens exemptions
for tax shelters and business expenses and would affect mainly the
wealthy.
   Dukakis also wants to raise about $16 million by closing a
corporate tax loophole. Because revenues have not met projections,
he now favors an $11.8 billion spending plan, some $200 million
less than his original proposal.
   Dukakis has said he would raise federal taxes only as a last
resort, seeking first to reduce the deficit by trimming spending,
cutting inflation rates through economic growth and collecting
unpaid taxes.
   The long-awaited word on Dukakis's position on the tax proposals
came the same day the FBI said it was conducting a preliminary
inquiry into plans to build a medium-security prison in rural New
Braintree.
   The agency said it was reviewing whether there were possible
violations of the Hobbs Act, a federal anti-racketeering statute.
Dukakis is not currently a subject of the investigation, the FBI
said.
   Opponents of the proposed prison contend the owner of the land
purchased it after receiving inside information that it was being
eyed by the state.
   ``The process was as open as it could possibly be,'' Dukakis
said. ``We have very tough procedures for the acquisition of
property.''
   Also Thursday, former Dukakis education adviser Gerard T.
Indelicato was accused of larceny and forgery related to his state
duties. Indelicato previously pleaded guilty to separate federal
charges of fraud and conspiracy.
   ``The criminal charges against Gerard Indelicato are very
serious, more so because they allege a violation of the public
trust,'' Dukakis said. ``I expect every public official who works
for the commonwealth to meet the highest standards of integrity.''
</TEXT>
