<HEAD>Man Arrested In Honeywell Parking Ramp Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to delete reference to number of rapes; ADDS graf
of background on previous charges against Thomas</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with previous rapes and
released from prison last month was arrested Thursday in the
slaying of a Honeywell Inc. manager on a parking ramp, police said.
   David Anthony Thomas, 26, was arrested without resistance at the
Epilepsy Foundation in St. Paul where he worked, police Capt. Carl
Johnson said. He said fingerprints at the murder scene led to the
arrest.
   Police have until noon Saturday to charge Thomas in the June 12
death of Mary Catherine Foley, 34, of St. Paul, Johnson said.
   Johnson said police have found ``absolutely no connection''
between Thomas and Foley.
   Foley's death came 16 days after 19-year-old Carrie Coonrod of
Eau Claire, Wis., was stabbed to death on a downtown Minneapolis
parking ramp. A suspect in the Coonrod killing was arrested shortly
afterward and has been indicted.
   Three other attacks on women in Minneapolis since May 22 had
heightened concerns about the safety of women where they work.
Among the victims was an attorney abducted from her downtown office
and repeatedly raped during a 13-hour ordeal.
   Johnson said Thomas was identified in 1980 in several
burglary-rapes in south Minneapolis, less than a mile from the
murder scene. Johnson said he was not certain of the disposition of
the cases, but said Thomas was placed on probation and didn't serve
time in prison until he violated terms of the probation.
