<2ND_LINE>PM-Seasick Seaman,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ill Seaman Who Wanted To Go Ashore Charged With Mutiny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seasick seaman accused of threatening to
kill the captain of a commercial fishing boat unless he was
returned to shore said he was so sick he ``couldn't take it
anymore.''
   Patrick James D'Alessandro, 27, of Cape May, N.J., who allegedly
brandished a rifle and a knife in his attempt to get back on land,
was charged Thursday with assault and mutiny. He faces up to 20
years in prison if convicted on the federal charges.
   ``I didn't want to hurt anyone. I couldn't take it anymore,''
said D'Alessandro in a telephone interview from the Newport News
City Jail.
   ``I just wanted to go home,'' he said.
   D'Alessandro, who had never been to sea before, acknowledged
that he was armed with a .22-caliber rifle and a knife when he
demanded Wednesday afternoon that Capt. Edward Lominec of the
70-foot Miss Marie take him ashore because he was seasick.
   D'Alessandro was taken into custody by the Coast Guard Wednesday
evening and no one was injured in the incident, which occurred
about 90 miles east of Cape Hatteras, N.C.
   Lominec and three other crewmen aboard the boat said
D'Alessandro threatened to kill the captain if the vessel didn't go
to shore, said Lt. Allan Black, commanding officer of the Coast
Guard patrol boat that responded to the vessel's call for help.
</TEXT>
