<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Turkey-Handslides Bjt   06-24 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey-Handslides, Bjt,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Landslide Forces Suspension Of Rescue Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tons of rocks and earth tumbling down on a
mountain village have forced the suspension of rescue work at the
site of a major landslide that buried at least 100 people alive,
officials said.
   Radio reports late Thursday said villagers heard people crying
for help from underneath the debris.
   The victims, including 30 travelers stranded in a coffeehouse by
an earlier landslide early Thursday, were buried by the major
landslide which swept down on Catak village Thursday afternoon,
according to reports from the northeastern area.
   Catak is located in Trabzon province about 500 miles northeast
of Ankara and not far from the Black Sea. The earth was loosened by
heavy rains in the region, where frequent landslides are sometimes
blamed on extensive cutting of forests.
   Provincial Deputy Gov. Haydar Ozgun said it was feared the death
toll would be high, since so many people were missing. Rescuers,
hobbled all day by rain, had recovered only one body by late
Thursday, provincial Governor Enver Hizlan announced.
   An announcement over loud speakers by the Turkish Red Crescent,
a relief organization, caused panic when it said 300 people had
been killed, the independent Hurriyet News Agency said. Officials
denied that the toll was so high.
   State radio reported that at least 31 people were injured in the
disaster in Catak. One victim said the landslide came without
warning Thursday.
   ``It happened all at once after a noise that sounded like
thunder,'' Turan Alemdar, a truck driver who witnessed the
disaster, was quoted as saying by Hurriyet. ``The rocks swept away
everything in a second.''
   ``I saw the mountain coming over me and started running away,''
Zeki Ilhan was quoted as saying by the semi-official Anatolia news
agency.
   State radio said villagers reportedly heard people crying for
help as they lay underneath a mass of earth and stones.
   Rescue teams put off work until early today after a third
landslide hit area Thursday evening. No one was reported buried in
the new slide which dumped tons of mud and rocks near the village.
   Ozgun told The Associated Press by telephone that land slide
experts had ordered the rescue operations halted for the day.
   Hizlan said that a German rescue team today will fly in to help
Turkish rescue efforts. He said the German team would bring trained
dogs to help dig out victims.
   The mud and rock roared down a mountainside onto at least three
houses, four stores, a restaurant, a high school and the crowded
coffeehouse, according to news agency reports.
   Several buses and cars were lined up on the road when the
landslides hit, state radio said.
   Televised reports said the landslides had also caused a river to
flood the village. Footage showed houses under water.
   Landslides blocked a riverbed and sent the waters coursing
through the village, according to news reports.
   The televised reports also showed trees and lampposts lying on
ground. Some vehicles were buried in soil.
   A survivor wrapped in blankets said on television that he was
trapped in the coffeehouse but swam out.
   Rescue workers recovered two minibuses under the wreckage, but
no one was found inside, according to news services.
   Television also showed footage of the village smothered between
mountains with the roofs of its houses barely protruding from the
rubble.
   The reports said it took about four hours for rescue teams to
reach the site. They said 40 trucks and 20 bulldozers tried
unsuccessfully to push away the mud and stone which covered the
area. They moved slowly for fear of causing new landslides.
   Buses and vehicles were waiting on road at the time of the slide
because the highway was closed by the earlier landslide Thursday
shortly after midnight, the reports said.
   Deputy Gov. Erkan Isilgan told The Associated Press that
authorities were trying to find out whether the buses were carrying
any foreign tourists.
   Isilgan said 17 houses in the village were evacuated.
   The Red Crescent sent 150 tents to the area and dispatched a
mobile hospital, according to the news reports.
   Meanwhile, the closure of the highway disrupted traffic in the
area. Bus services from eastern provinces to Tarbzon province were
canceled, Hurriyet said. Vehicles formed long lines on both sides
of the highway waiting for bulldozers to clear the road.
</TEXT>
