<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Fire 7thLd-Writethru(a0468   06-24 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Fire, 7th Ld-Writethru( a0468,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge Gasoline Tanks Explode, Two Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with injury toll revised upward in
graf 2, arrival of special equipment in grafs 12-13, EDITS
elsewhere to conform, no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUADALUPE, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three huge gasoline tanks exploded
Thursday at a depot in this northeastern industrial city, killing
at least two people and starting a blaze too hot for firefighters
to approach, officials said.
   Twenty people were hospitalized with burns, including six in
very serious condition, officials said.
   Several vehicles parked near the tanks turned to molten metal
and the temperature near the fire at times reached 5,400 degrees,
said Nuevo Leon state judiciary police director, Hernan Guajardo
Garza, who visited the site.
   Two workers died from burns at the San Rafael tank farm owned by
the government petroleum monopoly, Pemex, said Raul de la Garza,
Nuevo Leon press secretary. De la Garza earlier had said four
workers died but later corrected the figure, citing his latest
information.
   Pemex spokesman Guillermo Guevara, at a press conference with de
la Garza, said firefighters managed to extinguish the flames in two
of the tanks around 11:30 p.m. EDT, and said they expected the
blaze in the third tank to be put out early Monday.
   De la Garza said 10,000 people were evacuated from their homes
around the tank farm in case the flames spread.
   About 200 amy infantry troops cordoned off the area to prevent
looting and the government news agency Notimex quoted police as
saying 40 people found loitering around evacuated houses were
detained for questioning.
   Federal and state police blocked access roads to Guadalupe,
creating traffic jams around the greater Monterrey metropolitan
area.
   The three tanks exploded one after another starting at about 3
p.m. (5 p.m. EDT). At 9:30 p.m. (11:30 p.m. EDT), the fire was
still out of control and a reddish glow could be seen 10 miles away.
   Flames shot up more than 100 feet in the air, and palls of smoke
about 1,000 feet high rising from the three burning tanks.
   Guadalupe is just outside Monterrey, Mexico's industrial center
and its third largest city, with a population of about 2 million.
Both cities are about 440 miles northeast of Mexico City.
   Firefighters at the tank farm said intense heat prevented them
from approaching the three tanks to pour in chemicals to control
the blaze. Authorities said they used 50-foot pipes that can eject
chemical foam at a great distance to put out fires at two of the
tanks.
   The special equipment was flown in from the Gulf of Mexico port
of Ciudad Madero, 280 miles southeast of Guadalupe.
   The San Rafael complex has 23 tanks of about 55,000 barrels
capacity each, where Pemex stores gasoline and diesel oil for
retail distribution in Monterrey and other parts of northeastern
Mexico.
   Guillermo Guevara, a Pemex spokesman, said in a telephone
interview the three tanks were full of low-grade, 81-octane
gasoline. He said the other tanks contained higher-grade, 90-octane
gasoline and diesel oil, mostly used by trucks.
   ``We're trying to control the fire and allow the gasoline to be
consumed naturally. Gasoline ... is very flammable, it burns
easily. We don't know why the explosions occurred. We can't get
close enough to investigate because it's too hot,'' Guevara added.
   Fire brigades were also rushed to the scene from dozens of
industrial plants in Monterrey, including private companies, the
Monterrey airport, other Pemex facilities in the area and the
nearby Pemex refinery at Cadereyta.
   Guevara said a total of 2.26 million gallons of liquid fuel was
stored at the tank farm.
   He said 250 Pemex workers are employed at the tank farm, but
added he did not immediately know how many were at the site when
the explosions occurred.
   Four Pemex workers were hospitalized with second- and
third-degree burns on more than 50 percent of their bodies, and two
others were hospitalized with lesser injuries, Guevara said.
   Natalia Palacios, who lives about four blocks southeast of the
tank farm, said se took her family of eight, including an uncle and
aunt, out of their home, and rushed them to a friend's home farther
away, where they planned to spend the night.
   Mrs. Palacios said her husband works at another Pemex plant.
   An explosion and fire May 24 at Pemex's gas and kerosene supply
depot in the northern city of Chihuahua caused the evacuation of
more than 100,000 residents, according to the Chihuahua state
government.
   Pemex's preliminary report on that disaster found that a spark
during the installation of firefighting equipment touched off the
blaze.
</TEXT>
