<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraSuit     06-24 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Suit,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Christic Suit Against `Guns-For-Drugs' Contra
Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's dismissal of a damage suit
accusing 29 people of running a guns-for-drugs smuggling scheme to
aid the Contra rebels was angrily denounced by stunned plaintiffs
as a political move.
   But one of the defendants, who included former CIA officials,
Contra leaders and cocaine traffickers, said the $24 million
lawsuit was itself a political attack on the Reagan administration
and probable Republican presidential nominee George Bush.
   ``I'm very pleased,'' retired Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub, a key
figure in the Iran-Contra scandal, said following Thursday's
ruling. ``I think the case is 100 percent political.''
   Chief U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King's ruling also
cleared Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord and Albert Hakim, former
CIA deputy director of operations Theodore Shackley, Contra leader
Adolfo Calero and leaders of Colombia's violent Medellin Cartel.
   In granting summary judgments to the defendants, King found that
the plaintiffs, two journalists, had failed to prove their case.
   Christic Institute attorney Daniel Sheehan, whose liberal,
Washington-based organization represented the plaintiffs, accused
King of political motivations in his ruling and said he would
appeal to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
   ``The judge's action is a conscious action to stop this case
from going to trial before the election,'' said Sheehan. ``The
court has defied the law, not just mistaken the law.''
   Sheehan and the plaintiffs said they were stunned the judge's
ruling came only a few days before the trial was to start Monday.
   Tony Avirgan, who filed the suit with his wife Martha Honey
after being wounded in a 1984 bombing blamed on the defendants,
reacted angrily to the decision.
   ``I think it's absolutely absurd that the judge has said we
don't have enough evidence,'' Avirgan said in a telephone interview
from his Costa Rican home. ``All the key defendants have refused to
take depositions, walked out on depositions, refused to turn over
documents, and he's refused to take sanctions against them.''
   King ruled the plaintiffs failed to prove their basic contention
that a wide-ranging conspiracy was behind the news conference
bombing in Nicaragua that injured Avirgan. Eight people were killed
but the apparent target, Contra leader Eden Pastora, was only
wounded.
   The judge also ruled the plaintiffs failed to prove the
defendants were responsible for threats to news sources and the
journalists aimed at covering up the defendants' involvement.
   Singlaub, who said he spent $250,000 on his defense, and
Shackley promised retaliatory legal action against the Christic
Institute.
   Singlaub and Calero said the motive for the suit was to attack
the administration and Vice President George Bush before the
November election and to punish those who helped the Contras.
   The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the
Iran-Contra affair became public. Many of the people it brought to
light have been indicted or appeared before congressional
committees investigating that case.
   It alleged the defendants belonged to a right-wing terror
network dating back to 1959 that illegally participated in
assassination plots, gun running and drug trafficking.
   The suit accused the defendants of funding illegal Contra
activities with drug runs in cooperation with the Medellin Cartel
and threatening, imprisoning and even killing anyone who threatened
to uncover the ring.
   Other well-known defendants included cartel leaders Pablo
Escobar Gaviria and Jorge Ochoa Vasquez, Iran-Contra figure Robert
Owen, Costa Rican rancher John Hull and former mercenary Sam Hall.
Hall had been ordered jailed during the trial after refusing to
answer questions in a deposition but apparently will not have to
serve the sentence.
</TEXT>
