<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-RainDance     06-24 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Rain Dance,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Heat Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Florist Happy with Indian Medicine Man's Drought Remedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLYDE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local florist who paid $2,000 to bring a
Sioux Indian medicine man to dance and pray for rain in the
drought-stricken Midwest says the showers were brief, but the money
was well spent.
   Cliff Doebel said Thursday he was pleased with the attention
Leonard Crow Dog's ceremony drew to the drought and its effect on
the state's agriculture economy.
   ``People around the world need to know that this year we may not
be able to supply the grain we usually supply,'' he said.
   Crow Dog used an eagle bone whistle and a peace pipe at the
30-minute ceremony Sunday, when he guaranteed that the
drought-stricken northwest Ohio town would receive rain by Thursday.
   The medicine man, who said the ritual always brings rain, blew
the whistle toward the north, south, east and west, and then toward
the sky and ground.
   The showers arrived ahead of schedule Wednesday night as a cold
front moved through the state. The National Weather Service does
not have an official rainfall monitor in Clyde, but precipitation
in nearby communities ranged from .22 inches in Fremont to .08
inches in Milan, forecaster Matthew Peroutka said.
   ``It's not enough, and the situation is still here and still
severe, but I think it was enough to help some of the corn out,''
Doebel said.
   Doebel said he wasn't sure whether to credit Crow Dog or just
luck.
   ``I'm not one to know those answers,'' he said. ``All I know is
you flip a coin and sometimes it comes up heads.''
</TEXT>
