<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-24 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed sharply higher in trading against
the Japanese yen on Friday, and stock prices rallied slightly.
   The dollar closed the week at 129.70 yen, the day's high, up
1.15 yen from Thursday's finish. It opened trading at 128.63 yen
and ranged between 128.50-129.70 yen during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 127.85-point loser Thursday, gained back a
modest 17.46 points, or 0.06 percent, to finish the week at
27,750.39.
   The dollar was higher in response to Japanese news reports that
the United States would tolerate its rise through the 130 yen
level, traders said.
   The report quoted an anonymous U.S. Treasury source as saying
the dollar's strength against the yen since the beginning of this
week was within the range the United States could accept.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said the
market was ``becoming nervous'' following wild fluctuations in
trading Thursday, when the dollar ranged between 129.80 yen _ a
nearly four-month high _ and 128.25 yen.
   The Bank of Tokyo dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the dollar's further moves would depend on activity by
Japanese institutional investors.
   ``The firmness of Japanese government bond prices and stabilized
foreign exchange dealings helped the stock market,'' said Masahiro
Umemori of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   He also said market participants were confident that inflation
in Japan was not heating up.
   Traders also said losses over four consecutive trading days made
share prices attractive to investors.
</TEXT>
