<DOCNO> AP880624-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-HealthWorkers     06-24 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Health Workers,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Updates Precautions For Health Care Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials say they believe health care
workers are heeding a set of recommended precautions designed to
protect them from potentially dangerous viruses, including the one
that causes AIDS.
   The recommendations dealing with patients' body fluids were
published last August and, in response to numerous questions from
health care workers across the country, clarified and updated in a
report issued Thursday by the Centers for Disease Control.
   Officials at the Atlanta-based CDC said the questions and other
signs indicate that people are paying attention to the
recommendations.
   ``We have not done any formal study. However, from what we hear,
health care workers are being more careful,'' said Julia S. Garner,
the CDC's chief of prevention activity.
   Use of protective gloves by health care workers, the main
emphasis of the CDC report, has increased to the point where there
is a shortage of the gloves, officials said.
   Ms. Garner said it was not clear how much can be attributed to
the government's recommendations and how much is simply the result
of generally heightened awareness of the AIDS epidemic.
   In addition, more care apparently is being taken in the disposal
of needles and other sharp objects, which Ms. Garner said is a
serious threat to transmit human immunodeficiency virus _ the virus
that causes AIDS _ and hepatitis B virus.
   The CDC recommends that needles, scalpels and other sharper
objects that come in contact with blood and other potentially
dangerous body fluids be disposed of in puncture-resistant
containers.
   ``Four years ago it was not unusual to see used needles in
cardboard boxes used to store supplies,'' Ms. Garner said.
   The 1987 report was updated to be more specific about what types
of fluids health care workers must protect themselves from and to
apply the precautions to hepatitis B as well as HIV, Ms. Garner
said. Officials also wanted to quell rumors that a certain type of
medical glove was inadequate.
   Gloves should be used whenever an individual might come in
contact with a patient's blood, the updated report said. Other
``universal precautions,'' such as gowns, masks and protective
eyewear, also are advised.
   Blood is ``the single most important'' source of HIV, hepatitis
B and other disease-causing micro-organisms and viruses, the CDC
said.
   Universal precautions also apply to tissues, semen, vaginal
secretions, cerebrospinal fluid, synovial fluid, pleural fluid,
peritoneal fluid, pericardial fluid and amniotic fluid, the CDC
said.
   Feces, nasal secretions, sputum, sweat, tears, urine, and
vomitus do not require universal precautions, the CDC said, unless
they contain visible blood.
   Breast milk, though it has been implicated in the prenatal
transmission of HIV and hepatitis B virus, does not require the
high degree of precaution for health care workers, the CDC said.
However, those who have frequent exposure to breast milk should
consider wearing gloves.
   Gloves are not needed when feeding patients or wiping saliva
from skin, the CDC said, though gloves and handwashing are
recommended for such practices as digital examination of mucous
membranes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
