<HEAD>Cuomo Expects No Quick Decision on Dukakis VP Choice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo says he doesn't
think likely Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis is
going to make a quick decision on his vice presidential running
mate.
   Cuomo Thursday said he came to that conclusion after a long
discussion with Paul Brountas, who's leading the effort to find a
suitable running mate for Dukakis, about the vice presidential
selection process and came away with the impression that it would
take awhile.
   ``They do not seem to me the kind of people who would make
precipitous judgments or very early judgments,'' said Cuomo. ``I
don't expect a quick decision.''
   Meanwhile, a political adviser to both Cuomo and Dukakis said
the New York governor had agreed to stump the nation in support of
the Massachusetts governor's Democratic presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Missourinet Poll Says Dukakis Leads Bush in Missouri</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis has the
early lead over Republican Vice President George Bush in the
presidential race in Missouri, according to the results of a recent
Missouri poll.
   According to the Missourinet poll, released Thursday, 47 percent
of the Missourians surveyed favored Dukakis and 37 percent
supported Bush.
   When asked how they would vote if Dukakis selected Jesse Jackson
as a running mate, 43 percent said they would back Bush and
whomever he selected for a running mate while 36 percent said they
would back the Democratic ticket.
   The survey consisted of 413 random telephone interviews
conducted between June 13-16 with Missourians over the age of 18
who are also registered to vote. The poll has a sampling error of
plus or minus 4 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dispute Over Jackson Delegates Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana Democrats have revised a compromise
in a dispute between two Lake County politicians who each claim the
right to represent Jesse Jackson at the national Democratic
convention next month in Atlanta.
   State Democratic Chairman John Livengood said Thursday both
former Gary Mayor Richard G. Hatcher, who is vice chairman of
Jackson's national campaign, and current Gary Mayor Thomas V.
Barnes will attend the convention as Jackson delegates.
   Under the new settlement Carlos Toliver, who had been teamed
with Hatcher and Barnes' partner, Rudolph Clay, a Lake County
commissioner would also go to Atlanta.
   Under the latest plan, all four will attend the convention and
the votes of four other Indiana delegates backing Jackson will be
cut in half to make room.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Says Jackson's Challenge To Iowa's Caucuses Will Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Tom Harkin is defending Iowa's
precinct caucuses as a showcase for candidates with small
bankrolls, such as Jesse Jackson, and predicts Jackson's challenge
to Iowa's prominence in presidential politics would fail.
   ``I don't know what Jesse Jackson's so sore about. He did pretty
well in Iowa; without money he did pretty well,'' Harkin said
Thursday in a telephone news conference. ``If Jesse Jackson wants
to replace Iowa with the regional-type primaries he's been talking
about then when another Jesse Jackson comes along he wouldn't have
a prayer.''
   Jackson has proposed reducing the emphasis of Iowa on the
presidential selection process and giving more heavily populated
states an earlier say.
</TEXT>
