<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-24 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges, Stocks Creep Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged today to close the week at its
highest level in about four months against the Japanese yen, while
stock prices inched up after declining for five consecutive trading
days.
   After opening the day at 128.63, the dollar continued to climb
and closed at 129.70 yen, the day's high, up a sharp 1.15 yen from
Thursday's finish. It was the currency's highest level since late
February.
   ``Institutional investors and interbanks bought substantial
amounts of dollars in the late afternoon,'' said a foreign exchange
dealer with the Bank of Tokyo who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said there was no obvious reason behind their moves.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
127.85 points Thursday, won back 17.46 points, or 0.06 percent, on
Friday. It closed at 27,750.39.
   ``The market was led mainly by large-capital issues on their
favorable prospects,'' said a stock analyst with a major commercial
securities house, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Traders said the market continued to reflect concerns about
interest rates and inflation. Issues such as blue chip electricals
that should benefit from the stronger dollar have not been able to
sustain gains over the past few sessions.
   The Nikkei index lost a total of 609.53 points during the week.
   Volume of the first section trade was estimated at 1.6 billion
shares, up from 1 billion shares Thursday.
   Among the gainers were steels and non-ferrous metals. Losers
include marine transportations, shipbuildings, and machineries.
</TEXT>
