<DOCNO> AP880624-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cambodia     06-24 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Will Negotiate With Vietnam, But Doubts Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk said today he will take part in peace talks with
Vietnamese officials next month but expressed doubt about Hanoi's
planned withdrawal of troops from Cambodia.
   ``I'm in favor of dialogue. I am not Mr. Nyet. I am Mr. Da. I'm
not going to say no to anybody,'' Sihanouk said at Beijing's
airport.
   He left today for Bangkok to attend a meeting of the foreign
ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), a
principal backer of the three-party anti-Vietnam coalition that
Sihanouk heads. He is also likely to meet Secretary of State George
Shultz, who will be in Bangkok for the conference.
   Sihanouk said he will ``say always `yes' to all proposals'' that
would lead to a settlement of the Cambodian conflict and called
plans for informal peace talks to be held next month in Jakarta a
``good thing.''
   Vietnam has said it will also attend the ``cocktail party''
talks in Jakarta.
   ``I am interested in solving the problem of Kampuchea so with or
without the Vietnamese in Jakarta I'm going to attend,'' he said.
``The composition of the participants has no importance.''
   The ``cocktail party'' would bring together for the first time
the rival factions of the three-party resistance, representatives
from Vietnam and from the Hanoi-installed Cambodian government.
   Sihanouk also said he was willing to meet with Cambodian Prime
Minister Hun Sen. He broke off talks with Hun Sen in Paris earlier
this year, accusing him of being a puppet of the Vietnamese.
   ``I will talk to the Vietnamese, to Hun Sen, to everybody,''
Sihanouk said. ``The most important thing is to start the process
of examining the problem and trying to exchange views and having
discussion.''
   The resistance coalition, made up of Sihanouk, the Communist
Khmer Rouge and the non-Communist forces of Son Sann, is calling
for the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops that have occupied Cambodia
since late 1978. The group also wants the formation of a four-party
government that would include Hun Sen.
   Vietnam has said that it will pull out 50,000 troops this year
and the remainder of its estimated force of 120,000 by 1990, but
Sihanouk said he feared the troops would only be rotated.
   ``I don't believe it is true,'' he said. ``That must be rather a
rotation of troops rather than a genuine withdrawal. The Vietnamese
cannot afford to withdraw ... because the Hun Sen regime would
collapse.''
   Vietnam's pullout, which is to begin this month, has renewed
concern about the return of the Communist Khmer Rouge, which killed
a million or more people before being ousted by Hanoi.
   Sihanouk denied Western news reports that China had offered to
give asylum to Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot in an attempt to help
solve the Cambodian conflict.
   China on Thursday called the reports ``highly irresponsible''
and ``absolutely groundless.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Protests     06-24 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Protests,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opponents of Burma's Regime Fight Great Odds</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 26 years of Buddhist passivity
and private grumbling, opponents of Burma's authoritarian regime
are taking to the streets in violent protest.
   Since October, students have mobilized demonstrations three
times, causing deaths, mass arrests and long university closures.
Nine people were killed this week in the latest, ongoing street
confrontations in Rangoon, the Burmese capital, officials said.
   The students are demanding release of detainees and legalization
of their unions.
   However, Western diplomats in Rangoon and knowledgeable Burmese
observers say the outbursts reflect deep-rooted disillusionment
with a regime that has monopolized power for a quarter century.
During that time, it has led the resource-rich Southeast Asian
nation to economic ruin and isolation.
   In an unprecedented admission of failure, strongman U Ne Win
last year called on the state to ``pinpoint the disease'' and
lifted controls on the vital rice trade. There was also talk of
constitutional change but little to indicate Ne Win's party would
throw out the basic tenants of his rule: rigid socialist economics,
isolationism and single-party control backed by the powerful
military.
   ``No real reform has yet been made, although there has been some
small-scale tinkering with the economy,'' wrote a leading American
Burma scholar, Josef Silverstein, recently. ``The economy's
downward spiral remains unchecked.
   Despite the unprecedented surge of opposition, there have been
no predictions so far that anything but old age or ill health will
topple the 78-year-old leader.
   While ordinary citizens have joined students in some
demonstrations, there has been no sign of a meaningful and
organized opposition to Ne Win among the military, bureaucracy or
influential Buddhist monkhood.
   The activist students themselves have shown little evidence of
planning and coordination, although the Rangoon-centered protests
have been touching off minor disturbances elsewhere in the country.
   Ne Win, who came to power in a 1962 military coup, has in the
past systematically rooted out opponents and dealt harshly with the
few open protests he faced. Rarely seen in public and never
interviewed by the press, Ne Win is said to be a superb and highly
intelligent political infighter and a strong nationalist.
   But beyond a neutralist foreign policy that has paid dividends,
his overall record as national leader is badly marred.
   ``He has lost whatever lingering support he may have had. People
now realize the government has never had their interests in mind,''
said one Western diplomat in Rangoon last year. He made the comment
after the government took about 60 percent of the kyat currency out
of circulation without explanation or compensation.
   Burmese in the streets talked of ``official robbery.'' Angry
students spilled out of their campuses in the first rioting since
1974.
   Analysts regarded the reaction to the demonetization as a
watershed event.
   It coincided with a nosedive of the already weak economy that
continues even now.
   Once the world's largest rice exporter and an oil producer,
Burma has suffered spot food shortages and has had to import
petroleum products. Regarded as potentially the richest nations in
Southeast Asia because of its vast natural resources, Burma _ with
a per capita annual income of less than $200 _ ranks among the
world's ten poorest nations.
   Although the state officially controls much of the economy, a
black market actually accounts for two-thirds or more of the
transactions. The government must spend a third of its budget on
fighting a welter of ethnic minorities seeking autonomy and another
big chunk on servicing a foreign debt of about $3.5 billion dollars.
   Observers have long said that one lid on protest in Burma was
its fertile soil and a low population _ currently about 38 million.
   Another widely accepted theory was that Burma's deeply rooted
Buddhism fostered an acceptance of suffering as one's ''karma,'' or
fate, and deference to authority figures.
   A final factor may be Burma's state-imposed isolation from much
of the world. With few real friends and no real enemies, outside
pressures for change have been minimal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   AP correspondent Denis D.Gray has made nine
trips to Burma over the past decade from Bangkok, the key
Burma-watching post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India)Politics     06-24 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India)Politics,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Minister Resigns After By-Election Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief minister of India's most
populous state resigned today, eight days after Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi's ruling Congress Party lost a critical election to a
rising Gandhi opponent.
   Chief Minister Bir Bahadur Singh, the highest-ranking elected
official in Uttar Pradesh, tendered his resignation after a meeting
Thursday night with Gandhi, the United News of India reported.
   A second resignation was expected today from the chief minister
of western Maharashtra state, UNI said.
   The minister there, S.B. Chavan, has been accused by party
members of failing to deal with rising opposition groups, including
Shiv Sena, which was set up to protect Hindu rights. Shiv Sena has
won control of the government in the state capital at Bombay.
   Congress Party committees were scheduled to meet in both states
late today to select successors.
   Both moves were intended to strength the Congress Party hold on
the populous states in advance of national elections, which must be
held before January 1990.
   Uttar Pradesh has more than 120 million people. Maharashtra has
nearly 70 million. India's total population is about 800 million.
   The Congress Party suffered a major setback in Uttar Pradesh in
elections June 16.
   Former Defense Minister V.P. Singh, an independent running with
the backing of major opposition parties, defeated the Congress
Party candidate by a 2-to-1 margin.
   V.P. Singh resigned from Gandhi's Cabinet last year after
revealing that he was launching investigations into possible
kickbacks on Indian defense contracts.
   Indian newspapers and opposition parties have alleged that some
of the funds may have gone to Gandhi supporters. Gandhi and his
party leaders have denied any wrongdoing.
   Gandhi's Congress Party won a landslide victory in national
elections in 1984, largely on a sympathy vote after the prime
minister's mother and predecessor, Indira Gandhi, was assassinated.
   Since then, his party has lost 10 of 14 state elections.
   In the latest by-election, Congress won only two seats of the
seven being contested, while the opposition won three. Results have
not yet been announced in two districts because of allegations of
vote rigging.
   The Congress Party had held all seven seats going into the
election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
