<HEAD>Boy Sacrificed In Quest For Treasure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasure hunters killed a 4-year-old boy
in central India because they believed that by sacrificing the
child they would find hidden loot, the United News of India
reported today.
   The news agency said the boy disappeared from his home last
Saturday in the village of Panchampur Sarseni.
   The village is near the town of Gwalior, 210 miles north of the
Madhya Pradesh state capital at Bhopal.
   UNI quoted police as saying the boy was lured by a neighbor to a
hidden site where a treasure was believed buried. He was killed at
the site, but no treasure was found.
   The boy's body was later found on the outskirts of the village,
the news agency said.
   Three villagers have been arrested in connection with the case,
UNI said.
   Human sacrifice is outlawed in India, but it sometimes occurs in
remote villages where superstitions run high.
</TEXT>
