<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PuertoRico-Bomb     06-24 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Puerto Rico-Bomb,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Charges Filed Against Miami Cuban Linked To Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYAGUEZ, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban resident of Miami has been
charged with first degree murder in connection with a bomb blast
that killed another Miami resident on the west coast of Puerto Rico.
   Antonio Alfredo Gonzalez Olmeda, 25, faces one count of murder
stemming from the death of Jeff Parker, 33, who was killed when an
explosive device blew up while he was apparently assembling it
inside a car.
   Gonzalez Olmeda was charged Thursday.
   Gonzalez Olmeda, who was standing beside the car and received
face and upper body injuries, will be charged with murder under the
felony murder rule, according to assistant district attorney Eric
Velazquez. The rule applies when someone died in the commission of
a felony.
   He was also charged with damages and explosives law violations.
   Bail for Gonzalez Olmeda, who was still hospitalized, was set in
absentia at $790,000.
   Investigators did not disclose the target of the attack.
   The explosion took place about 1:40 a.m. Monday in the town of
Mayaguez, 100 miles from the capital San Juan.
   A briefcase found in the trunk of the car, which was rented,
contained a digital remote control detonator, officials said. It
also held airline tickets for a Monday afternoon flight to Miami,
and an Immigration and Naturalization Service card and driver's
licence, both in Gonzalez Olmeda's name.
</TEXT>
