<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailhouseLawyer     06-24 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailhouse Lawyer,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Inmate Didn't Die; Has To Serve Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jailhouse lawyer tried to prove that he
``died'' on the operating table during open-heart surgery and
therefore completed his life sentence for murder, but a
disbelieving judge ordered him back to prison.
   ``Law is interesting,'' Cayuga County Judge Peter Corning said,
trying to suppress a smile after hearing convict Jerry Rosenberg's
argument Thursday.
   Corning ruled that Rosenberg, 49, did not meet the Court of
Appeals' 1984 definition of death: a lack of brain activity or an
irreversible halt in heart and lung activity.
   ``As his presence in this courtroom indicates ... he did not
die,'' Corning said.
   Rosenberg, who has earned several law degrees from
correspondence schools during his 25 years in prison, said before
the ruling that he planned to appeal if he lost. After the
decision, guards from Auburn Correctional Facility escorted him
from the courtroom.
   Rosenberg contended that he died when his heart stopped during
the 1986 bypass operation. Doctors restarted his heart.
   He tried to convince Corning that the definition of death was
ambiguous and that there were two kinds of death, reversible and
irreversible.
   ``The higher courts, the Supreme Court has never defined death.
They've defined life,'' Rosenberg said before a crowded courtroom.
``Reversible death, which is a medical term, means they bring you
back from death to life, not life to life.''
   However, Assistant Attorney General Ken Goldman presented
affidavits countering Rosenberg's claim from three doctors,
including Dr. Leslie Kohman, who operated on the convict.
   Having a patient's heart stop during a bypass operation does not
``represent an untoward occurence,'' Kohman wrote.
   Corning asked Rosenberg if he believed that everyone whose heart
stopped during heart surgery should be considered legally dead.
Rosenberg said yes.
   The judge said that under Rosenberg's theory, everyone who has
heart surgery could collect on his or her life insurance policy, be
declared divorced and have estates probated.
   ``Yes, yes,'' said Rosenberg. ``I know this is far-reaching and
I'm opening up a can of ... not worms, but boa constrictors.''
   Rosenberg was convicted in 1963 of murder in the killing of two
police officers in New York City, and was sentenced to death, but
managed to find a legal loophole and have his sentence commuted to
life.
   While in prison, he has filed lawsuits ranging from a successful
appeal for a Mafia kingpin to a child custody request for a fellow
convict.
   Rosenberg has another lawsuit pending in federal court in
Syracuse in which he claims he's being denied proper medical
treatment and access to the media.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drought-Forecast 1stLd-Writethru a0467 06-24 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Forecast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather Service Sees No Short-Term Relief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to restore dropped word</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new National Weather Service forecast for
the Colorado Rockies eastward through the Central Plains, the lower
Midwest and the Middle Atlantic states is for more of the same hot,
dry weather for the rest of June.
   In its first ``drought advisory'' of the year, the service on
Thursday forecast below-normal rainfall from the Central Plains to
Illinois and Indiana, although surrounding areas may have closer to
normal precipitation.
   The Climate Analysis Center issues drought advisories when lack
of rain has continued over a large area for several weeks and the
forecast fails to indicate any upcoming rain.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng, meanwhile, told President
Reagan on Thursday that it is too early for emergency relief
measures to deal with effects of the drought.
   ``Despite the serious potential effects of the drought, the
secretary said rainfall in the next two weeks would alleviate much
of the potential damage,'' Deputy White House Press Secretary B.
Jay Cooper said.
   Vice President George Bush, however, said in a separate
statement, ``If conditions continue to deteriorate, money that has
been saved in this year's farm programs will be redirected to farm
families as disaster relief for the rural economy.''
   The weather service noted in its advisory that the period from
April 1 to June 1 was among the driest since 1920 in the North
Central states, although not yet as dry as in 1934.
   The center also expressed concern about conditions in the
Southeast, where a dry spell has prevailed for nearly four years,
and in the Mississippi-Missouri watershed.
   Since April 1, less than 50 percent of normal precipitation has
occurred in an area stretching from the states on the Gulf of
Mexico to the northern border.
   Drought conditions have been gradually worsening over the
northern Great Plains and Rockies, the Tennessee and Ohio valleys,
the southern Appalachians, California, the interior Pacific
Northwest and northern Maine, the statement noted.
   The Climate Analysis Center regularly issues 30- and 90-day
national forecasts but rarely issues special statements such as the
drought advisory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
