<DOCNO> AP880624-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-China     06-24 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-China,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Turks Demand More Say In Kuomintang Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty liberal lawmakers from the governing
Nationalist Party proposed today that Taiwan improve its almost
non-existent relations with Communist China.
   The legislators, who were elected delegates to upcoming party
congress in July, issued a statement urging the Nationalist Party
to map out a ``positive and forward-looking'' policy toward China.
   It said the Nationalist Party, or Kuomintang, should ``adopt an
open and realistic attitude to promote more exchanges and
contacts'' with China.
   The Nationalists have refused all official contact with the
rival Communist government in Beijing since 1949, when they fled to
Taiwan after losing a civil war on the Chinese mainland. Both
governments claim to be the rightful ruler of both Taiwan and the
Chinese mainland.
   Last year, the Nationalists lifted a ban on travel to China to
allow family reunions. The party's policy-making Central Standing
Committee proposed last week to allow mainland Chinese studying
overseas to visit Taiwan but ruled out cultural and athletic
exchanges with China.
   The legislators demanded that the party allow the 1,200 party
delegates to decide on a new policy toward China rather than
``rubber-stamping'' a resolution made by the Central Standing
Committee.
   The statement urged the government to also allow sightseeing,
cultural and athletic exchanges.
   ``We should open up gradually,'' the statement said. ``The next
phase of development should depend on how the Chinese Communists
respond'' to Taiwan's relaxation of its policy.
   The Nationalist government wants China to promise that it won't
use force to unite the two and stop isolating the island
diplomatically.
   Taiwan maintains diplomatic relations with 22 countries and has
withdrawn from most international organizations because of China's
objection.
   In a related development, Taiwan announced today that it had
rejected a request by a state-run research group to attend an
international science meeting in Beijing.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Chen Yu-chu told a press conference
that the Cabinet would not allow Academia Sinica of Taiwan to send
a delegation to the 22nd annual meeting of the International
Council of Scientific Unions in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
