<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0545EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-PrisonProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0429 06-24 0897</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Prison Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Discounts Any Suggestion Of Impropriety In Prison Site
Selection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 13th graf bgng ``Dukakis said ...'' to
include New Braintree selectwoman's claim that Dukakis was told who
owned land at proposed prison site; picks up pvs 14th graf bgng
``Jacobson and Striar...''; edits throughout for transition</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis says any suggestion that his
administration acted improperly in selecting a prison site in a
small Massachusetts town is ``unfortunate and regrettable.''
   And Dukakis administration officials are questioning whether
political motivations lay behind the revelation that the FBI is
looking into the selection process. In publicly acknowledging the
probe, the FBI broke its usual policy of neither confirming nor
denying the existence of investigations.
   A bureau spokesman in Washington, Bill Carter, said Thursday the
reason for the exception was that this case could appear to
implicate a presidential candidate. Dukakis is all but assured the
Democratic presidential nomination.
   The bureau released a statement saying Dukakis was not the
subject of the probe. But spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer added that the
inquiry has yet to reach the stage where any individual would be
identified as a subject of investigation.
   Bureau spokesmen declined to say whether any information
implicating Dukakis had been discovered. Dukakis said no
administration official has been contacted or subpoenaed by the FBI.
   Some residents of the town of New Braintree have accused Dukakis
of cronyism in his support for purchasing land there for the
prison. The governor told reporters Thursday that his
administration had been ``as open as it could possibly be'' about
the prison controversy.
   ``Any suggestions that the secretary of human services and his
staff proceeded other than in accordance with the law and strict
standards of integrity are unfortunate and regrettable,'' Dukakis
told reporters.
   Dukakis administration officials on Thursday questioned whether
the Reagan administration might have engineered publicity over the
probe, the first report of which appeared Thursday in The
Washington Times.
   ``I think it's very curious,'' said John DeVillars, a top
Dukakis aide, adding: ``I would certainly be interested in what
U.S. Attorney (Frank) McNamara has to say.''
   McNamara, a former Republican candidate for Congress, is a
Reagan appointee. He declined comment on the probe on Thursday.
   Those who accuse the Dukakis administration of tailoring a deal
on the prison site point to the fact that the co-owners of the
782-acre property are longtime acquaintances of the governor and
one co-owner has contributed to Dukakis' presidential campaign.
   A Norwood, Mass., development firm owned by Daniel Striar and
Gary Jacobson purchased the land from the Seventh-day Adventist
Church in December 1985 for $3 million. Jacobson was a boyhood
neighbor of Dukakis.
   Dukakis said he was unaware who owned the land at the time he
approved it as a prison site.
   But The Boston Globe reported in today's editions that
Selectwoman Dorothea Thomas-Vitrac, a member the governing board of
New Braintree, said Dukakis was told the names of the people who
owned the land at a meeting with town residents in the governor's
office May 6, 1986.
   Jacobson and Striar purchased the land a month after the state
listed the land as a possible prison site. A later state-funded
appraisal of the property in 1986 valued the land at $8.7 million.
   That appraisal led critics of the plan to complain that the site
owners were going to make millions. Dukakis said Thursday that the
state would release its final appraisal of the land in the next 10
days, and hinted it would be considerably less than $8.7 million.
   In February 1987, Jacobson and Striar offered to sell the land
to the state for $9.5 million, more than three times the purchase
price.
   Jacobson has been a contributor to Dukakis' political campaigns.
He and his wife each contributed $1,000 to Dukakis' presidential
campaign this year, the maximum allowed by law.
   A secretary said Jacobson, a physician, was seeing patients and
was unable to return a reporter's phone call. Striar is on vacation
and could not be reached.
   New Braintree has a population of 800. The $22 million prison
would hold 500 inmates.
   Dukakis has been dogged by opponents of the prison plan while
campaigning for the Democratic nomination. Residents have held
protests and lobbied lawmakers against the prison proposal.
   Thomas-Vitrac, one the strongest opponents to the prison, said
she has been questioned at least twice by FBI agents beginning last
March. The selectmen have been independently seeking a probe, first
with the state attorney general and, last March, with the U.S.
attorney.
   Thomas-Vitrac said she has turned over to the FBI a box of
documents relating to the case. She has received through requests
under the Freedom of Information Act documents relating to the
prison site.
   But the Dukakis administration has refused to release two
documents she wants. One is an October 1986 memo to Dukakis' chief
legal counsel Stephen Rosenfeld from an aide the day before the
Adventists announced that Striar and Jacobson were potential buyers
of the property. Another, dated Dec. 2, 1985, were sent from
Rosenfeld to Dukakis the day before the actual sale of the property.
   An index of documents released by the administration indicated
the author, recipient and subject of the memos.
   ``There are some documents in this administration we don't
release publicly on grounds of executive privilege,'' Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
