<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Students     06-24 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Students,0055</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Protesters Leave Holy Temple, Guards Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Burma-Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student protesters abandoned Burma's
holiest Buddhist shrine, its trustees said, but authorities kept
guard around the reopened complex and other major temples in the
capital today.
   The heightened security culminated a week of tension and
student-led rioting. Officials said nine people died in street
violence, and the government has imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew,
closed institutions of higher learning and prohibited all public
meetings.
   Buddhist pilgrims reported Thursday that students had moved into
the sprawling hilltop Shwedagon Pagoda, a centuries-old marvel of
golden spires and stupas, to set up a ``strike center'' that would
coordinate anti-government protests.
   However, pilgrims who entered the pagoda after it was reopened
today said they found no trace of student demonstrators.
   Pagoda trustees who spoke on condition of anonymity said
university students arrived in groups at the shrine on Wednesday
afternoon and probably mingled with worshippers before the 6:00
p.m. government curfew.
   The students were also said to have left later that day, though
it was not clear whether they too were observing the curfew or
departed for some other reason.
   The trustees said security officials searched the temple grounds
Wednesday night and barred public access Thursday.
   The week's protests have also caused classes to be suspended at
schools in Mandalay, the country's second largest city.
Anti-government protests have also been reported in Pegu, north of
Rangoon, and in Moulmein, on the southeastern seacoast.
   Since October, the 26-year-old regime of strongman U Ne Win has
been rocked by three violent protests in Rangoon and smaller ones
in other parts of the country.
   Diplomatic and other sources says lack of personal freedoms and
a downward spiraling economy are fueling unrest.
   Buddhist pagodas in Burma have traditionally been centers of
political protest. In 1920, Rangoon students moved into the
Shwedagon grounds to launch agitation against the British, who were
then the colonial rulers in Burma.
   The posting of guards at Sule, Botataung and other shrines today
was viewed as a measure to prevent activists from entering the
Buddhist holy places, where violence of any kind is forbidden.
   Traffic increased in Rangoon today and all markets were open,
although fewer shoppers were seen.
   Last week, students at several institutions had peacefully
demonstrated for release of detained students and legalization of
student unions. Violence broke out after the government responded
by closing the schools.
   On Tuesday, about 5,000 students and other protesters fought
police with stones.
   Last March, police and military units brutally suppressed a
similar demonstration, arresting hundreds and killing what Western
diplomats put at possibly up to 100 protesters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
