<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Iran     06-24 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Iran,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Says No Hostage Deals With Iran, Newspaper Predicts
Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Secetary Sir Geoffrey Howe denounced any
bargain for release of British hostages in Lebanon, while a Middle
Eastern newspaper said it had obtained reports that those captives
would soon be freed.
   Howe spoke Thursday amid rising hopes that a recent series of
contacts between Britain and Iran could lead to the early return of
a British diplomat to Tehran and negotiations for the British
hostages.
   But he told the Association of American Correspondents that this
week's private visit of four British lawmakers to Tehran had not
changed Britain's policicies toward Iran or the hostages.
   The Parliamentary delegation, the first to visit Iran since the
1979 revolution, said Wednesday that Iran had agreed to use its
influence to try to obtain the release of the British hostages. The
delegation urged Britain to post a diplomat to Tehran.
   Meanwhile, the Al-Khaleej newspaper in Sharjah, United Arab
Emirates, reported Thursday that Church of England envoy Terry
Waite and some other hostages held in Lebanon have been taken to
Iran, where they will be freed soon.
   The publication, which is usually reliable, quoted ``informed
Lebanese sources'' in its front-page report, which said the other
hostages involved ``are believed to be British too.''
   The daily said Waite and the other hostages were moved from
their kidnappers' hideouts in the Shiite Moslem-dominated slums of
south Beirut by Iranian Revolutionary Guards last month.
   The Guards had been fighting alongside guerrillas of the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, against the Syrian-backed
Shiite Amal militia.
   They left south Beirut under the cease-fire brokered by Syria
and Iran that ended three weeks of fierce fighting, al-Khaleej
reported.
   It said the Guards took Waite and the other captives first to
the Syrian capital of Damascus and then to Tehran.
   It was not clear whether the Syrians were aware the hostages
were being moved.
   The daily said the captives ``are expected to be released within
the coming few days.''
   However, other reports have said the hostages are held in a
Hezbollah barracks ringed by Syrian troops in south Beirut.
   Mohammad Akhoond Zadeh Basti, Iran's charge d'affaires in
London, said Wednesday night he was ``very optimistic'' that the
improvement in diplomatic relations could lead to the release of
Waite, journalist John McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan.
   But Howe said Britain's relations with Iran remained ``at a very
low ebb'' because of ``the shameful way'' in which British diplomat
Edward Chaplin was abducted and beaten by Iranian agents in Tehran
May 28, 1987. Britain reduced its ties with Iran to a caretaker
status following the incident and ordered its diplomats home.
   The foreign secretary stressed that the Parliamentary mission
was organized by Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie of the
Church of England _ not the government.
   Waite, McCarthy and Keenan are among 18 foreign hostages held in
Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was abducted March 16,
1985.
   France and Iran named ambassadors to each other's countries
Thursday, one week after restoring diplomatic relations. The
appointments were linked to the return of the last three French
hostages from Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
