<HEAD>Cool Air Brings Relief to Northeast; Heat Continues Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cool Canadian air settled over the Northeast early today, but a
heat wave that gripped much of the nation showed no sign of easing.
   On Thursday, 26 cities recorded record high temperatures for the
date, while another nine tied record highs. Tucson, Ariz., had the
nation's high with 113 degrees.
   Early today, temperatures were mostly in the 40s and 50s from
Pennsylvania and New York through New England. Readings in the 50s
also were common over northeast Minnesota, Michigan and eastern
Ohio.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over eastern Montana,
the southern San Joaquin Valley in California, northeast Arizona,
New Mexico and southeast Colorado, where nearly an inch of rain
fell Thursday night and flooded some streets in Colorado Springs.
   A few showers and thunderstorms lingered over southeast
Minnesota, eastern Iowa, southern Wisconsin, southeast Virginia and
northern North Carolina, where winds gusted to 47 mph Thursday
night at Durham.
   Heavier rainfall during the six-hour period ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included a half-inch at Knob Noster, Mo.; nearly a half-inch at
Mason City, Iowa; and about a quarter-inch at Norfolk Naval Air
Station, Va., and Evansville, Ind.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Massena and Watertown, N.Y., Bradford, Pa., and
Limestone, Maine, to 99 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over the upper Mississippi Valley and upper Michigan; scattered
thunderstorms from southern Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast;
and scattered thunderstorms over the southern and central Plateau
region and the southern Rockies in the afternoon.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the upper 80s or 90s
across much of the nation. Highs were forecast for the 60s and 70s
along the Pacific Coast and in New England; the 70s from the Great
Lakes to the middle Atlantic Coast; 100 to 105 degrees over the
central Plains and Arkansas, as well as parts of California,
southern Oregon, southwest Idaho and western Colorado; and 100 to
115 degrees across the desert Southwest.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 hazy; Boston 58 fair; Buffalo 50 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 79 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 67 fair; Cleveland 58
partly cloudy; Detroit 60 partly cloudy; Miami 80 partly cloudy;
New York 60 fair; Philadelphia 65 fair; Pittsburgh 57 fair;
Portland, Maine, 50 partly cloudy; Washington 69 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 80 fair; Chicago 67 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
78 fair; Denver 70 fair; Des Moines 78 cloudy; Indianapolis 69
fair; Kansas City 79 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 70 partly cloudy;
Nashville 80 hazy; New Orleans 76 cloudy; St. Louis 79 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 73 partly cloudy; Anchorage 50 rain; Las
Vegas 87 fair; Los Angeles 60 fair; Phoenix 96 fair; Salt Lake City
74 fair; San Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 57 partly cloudy;
Seattle 54 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 fair; Toronto 52 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
