<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-24 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILDWOOD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With knuckles down and backs to the wind,
two 12-year-olds became the king and queen of marbles in the 65th
annual National Marbles Tournament.
   Shannon Capasso of Pittsburgh and Dan Strohecker of Reading,
Pa., were crowned Thurday after winning the best of 15 matches in
the final round of competition on the beach in this vacation
community.
   Both credited their ability to maintain a ``spin'' on their
``shooter,'' the main marble used to send seven of 13 marbles
hurling out of a 10-foot ring. Squatting _ with knee pads _ on
concrete platforms in the steamy air, the final competitors in the
girls and boys categories nervously wiped their sweaty hands on
towels and blew on their shooter marble to cool it.
   They reached their spots after competing since Monday against 42
other contestants from 10 states, including Michigan, Iowa and
Georgia.
   Shannon and Dan each won a giant trophy, a plaque, a $2,000
college scholarship and a medal. Seated on wooden ``thrones'' set
on a beach platform, they rejected the tradition of kissing each
other, and instead smirked and shook hands.
   Last year, the future of the marbles tournament appeared
uncertain because a sponsor could not be found. This year, an Iowa
company that manufactures a marbles game, Creative Athletic
Products Inc., not only boosted the scholarships but helped pay
each contestant's room and board, said Eugene Mason, the
tournament's director.
   ``There's been a resurgence in marbles interest,'' Mason said.
``Kids have needed a new activity.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie ``Bull Durham'' apparently has
created new fans for the the Class A baseball team the film
depicts, and team officials say they hope it leads to increased
attendance as well.
   ``We were all over the papers, both locally and nationally,''
said Durham Bulls sales manager Kevin Maloney. ``Souvenir sales
have picked up and phone-in orders have picked up nationwide.
   ``I think we do foresee an upturn in that, a lot more people
purchasing pennants and T-shirts,'' he said.
   Maloney said the Bulls' office has taken souvenir orders from as
far away as Edmonton, Alberta; Yardley, Mass.; and New York City
since the movie opened last week. Bill Miller, the team's assistant
general manager, has done pregame radio shows for stations in
Chicago and San Francisco.
   The movie's effect on local theater audiences should be known
tonight when the Bulls return from a road trip for their first home
game since the film's release.
   ``We already lead the nation in A-ball attendance. Certainly,
our name is out in the open,'' Maloney said this week. ``They hear
Durham Bulls, they know who the Durham Bulls are. This could be the
opening of the floodgates.''
   The comedy-romance movie stars Kevin Costner, who plays a new
Bulls catcher, and Susan Sarandon.
</TEXT>
