<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gohd     06-24 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gohd,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Climb Continues, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar extended its recent gains in early
European trading today before running into a bout of profit-taking
and reported central-bank intervention. Gold bullion eased.
   Buoyed by a reversal in market sentiment, the dollar hit an
eight-month high of 1.7978 West German marks in Frankfurt early
today. Traders said the currency was likely to test the
psychologically important 1.8-mark during the day.
   The dollar also was trading at levels last seen in February
against the Japanese yen and the British pound and at its highest
levels since last year against some other European currencies.
   However, the dollar eased later in the morning as profit-takers
stepped in amid reports that Bundesbank, West Germany's central
bank, had bought dollars on the open market to keep the currency
from rising too fast.
   Here are some mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with
late Thursday:
   _1.7905 West German marks, up from 1.7855
   _1.4905 Swiss francs, up from 1.4800
   _6.0520 French francs, up from 6.0245
   _2.0258 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0145
   _1,331.50 Italian lire, up from 1,326.50
   _1.2030 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   The dollar rose against the British pound, which was quoted at
$1.7460, compared with Thursday's $1.7565.
   The dollar surged to a closing rate of 129.70 Japanese yen in
Tokyo, up from 128.55 yen. In London trading later today, it was
quoted at 129.68 yen.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price of
$447 a troy ounce at mid-morning, down from $448.75 late Thursday.
A dealer said the dollar's strength was putting pressure on
bullion, but trading volume was light.
   In Zurich, gold traded at a bid of $446.70, down from $448.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $448.55, down
from $449.78.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.92 a troy ounce,
down from $7.02.
</TEXT>
