<HEAD>Convoy of Supplies for Nicaragua Circles White House in Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convoy of 36 trucks and buses came to
Washington from Laredo, Texas and in an Old West style immediately
circled the object of its focus, the White House.
   The Veterans Peace Convoy came to Washington Thursday to protest
recent actions by the Reagan administration to block the group's
delivery of food, medicine and clothing to Nicaragua.
   ``We have come to take care of the children of Nicaragua,'' said
convoy organizer Gerry Condon of San Francisco. ``We intend to
lobby and gain support for this convoy to pass. We want to feed the
children, not the war.''
   But custom agents in Texas recently seized four vehicles and
barred the group from crossing into Mexico when they would not post
bond and sign an agreement that the aging school buses and pickup
trucks would be returned to the United States because the
administration contends that to let the vehicles remain in
Nicaragua would violate a trade embargo.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Says High-Level Officials Let Off Lightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York congressman says the Education
Department is allowing high-level officials to get away with abuses
for which it punishes low-level employees and program beneficiaries.
   Democratic congressman Ted Weiss, who chairs the House
subcommittee on Government Operations said Thursday ``High-ranking
officials have gotten off with slaps on the wrist, while low-level
employees and program participants have been disciplined or
prosec;uted to the full extent of the law.''
   ``Our preliminary review of these cases indicates that justice
is not blind when it comes to corruption at the Department of
Education,'' said Weiss at a committee hearing.
   Much of the discussion at the hearing focused on an incident
involving Madeleine Will, assitant secretary for special education
and estranged wife of nationally syndicated columnist George Will.
   Mrs. Will was allowed to make restitution when it was discovered
she had used a department car and driver for personal business,
claimed travel expenses that she never incurred and had authorized
payments to a special assistant after the assistant had been
terminated from her office.
