<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Debate Counting Illegal Aliens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers are debating whether following the
letter of the Constitution as it concerns the 1990 census may
result in a system that is unfair to citizens.
   ``This is a fairness issue,'' said Rep. Thomas J. Ridge, R-Pa.,
at a Census subcommittee hearing on Thursday.
   Ridge and others argued that illegal aliens should not be
included in the 1990 count because states will large numbers of
illegal aliens would benefit unfairly when their large population
totals give them extra seats in the House.
   ``Every census since the Constitution was adopted has counted
all residents of the states, including both legal and illegal
aliens,''said Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif.
   House and other political districts are redrawn every ten years
on the basis of the census and because there is a 435-seat limit in
the House, when one state gains a member another must lose one.
</TEXT>
