<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Wolfe     06-24 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Wolfe,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tom Wolfe: Courts Should Get More Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Wolfe, whose best-selling novel ``The
Bonfire of the Vanities'' focuses on the criminal-justice system,
says reporters are missing out on billions of stories by failing to
cover the courts.
   ``Despite the highly publicized cases that you're all aware of,
I submit that the courts in this country are grossly undercovered
by the press,'' Wolfe said Thursday in a speech to 800 members of
the Philadelphia Bar Association.
   Wolfe, a former reporter for The Washington Post and the New
York Herald Tribune, said that while researching the novel in New
York City he was alarmed to find reporters unwilling to sit in on
court cases.
   He said reporters would gather in a press room and wait for a
district attorney or a spokesperson to come to ``deliver or get
their story for them.''
   ``I would find that day after day, I was the only reporter in
any courtroom in Manhattan or in Bronx County,'' said Wolfe. ``I
think that is a terrible mistake on the part of the press.''
</TEXT>
