<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Newman     06-24 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Newman,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newman Case Ends In Mistrial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Paul Newman and delicatessen
owner Julius Gold both say they believe jurors were leaning in
their favor before Gold's lawsuit against Newman came to an abrupt
end with a mistrial.
   But several jurors said they weren't even close to a decision
and predicted that if the case hadn't ended in a mistrial Thursday
there would have been a hung jury.
   Gold, who owns a deli in nearby Westport, is seeking stock in
Newman's food company, Newman's Own Inc., claiming he helped
develop Newman's products and is partly responsible for their
success.
   ``We were nowhere near close to a verdict,'' said juror Janice
Mayeran.
   Mayeran and another juror, Timothy Morris, said there was a
possibility of a hung jury if the trial hadn't ended.
   Bridgeport Superior Court Judge Howard Zoarski declared the
mistrial after jurors sent a note saying they couldn't ignore
depositions that weren't admitted as evidence but were
inadvertently turned over to them Wednesday, the second day of
deliberations.
   Zoarski's ruling reversed one he made minutes earlier
instructing jurors to disregard copies of the depositions from Gold
and others involved in the case.
   The note delivered to the judge said, ``Some members do not feel
an unbiased opinion can be rendered in light of their reading of an
amount of the depositions.''
   Zoarski said he had no choice but to order a mistrial.
   Afterward, Newman, standing in the courthouse lobby, thanked
jurors for their efforts. The Westport resident called the mistrial
``a terrible, unfortunate circumstance,'' adding that ``I always
thought this case had no merit, and Mr. Gold did not have a case.''
   Newman said he was ready for another trial, and Gold vowed to
continue pursuing the lawsuit he filed five years ago.
   Attorneys for Newman indicated they would file a motion asking
the judge to decide the case in their favor. There was no immediate
indication from Zoarski as to how the case eventually would be
resolved.
   Several jurors disregarded the judge's instructions not to speak
to reporters.
   Jury foreman Joseph Grassi said a number of the jurors were
``extremely disappointed'' by the mistrial after spending more than
three weeks on the case.
   The panel, which had deliberated for eight hours over two days,
was sent home Wednesday after Grassi told the court that it had
received depositions from Gold and some of the defendants, and
wanted to see Newman's.
   Newman's attorney, W. Patrick Ryan, said Wednesday it appeared
the clerk who took the exhibits into the jury room also
inadvertently took the depositions.
   Gold alleged that an attorney for Newman promised him 8 percent
of the stock from Newman's Own Inc. Gold said he contributed 30
months of effort to the company.
   Newman's Own, whose products include spaghetti sauce, lemonade
and popcorn, has donated $15 million in profits to charity since
1982.
</TEXT>
