<HEAD>Zia Opens Mosque That Pakistan Claims as World's Largest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq knelt
with other worshipers today to open what Pakistan claims to be the
world's largest mosque.
   The building accommodates 10,000 people in its prayer hall and
an additional 200,000 on its surrounding lawns.
   It is named after the late King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, who
supplied the financing. The mosque bears a white vaulted dome
surrounded by four 285-foot minarets.
   Gen. Zia dissolved the National Assembly and fired his civilian
government on May 29, accusing them of foot-dragging in making
Islam the supreme law of the land. King Fahd of Saudi Arabia had
been expected to open the mosque, but political observers
speculated that the ceremony may have been moved up as part of
Zia's Islamisation program.
