<1ST_LINE>r a PM-911Delay     06-24 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-911 Delay,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Dispatcher Suspended Over 911 Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran 911 emergency dispatcher has been
suspended for a delay in reporting to patrol officers a frantic
call from a woman facing an assailant who then shot and killed her.
   Police said Thursday that it took officers 38 minutes to respond
to an emergency call from the woman. She was shot while phoning a
second time for help.
   The average time for a dispatcher to send an emergency call to a
radio car is 3.5 minutes, but in this case the dispatcher took
almost 20 minutes to alert a patrol car after a police operator
told the dispatcher of the call, said police spokeswoman Alice
McGillion.
   Carol Kudelycz, 24, of Queens was shot to death shortly after 11
p.m. Tuesday, 23 minutes after she first called the police
emergency number. A police operator heard Ms. Kudelycz scream and
then heard a gunshot.
   Officers arrived 15 minutes after the shooting, according to
police records.
   Investigators today said they were looking for her former
boyfriend for questioning. He had been free on $5,000 bail while
awaiting trial on charges of having tried to set Ms. Kudelycz on
fire in March.
   During her first call to police, Ms. Kudelycz reported that a
man who was trying to kill her, and who had already tried once
before, was ringing her doorbell, Ms. McGillion said.
   The dispatcher, Cloria Washington, 32, who worked for the police
emergency phone system for seven years, was suspended without pay
and will face a departmental hearing, Ms. McGillion said.
   The department also will discipline the operator who took Ms.
Kudelycz' first call because he failed to include information about
the past attempt on the woman's life when forwarding the call to
Ms. Washington, the spokeswoman said.
   That operator, whose name was not released, will face
departmental charges, and will be reassigned and retrained,
according to Ms. McGillion.
</TEXT>
