<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainDerailment 1stLd-Writethru a0514 06-24 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Derailment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train May Have Been Traveling Too Fast, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 50 families evacuated, no
reported injuries and quotes from officials, picks up 8th graf pvs,
`George Powell ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROFTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heat-sensitive phosphorus inside a derailed
CSX tanker reignited as workers righted it, spewing more toxic
smoke a day after 15,000 people were evacuated from eight western
Kentucky counties, authorities said.
   Thursday night's cloud, however, was not as severe as the one
the previous night, which forced one of the largest evacuations in
the state's history, officials said. There were no reported
injuries from the second fire.
   Only about 60 families living within three miles of the
derailment were evacuated after the chemical reignited, said Don
Armstrong, a spokesman for the state Division of Disaster and
Emergency Services.
   ``By midnight it was determined that the problem was getting
less and not greater,'' said Armstrong. ``They're letting it burn
out this morning.''
   ``There's just a small fire this morning and very little of the
chemical left in the tank,'' said Shirley Arnold, a state police
dispatcher. Police units remained at the scene throughout the night
to keep sightseers away.
   The tanker was part of a CSX Transportation Corp. train that
officials say was going too fast through rural Christian County
when 34 of its cars derailed in a ravine.
   The new cloud, 100 yards wide and 400 feet high, was moving
southeast, Armstrong said.
   Greg Powell, of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's
Atlanta office, said the danger appeared minimal. Nobody was hurt
when the train caught fire again, Armstrong said.
   Officials said they believe that once the second fire is out all
of the phosphorus will have been consumed.
   Earlier Thursday, officials said the crew of the freight train
that derailed Wednesday might have avoided the accident had it seen
a 10 mph speed limit sign.
   The speed limit was posted because of a problem with the track
at the point where the train derailed. The train was traveling 35
mph, said Tim Hensley, a spokesman for CSX Transportation Corp.
   ``This probably is a factor, but we are not saying that this is
a cause,'' Hensley said. ``And it has not been developed whether it
was human error on the part of the crew, or whether they were not
provided with the information with regards to that slow order.''
   Hensley said the track was found to be in good condition when it
was inspected last month. He said the safety order was issued
because of a one-block-long stretch of rough track, possibly caused
by heat extension of the rails.
   ``Where there's a curve it will cause them to move to the
outside and form a kink,'' he said.
   The phosphorus, which can ignite spontaneously in high
temperatures, spilled from the ruptured 33,000-gallon tanker and
burned in 99-degree heat for more than 12 hours after the Wednesday
night crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
