<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Stennis 2ndLd-Writethru a0492 06-24 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Stennis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0492,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Praises Retiring Senator Stennis for His `Calm Resolve'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 10, Stennis was, to CORRECT Hayden's party</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan praised Mississippi Democrat
John C. Stennis for leading ``crucial battles'' to build up U.S.
military might during his 41-year Senate career and announced that
the Navy's next nuclear-powered aircraft carrier will be named for
the retiring senator.
   Stennis, the president pro tem of the Senate and chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, was honored at a benefit dinner on
Thursday night for the John C. Stennis Institute of Government and
the John C. Stennis chair of political science at Mississippi State
University.
   The president, in his speech, said that ``this humble man who
came to Washington from a small town in Mississippi has made an
impression on American government that is difficult to measure and
hard to fully describe.''
   As chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee in the 1970s,
Reagan said, Stennis ``led some of the most crucial legislative
battles in history on behalf of our nation's defense.''
   The president told of going to see Stennis at Walter Reed Army
Medical Center after Stennis' left leg was removed in a cancer
operation in 1984.
   ``I went to Walter Reed to encourage Senator Stennis, but when I
left it was I who had been strengthened,'' he said. ``For even from
his hospital bed, John Stennis talked of the future of this
nation.''
   Turning to Stennis, he said, ``In troubled places, you have
brought calm resolve, like one of the many great fighting ships
which you did so much to obtain for the Navy.''
   Then, to applause from the crowd of more than 1,000, the
president announced that the U.S.S. John C. Stennis will be the
next addition to the nation's nuclear-powered carrier fleet.
   Stennis, who is not seeking re-election this year, responded
with a wide smile and a wave to the crowd.
   Stennis was first elected to the Senate in a special election in
1947. He has served longer than any other senator in history except
the late Democratic Sen. Carl Hayden of Arizona.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., who succeeded Stennis as chairman of the
Armed Services Committee, said in introducing the president, ``It
is hard for me to imagine the Senate of the United States next
January without John Stennis at its helm.''
   Stennis, speaking from his seat, said the speakers who had
praised him were truly ``expressing their interest in and respect
for the free government that we have.''
   ``I am not entitled to as much credit as my friends have given
me tonight,'' he said. ``I was just trying to do what looked to be
my duty, and kept up the best I could.''
</TEXT>
