<HEAD>West German Allegedly Involved In Selling Babies Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government agents today arrested a
West German woman allegedly involved in a ring that bought babies
from impoverished Filipinos and sold them to Europeans, officials
said.
   Margaret Kresser, 48, was arrested in the tourist district of
Ermita, said the Commission on Immigration and Deportation. Birth
certificates, affidavits from Filipino parents giving up custody of
their children, and infant clothes were taken from her residence, a
commission statement said.
   Immigration and Deportation Commissioner Miriam
Defensor-Santiago said Kresser was part of a syndicate that offers
money to poor Filipinos in exchange for their children, who later
are sold in Europe.
   ``In Europe, it's extremely difficult to adopt children, apart
from the rarity of children put up for adoption. That is why this
racket flourishes,'' Santiago said.
   In a separate case, immigration agents arrested an American,
Roger Leonard Landry, on charges he was involved in swindling
activities, illegal employment, and drug abuse. There were no other
details on that case.
</TEXT>
