<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Franken     06-24 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Franken,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Novelist Rose Franken Dies at Age 92</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writer Rose Franken, a prolific novelist
who also penned Hollywood screenplays and Broadway dramas, has died
at the age of 92.
   A native of Gainesville, Texas, she spent much of her life in
New York, moving to Tucson four years ago, said her youngest son,
Peter A. Franken, a University of Arizona physics professor. She
died Wednesday.
   Mrs. Franken's first book, ``Pattern,'' was published in 1925.
Her series of ``Claudia'' books, begun in 1939, were the basis for
the movie ``Claudia and David,'' which she wrote in 1946.
   Her play ``Claudia,'' was written in 1941. She also wrote the
plays ``Another Language'' in 1932 and ``Outrageous Fortune'' in
1944.
   As a screenwriter, Mrs. Franken wrote the movie ``Beloved
Enemy'' in 1936.
   Her books also included an autobiography, ``When All is Said and
Done,'' published in 1963. Her last book, ``You're Well Out of the
Hospital,'' was published in 1966.
   In addition to her son Peter, Mrs. Franken is survived by two
other sons, John and Paul of New York, four grandchildren and one
great-grandchild.
   Her first husband, Sigmund Franken, and her second, William B.
Meloney, both predeceased her.
</TEXT>
