<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Postal-DrugTests     06-24 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postal-Drug Tests,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office to Test Job Seekers for Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service announced today that it
will begin a drug-screening program for job applicants.
   The program is expected to begin in about 90 days, the agency
said, and will be phased in over a nine-month period.
   ``We have no plans to initiate random drug tests of current
employees,'' said Assistant Postmaster General Joel S. Trosch.
``Testing for drug use by a current employee is done only if a
physician decides it should be administered as part of a medical
examination.''
   The Postal Service said it has signed a contract with Pharmchem
Laboratories of Menlo Park, Calif., to conduct the tests.
   The Office of Personnel Management said last month that plans
were being developed to administer drug tests to new federal
workers. The Postal Service, while constituted as an independent
agency, follows federal personnel policies.
</TEXT>
