<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Africa-Locusts     06-24 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Africa-Locusts,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Locust Invasion Threatening Food Supply in Sahel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IGOR UBOLDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swarms of locusts migrating from northwest Africa
will threaten the food supply in the sub-Sahara region and could
reach the Red Sea, United Nations officials said today.
   ``There is actually little hope of being able to contain the
plague in the near future,'' the director-general of the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization, Edouard Saouma, said in a statement.
   He added that the invasion ``is of unprecedented dimensions and
will affect the food security of 15 African countries, from the
Atlantic Ocean to the Red Sea.''
   Dr. Lukas Brader, head of the Emergency Center for Locust
Operations at FAO, said the locusts moved south in April and May,
earlier than expected, because plentiful rains there resulted in
favorable breeding and living conditions.
   He said the situation will worsen during the next few weeks as
new swarms arrive, coinciding with the harvest in the Sahel, the
area that extends from Senegal to the Sudan and separates the arid
Sahara from tropical West Africa.
   Brader said countries in this region face a potential loss of 1
million tons of grains. About $300 million worth of food aid would
be required to make up for the destroyed crops, he said.
   United Nations experts have said a swarm covering just half a
square mile can contain 50 million insects, weigh 100 tons and eat
its weight in vegetation each day.
   Brader said that Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia, which were first
infested with the locusts, had succeeded in keeping the locusts
south of the Atlas mountains in relatively uncultivated areas.
   He added that since the beginning of 1988, 12.3 million acres in
those countries and Mauritania have been treated with pesticides.
   In the Sahel, locust control is more difficult because the
insects are more dispersed.
   Saouma said in his statement that locust swarms were sighted in
Sudan this week and that ``it must now be feared the plague will
extend to the Red Sea, where it may invade the Arabian peninsula
and the horn of Africa.''
   If unchecked, the swarms eventually could reach Israel and
Turkey as well as the Indian subcontinent.
   Authorities try to control locusts mainly by spraying pesticides.
   The fight has cost $45 million since the beginning of 1988, and
FAO estimates a total of $150 million may be needed for the year.
   The last major invasion of locusts in Africa began in 1950 and
lasted for 13 years. Brader said the current invasion is ``the
biggest plague history recalls.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HumpbackVisitor     06-24 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Humpback Visitor,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humpback Whale Cruising Waters of Puget Sound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young humpback whale, possibly trying to
find its way out of Puget Sound's maze of inlets, has been spotted
cruising the waters of the south sound, marine biologists say.
   The whale is only the fourth humpback sighted in Puget Sound
since 1976. The last sighting was in June 1986.
   ``He's covering a lot of ground,'' said John Calambokidis, a
marine mammal researcher with the Olympia-based Cascadia Research
Collective. Calambokidis observed the whale from a boat for about
two hours Wednesday evening.
   He described it as 25 to 30 feet long, perhaps 1 year old and of
unknown gender. Adult humpbacks reach 50 feet in length.
   By photographing the whale's flukes (tail), ``we `fingerprinted'
it,'' he said.
   ``If we run into him a month from now, we'd recognize the
markings on the underside of the flukes,'' he said. ``They're
distinctive enough markings that we can see them their whole
lives.''
   Humpbacks normally spend summers feeding in the ocean off the
west coast of Canada and the United States, but individual
humpbacks occasionally stray into Puget Sound. During the winter
breeding season, they frequent waters around Hawaii and Mexico.
   Calambokidis said the whale did not appear to be distressed or
in any danger. He said there were no plans to intervene or attempt
to guide the whale out of the sound.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NerveGas     06-24 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nerve Gas,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Condemns Use of Nerve Gas in Iran-Iraq War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today condemned the use of nerve
gas in the Iran-Iraq war and urged President Reagan to pursue
aggressively an international agreement to ban production and
stockpiling of all chemical weapons.
   On a 91-0 vote, the Senate adopted a resolution noting a United
Nations finding that Iraq has used chemical weapons several times
during the war and citing reports that Iran retaliated in kind.
   The resolution specifically cited a March 16 attack in which an
estimated 2,000 Kurds were gassed to death on Iraqi soil by Iraq in
an effort to regain control of an Iranian-ocuppied villate.
   ``This is a grave violation of international law,'' said Sen.
George Mitchell, D-Maine, chief sponsor of the resolution. ``Unless
both sides forgo use of chemical weapons, there could be an even
more alarming esclation of the nearly 8-year-old Gulf war.''
   Mitchell noted that a 1925 Geneva agreement outlaws use of
chemical weapons but does not bar their production or stockpiling.
``The United Nations has never invoked sanctions of any sort
against a violator of the Geneva protocol,'' he said.
   The resolution calls on the president to ``seek allied
cooperation to further tighten controls on the export of chemical
compounds to countries seeking to develop a chemical-weapons
capability.''
   It ``urges the president to pursue American efforts at the
Geneva Conference on Disarmament to reach an arms-control agreement
banning the use, production, development, stockpiling, transfer and
acquisition of chemical weapons.''
   ``Either we can sit around and wait for the inevitable,'' said
Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., ``or we can actively and aggressively
pursue an agreement today that seeks to prevent that next attack
tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
