<HEAD>Thailand Proposes Renting Islands for Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official said today that
he will recommend that the United Nations lease desert islands so
that Vietnamese boat people have a place to live.
   ``Thirteen thousand of these islands abound in Indonesia, and it
is possible they can be converted into profitable farming areas,''
said Somporn Klinpongsa, deputy permanent secretary of the Interior
Ministry.
   Somporn said the island rentals could solve the problem of what
to do with the increasing number of Vietnamese seeking asylum.
   ``When (the) leases expire, say in 10 years, the people must
return to their homeland,'' he told The Associated Press.
   Somporn said he would seek endorsement of the proposal from the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, Jean-Pierre Hocke, at an
annual refugee conference in Geneva beginning June 29.
   Somporn said the ``islands-for-rent'' idea gained widespread
acceptance during a recent tour he took of Southeast Asian nations.
   ``Many of the boat people are farmers, and they should be
encouraged to grow sugarcane and rubber on the islands,'' he said.
   Thailand and other Southeast Asian countries regard a large
majority of the recent Vietnamese fleeing their homeland as
economic migrants rather than genuine refugees.
   The United Nations said that as of March 31, it was handling
about 40,000 Vietnamese refugees in Asia, up from 32,000 two years
ago. The largest numbers are found in Thailand, Hong Kong,
Indonesia, Philippines and Malaysia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
