<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ForgeryTrial     06-24 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forgery Trial,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Adds Classroom Appearances To Consultant's Sentence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rocky Mountain is cq, 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEN HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MARCOS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who ordered a political
consultant to make classroom appearances and a public service ad on
voting said he wanted the sentence to serve as a warning to others
who contemplate tampering with the system.
   A jury ordered $7,600 in fines and a year on probation for Rocky
Mountain, who was convicted of 38 misdemeanor forgery charges for
instructing workers to put phony signatures on petitions that got
former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont on the state's Republican
presidential primary ballot in March.
   Southern Political Consulting Inc., of which Mountain is vice
president, was ordered to pay $38,000 in fines.
   Harris County Judge Sherman Ross added to the sentence, ordering
Mountain to talk to two civics classes a week for a year on the
topic, ``The Political Process and How to Make it Work Right'' and
prepare a public service announcement ``about the value of the
right to vote.''
   Ross also ordered Mountain to finish college. He must take six
hours of Spanish to do that.
   ``I hope this message rolls like thunder across the country that
at the grass-roots level, the most important level of politics, we
have to maintain the integrity of the system,'' Ross told the
political consultant Thursday.
   Mountain faced a maximum punishment of one year in jail and
$76,000 in fines. The company faced a maximum fine of $380,000.
Defense lawyers said the convictions might be appealed.
   After the trial, Kevin Burnette, the company's president,
reiterated his claim that his Houston-based firm was the victim of
selective prosecution because it is disliked by state GOP officials.
   ``We reacted very stupidly to a very stupid rule,'' he said of
the petition rule in effect for the presidential primary.
   GOP candidates had to submit 5,000 signatures to get on the
ballot. That rule has since been changed to allow a $5,000 filing
fee instead.
   Mountain, 27, testified Tuesday that he ordered the forgeries
because he had been pressured by a du Pont campaign official. He
said he never intended for the du Pont campaign to submit them.
   But after the punishment was announced, Mountain said, ``I don't
believe I was guilty of a crime, but I accept the verdict of the
jury.''
   Of the probation conditions set by Ross, Mountain said, ``If
this thing isn't overruled and if I have to, as a condition of
probation, go out and talk to civics classes, I'll look forward to
doing that. In the long run, that will probably help business more
than anything else.''
</TEXT>
