<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0549,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Settler Fires on Moslem Crowd, Wounds Seven Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with settler shooting at
Palestinians. Pick up 15th graf pvs: `In its...' trims to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish settler in the occupied West Bank
fired a submachine gun at a crowd of rock-throwing Moslem
worshippers today and wounded seven Palestinians, an Arab witness
and hospital officials said.
   Also on the West Bank, a Palestinian stabbed a U.S.-born settler
who then chased the Arab and shot him in the elbow, army radio
said. Both the Palestinian and the Israeli were hospitalized.
   And, the army began freeing 89 Palestinians jailed for taking
part in anti-Israel disturbances. Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
said the move was part of a new policy to reward Arabs for good
behavior.
   In Nablus, Palestinians leaving the central Mazuz Masri Mosque
after Sabbath prayers stoned a settler's car, said the Arab witness
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The settler got out of the car and fired his Uzi submachine gun,
and the Palestinians hurled back stones, watermelons and shoes, the
witness said.
   Officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad Hospital said seven Arabs were
hit in the arms or legs in the shooting. Two were 8-year-old boys.
   The witness said the area was quickly surrounded by troops who
fired rubber bullets and injured four Palestinians. Arab reports
said the army later clamped a curfew on Nablus, the West Bank's
largest city where some 100,000 Arabs live.
   Al Ittihad officials also reported that a protest broke out in
refugee Camp No. 1 near Nablus and that one Palestinian was
seriously injured in the left eye by a rubber bullet.
   The military command said it was checking the reports.
   The army also placed a curfew on Hebron's central casbah, or
Arab marketplace, where the stabbing incident occurred.
   The settler, Yonah Chaiken, was shopping when an attacker
stabbed him in the shoulder and lower back, the radio and a
Jerusalem hospital spokeswoman said.
   Chaiken pulled a gun, chased the Palestinian about 50 yards and
shot him, and then ran another 300 yards to a building housing
Jewish families, where he collapsed and received first aid, said
the radio and Zev Hever, a leader of the 200-member Jewish
community in Hebron.
   The wounded Palestinian, who was captured, was identified by
officials at Hebron's Alia Hospital as Abdel Majid Sharawneh, 22.
The radio and a hospital official said Sharawneh was shot in the
elbow.
   Chaiken was later taken by helicopter to a Jerusalem's Hadassah
Hospital, where he was in stable condition, a hospital spokeswoman
said.
   He told reporters his injury ``is a direct result of American
pressure on Israel not to take stronger steps against the Arab
rioters.''
   Chaiken, originally from Boston, was the second Israeli victim
of an apparent nationalistic attack this week. On Sunday, an
Israeli farmer was bludgeoned and stabbed to death while spraying
insecticide on his vineyard south of Jerusalem.
   That death was the fourth Israeli fatality since an uprising
began Dec. 8 against the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. In all, 211 Arabs have been killed.
   In its latest leaflet, the Palestine Liberation Organization
designated today as a day of attacks on Arab tax officials who
cooperate with Israeli military authorities in the occupied lands.
   The PLO has released leaflets encouraging anti-Israeli action
since the unrest began.
   The move to free the Arab prisoners drew fire from Benny
Katzover, a senior official in Gush Emunim, the Jewish settlement
movement. Katover said the Arabs would interpret the goodwill
gesture as a sign of weakness.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, commander of Israeli forces in the
occupied West Bank, said the army would pardon 17 Palestinians
currently in jail, halt judicial proceedings against 27 suspects
and cut short the administrative detentions of 45 others.
   The army command said the move was meant ``to help calm the
situation.''
   Rabin said the army releases 50 to 80 Arab detainees a day,
``some before their trial and some before they have served their
sentences.''
   ``If a village or a family have shown good behavior, we are
going to release some detainees from the area,'' Rabin said. ``We
want to use the carrot as well, not only the stick.''
</TEXT>
