<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DuckHunting     06-24 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Duck Hunting,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Ducks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service said today it
plans to cancel or restrict the special early hunting season for
the blue-winged teal in 18 states and two other jurisdictions
because of the drought.
   The action could be only the first of new hunting restrictions
this fall, the service has warned.
   This species of duck, whose migration south begins well before
others, has been hunted for a few days in September for the past 18
years. Last year the season was nine days in September in most
states that had one.
   Populations of the blue-winged teal total about 3.6 million this
year compared with a normal 4.8 million. The service has called the
prospects for breeding this year ``grim'' because of the loss of
marshy areas in the great plains of the United States and Canada.
   Frank Dunkle, director of the service, has accepted a staff
recommendation made earlier in the week to propose cancelling the
season in Alabama, Arkansas, Indiana, Illinois, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Missouri, Ohio, Texas, Colorado, Oklahoma, Kansas and
New Mexico.
   A similar season in Iowa, legally not limited to the blue-winged
teal but in practice dominated by it, also should not be held,
according to the proposal.
   Bag limit reductions, shorter seasons or both will be proposed
for blue-winged teal and some other species, in some cases all
ducks, for Florida, Kentucky, Tennessee, Alaska, Puerto Rico and
the Virgin Islands.
   Loss of habitat from drought and other causes led the service to
adopt hunting restrictions in 1985 aimed at reducing the annual
harvest by hunters by 25 percent. Dunkle has warned there will be a
``hard look'' at the regulations this summer.
   Today's action will be proposed for public comment and should be
adopted by July 18, said spokeswoman Meagan Durham.
   Regular-season regulations, generally taking effect in October,
are not adopted until August.
</TEXT>
