<2ND_LINE>PM-Ceiling Death,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed in Ceiling Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Part of a ceiling collapsed onto a sleeping
guest at Manhattan's Helmsley Windsor Hotel today, killing the man,
police said. The top three floors of the hotel were evacuated
briefly because of the accident.
   The victim, who was described as 35 to 40 years old but was not
immediately identified, was taken to Roosevelt Hospital, where he
was declared dead on arrival, said Emergency Medical Services Capt.
William Olsen.
   The time of the collapse was not clear, said Police Inspector
James McCabe. The body was found after a light on the hotel's
switchboard indicated at 6:40 a.m. that the phone in room 1628 was
off the hook.
   Hotel security guards went to the room on the top floor of the
16-story building and found the man on the bed. The ceiling and
part of the roof's underpinnings had collapsed; the room was full
of cinderblocks and dirt, and a 4-foot-by-4-foot-by-10-inch chunk
of ceiling material was on the bed.
   ``It looked like he was killed instantly, but he might have been
lying there injured'' and knocked the phone off the hook, McCabe
said.
   The victim and his wife checked into the hotel Wednesday; his
wife left Thursday.
   The hotel, on West 58th Street, has about 20 rooms on each floor
and was nearly full Thursday night, according to police.
   Police evacuated the 14th, 15th, and 16th floors as a
precaution, said Sgt. John Venetucci, a department spokesman. But
by late morning, only the man's room and the one beneath it
remained off limits.
</TEXT>
