<HEAD>Man Arrested In Honeywell Parking Ramp Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY SUZANNE MALICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an arrest described as a ``relief to the
community,'' a 26-year-old ex-convict is being held without bail in
the strangling of a Honeywell Inc. manager in the company parking
ramp.
   David Anthony Thomas, 26, was arrested Thursday at a charitable
foundation in St. Paul where he worked, police Capt. Carl Johnson
said. Thomas, he said, was linked to the murder by fingerprints
found at the murder scene, although police still had not formally
charged him Friday morning.
   Johnson said police can hold Thomas until noon Saturday before
charging him in the June 12 death of Mary Catherine Foley, 34, of
St. Paul, who was assaulted while returning to her car after work
at Honeywell headquarters. It is possible police could get an
extension until Monday, he said.
   Police have found ``absolutely no connection'' between Thomas
and Foley, the captain said. He said the Minneapolis man previously
had been charged with rape and had been released from prison last
month.
   City Council President Alice Rainville said the arrest is ``a
relief'' to the community.
   ``We are so pleased with the professional police work that led
to (the arrest),'' she said. ``This community has been awash in
grief.''
   Elizabeth Olson, who works at the Honeywell office where Foley
worked, said she felt very relieved after hearing of Thomas' arrest.
   Olson said she has been taking extra precautions since the
murder.
   ``I already had a can of Mace, so I took that. I started
checking under my car and in my car and making sure people were
with me when I went to the ramp,'' she said.
   The arrest coincided with a memorial service for Foley in St.
Paul attended by about 500 people.
