<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh     06-24 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clash Over Islamic Law Injures 25</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a fundamentalist Moslem
party clashed with opponents of a new law making Islam the state
religion, and at least 25 people were injured, police said today.
   The clash with homemade bombs and guns lasted about two hours
Thursday in Rajshahi, about 120 miles northwest of Dhaka, police
said by telephone.
   Trouble began after two major opposition groups began a march to
protest the new law.
   Jamaat-e-Islami, a fundamentalist Moslem Party, tried to block
the march, and fighting broke out, police said.
   Jamaat-e-Islami has been involved with the opposition groups
since last November in an unsuccessful campaign of strikes and
rallies to oust President Hussain Muhammad Ershad.
   But the Moslem party broke with its allies over the Islam bill,
contending that to oppose it would encourage anti-Islamic forces.
   The Bangladesh Parliament passed a constitutional amendment on
June 7 making Islam the state religion. More than 85 percent of
Bangladesh's 105 million people are Moslem.
   The law has drawn considerable protest, not only from minority
Hindus and Christians but also from opposition parties who contend
it violates the country's secular tradition.
   Bangladesh, formerly the eastern province of Pakistan, won
independence after a civil war in 1971.
