<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Immunity     06-24 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Immunity,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Limits Government's Immunity from Lawsuits in Maryland Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited the
government's broad immunity from lawsuits, reinstating a suit by a
couple fired on by a drunk, off-duty Navy medic in Maryland.
   The 6-3 ruling expands the government's liability for negligence
in personal injury claims.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the court, said
negligence by government employees that allows a foreseeable
assault to occur by someone else can be a basis for a lawsuit
against the government.
   The government assumed responsibility in this case when Navy
corpsmen found the drunk medic but failed to report his condition
or that he was armed in violation of Navy rules, Stevens said.
   ``The theory of liability in this case is analogous to cases in
which a person assumes control of a vicious animal, or perhaps an
explosive device,'' he said.
   Similarly, he said, the government ``has a duty to prevent a
foreseeably dangerous individual from wandering about unattended.''
   The case stems from an incident on the evening of Feb. 6, 1982,
outside the Bethesda Medical Center in Maryland, a few miles from
the nation's capital.
   Michael and Mary Sheridan were driving past the hospital when
shots rang out. Mrs. Sheridan was struck by the bullets and pieces
of the shattered windshield. Her husband said he suffered from
shock.
   The shots were fired by Robert W. Carr, a Navy enlisted man who
worked as a medical aide at the hospital.
   According to court records, Carr was inebriated when he was
found unconscious shortly before the shooting by three other Navy
corpsmen.
   They attempted to take him to an emergency room, at one time
permitting him to slip from their grasp and fall down a flight of
concrete steps.
   Before reaching the emergency room, Carr regained consciousness
and flashed he barrel of a .22 caliber rifle he was carrying. The
three corpsmen fled and took no further action to alert authorities.
   Carr began shooting at passing vehicles, hitting the Sheridans'
car.
   The Sheridans sued the government, claiming the three corpsmen
were negligent for violating a Navy regulation that requires
personnel to report violations of any Navy rule.
   The rule in question was Carr's possession of firearms on the
base, something that generally is forbidden by the Navy.
   The Sheridans argued that had a civilian possessed a firearm on
the Navy base, rather than an off-duty corpsman, the government
would be liable for any injury.
   The Sheridans also said the government violated its duty to
protect the public by failing to supervise Carr properly.
   They sued the government under the Federal Tort Claims Act which
authorizes claims against the government for negligence.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last year the
government is shielded from the suit.
   The Reagan administration urged the Supreme Court to uphold the
appeals court ruling on grounds that permitting the suit could
expose the government to a vast array of such claims.
   Stevens said today the government would not be liable for
negligence if nothing more was involved than Carr's conduct at the
time he shot at the Sheridans.
   But Stevens said the actions of the other corpsmen opens the way
for the the government to be sued for negligence.
   The government is in a legal position in this case similar to
that of a private hospital that was allegedly negligent, he said.
   Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
   The case is Sheridan vs. U.S., 87-626.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
