<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FAAComputer     06-24 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FAA Computer,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Completes Computer Upgrade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY ISRAELSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The completed upgrading of the nation's
air traffic control centers will allow controllers to keep pace
with air traffic through the next decade, the head of the Federal
Aviation Administration said.
   The Salt Lake City Air Route Traffic Control Center was the last
of 20 centers to receive the new, $40 million system, linking it
with facilities nationwide.
   FAA Administrator T. Allan McArtor said during a ceremony
Thursday that the new system operates 10 times faster and has four
times the capacity of the old system.
   ``The old system was difficult to maintain and had a back-up
system that was switched to quite often. The new one will allow for
much faster response times and easier maintenance'' and no need for
a backup system, he said.
   He said the new system will allow introduction of new functions
to enhance safety and increase controller productivity.
   McArtor said upgrading Salt Lake's computer was as significant
as the driving of the golden spike that joined rails linking the
nation's first transcontinental railroad about 50 miles north of
here at Promontory in 1869.
   ``Today we're passing another transportation milestone with
another golden spike. ... It's appropriate for us to take our bows,
this is a culmination of a lot of work,'' he said.
   The Salt Lake computer cost $9 million, with the remainder of
the $40 million going for support technology.
   The Salt Lake center controls air traffic over Utah, Idaho,
Montana and Wyoming and parts of Oregon, Nevada and North and South
Dakota.
</TEXT>
