<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PandaPolicy     06-24 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panda Policy,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wildlife Service Halts New Panda Exhibits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service will not
consider further applications to exhibit pandas in U.S. zoos while
it tries to decide what its policy will be, the service announced
today.
   At least 30 institutions, most in the United States but some
overseas, have been reported negotiating with China for panda
exhibits, ``posing new, cumulative threats to the wild and captive
populations of the species,'' said a Federal Register notice.
   The service promised decisions as quickly as possible.
   The world's pandas, of which only a few hundred live in the wild
in China, are an endangered species protected by treaty and may not
be imported without a permit from the service.
   On Monday, the service denied import permits to the Michigan
Department of Natural Resources for exhibition of two pandas at the
state fair on the grounds the trip might harm their breeding
potential.
   Last week, a court decision barred the collection of fees by the
Toledo, Ohio Zoo for its panda exhibit, for which the service had
granted import permits.
   Conservation organizations have protested the growing practice
of showing pandas imported from China. Pandas attract large crowds
and sharing the fees reportedly can yield China $300,000 to
$500,000.
   The zoos contend the fees help Chinese panda breeding and
conservation programs, but conservationists contend the panda loans
threaten more harm than good.
</TEXT>
