<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Motown Suit,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Songwriter Sues Motown Founder for $170 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A songwriter who helped write dozens of hit songs
during Motown Record Corp.'s heyday in the 1960s is suing company
founder Berry Gordy Jr. for more than $170 million.
   Eddie Holland Jr. charged in the suit, filed Thursday in Wayne
County Circuit Court, that Gordy failed to pay him royalties in
1987, maliciously sued him over those payments, refused to let
Holland examine Motown financial records, and made unfavorable
licensing deals.
   Holland, 48, also asked that the court order Gordy to return to
him compositions, master recordings and copyrights related to his
work for Motown. The songs alone are worth $35.2 million, Holland
said in the suit.
   Neither Gordy nor Holland was available for comment, The Detroit
News said. Motown officials in Los Angeles, where Gordy moved most
company operations in the early 1970s, declined comment.
   Holland, his brother, Brian Holland, and Lamont Dozier wrote Top
10 hits for most Motown recording artists during the mid-1960s.
Those songs included ``You Can't Hurry Love'' and ``Stop! In the
Name of Love'' by the Supremes; ``You're A Wonderful One'' by
Marvin Gaye; ``Baby, I Need Your Loving'' and ``I Can't Help
Myself'' by the Four Tops; ``Heat Wave'' by Martha and the
Vandellas, and ``Please, Mr. Postman'' by the Marvelettes.
   Members of the Vandellas and Marvelettes also have filed suits
recently suits against Gordy and Motown in county court over unpaid
royalties.
</TEXT>
