<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Schools 1stLd-Writethru a0575 06-24 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Schools, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0575,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says States Not Required to Provide Bus Transportation for
Poor Children in North Dakota Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 14-24, In other action, with other cases.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a case of particular importance to rural
areas, the Supreme Court ruled today that states are not required
to provide free bus transportion for poor school children.
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices said North Dakota officials did not
violate the rights of families that have trouble affording the
busing charges.
   ``A state's decision to allow local school boards the option of
charging patrons a user fee for bus service is constitutionally
permissible,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said for the court.
``The Constitution does not require that such service be provided
at all and it is difficult to imagine why choosing to offer the
service should entail a constitutional obligation to offer it for
free.''
   The ruling is in line with earlier court decisions upholding
laws that treat the wealthy and poor differently. The court has
said such laws are permissible if they serve a rational purpose.
   North Dakota law provides free bus transporation to those living
in districts that have reorganized to broaden their tax base and
improve education. Only those districts that have not reorganized
are allowed to charge parents for busing costs.
   The law was intended to spur reorganization while assuring
people in those districts they would not have to pay for
transporation.
   The court said the law is a rational approach to encouraging
local school officials to reorganize.
   The law was challenged by Paula Kadrmas from rural Dickinson,
N.D. She said the statute denied equal rights to her daughter,
Sarita, because the family could not afford a $97 annual bus fee.
   Ms. Kadrmas has driven Sarita the 16 miles to school rather than
pay the fee.
   Bus service in Dickinson is offered for a fee to elementary
school students who live more than three miles from school and to
high school students who live more than four miles away.
   The North Dakota Supreme Court had upheld the law.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, in a dissenting opinion, said,
``Today, the court continues the retreat from the promise of equal
educational opportunity by holding that a school district's refusal
to allow an indigent child who lives 16 miles from the nearest
school to use a schoolbus service without paying fees does not
violate'' the Constitution.
   He was joined by Justice William J. Brennan. Justices John Paul
Stevens and Harry A. Blackmun dissented in a separate opinion.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Limited severely states' authority to lower the electric rates
public utilities charge as a result of agreements with federal
regulators.
   The court, by a 6-3 vote, said Mississippi authorities are
required to pass through to retail electricity customers a
utility's federally determined share of the costs of constructing
the Grand Gulf 1 nuclear plant.
   _ Limited the government's broad immunity from lawsuits,
reinstating a suit by a couple fired on by a drunk, off-duty Navy
medic in Maryland.
   The 6-3 ruling expands the government's liability for negilgence
in personal injury claims.
   _ Ruled that state and federal officials may not be sued for
monetary damages by people whose Social Security disability
benefits were cut off unlawfully.
   By a 6-3 vote, the court said the fact that Congress has
provided an assortment of remedies for people whose benefits
wrongly are terminated means federal courts may not allow such
lawsuits.
   _ Said its famous Miranda ruling is sufficient to protect the
rights of criminal defendants questioned by police after they are
indicted or otherwise formally charged.
   The justices, voting 5-4 to uphold an Illinois man's murder
conviction, said the warnings police have given suspects since the
court's landmark 1966 decision adquately protect an
already-indicted suspect's right to legal help.
   _ Limited the power of federal judges to dismiss criminal
charges when prosecutors violate a law requiring speedy trial of
defendants.
   In a 6-3 ruling, the court reinstated the indictment in Seattle
of Larry Lee Taylor, who is accused of cocaine trafficking.
   The school-bus case is Kadrmas vs. Dickinson Public Schools,
86-7113.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Disability     06-24 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Disability,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Officials May Not Be Sued for Monetary Damages in
Arizona DisabilityCase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and federal officials may not be sued
for monetary damages by people whose Social Security disability
benefits were cut off unlawfully, the Supreme Court ruled today.
   By a 6-3 vote, the court said the fact Congress has provided an
assortment of remedies for people whose benefits wrongly are
terminated means federal courts may not allow such lawsuits.
   Millions of people file Social Security disability claims each
year.
   ``Such a remedy, not having been included in the elaborate
remedial scheme devised by Congress, is unavailable,'' Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court in reversing a legal
victory previously won by several Arizona residents.
   Their lawsuit, sparked by the cutting-off of benefits in 1981,
had been filed against one state and two federal officials who made
policy under the Social Security Act's disability-benefits program.
   The suit said the recipients' constitutionally protected
due-process rights had been violated by then-Secretary of Health
and Human Services Richard Schweiker; John Svahn, head of the
Social Security Administration at the time; and William R. Sims,
director of the Arizona Disability Determination Service.
   A series of Supreme Court decisions since 1971 has allowed
people alleging certain constitutional violations by public
officials to sue for monetary damages in federal court.
   The court has done so when it found ``no special factors
counseling hesitation in the absence of affirmative action by
Congress'' and ``no explicit congressional declaration'' that
monetary damages may not be awarded in such cases.
   In today's decision, O'Connor said Congress has indicated that
such lawsuits should not be available when Social Security
disability benefits are ended unlawfully.
   ``We agree that suffering months of delay in receiving the
income on which one has depended for the very necessities of life
cannot be fully remedied by the belated restoration of back
benefits,'' O'Connor said.
   She noted that one of the Arizonans who sued, James Chilicky,
was in the hospital recovering from open-heart surgery when he was
informed that his heart condition was no longer classified as
disabling.
   ``Congress, however, has addressed the problems created by state
agencies' wrongful termination of disability benefits,'' O'Connor
said. ``Whether or not we believe that its response was the best
response, Congress is the body charged with making the inevitable
compromises required in the design of a massive and complex welfare
benefits program.''
   Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall and Harry A.
Blackmun dissented.
   ``In appropriate circumstances we should defer to a
congressional decision to substitute alternate relief for a
judicially created remedy,'' Brennan wrote for the three. But he
said nothing in the Social Security Act or its amendments contains
``any suggestion that Congress meant to preclude recognition of
(federal lawsuits) for persons whose constitutional rights are
violated by those charged with administering the program.''
   The case is Schweiker vs. Chilicky, 86-1781.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
