<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-SpeedyTrial     06-24 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Speedy Trial,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Limits Power of Federal Judges to Dismiss Criminal Charges
in Seattle Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited the power of
federal judges to dismiss criminal charges when prosecutors violate
a law requiring speedy trial of defendants.
   In a 6-3 ruling, the court reinstated the indictment in Seattle
of Larry Lee Taylor, who is accused of cocaine trafficking.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun, writing for the court, said the
presiding judge in the case abused her authority by failing to
analyze adequately all the factors that contributed to delay in
bringing Taylor to trial.
   ``Seemingly ignored were the brevity of the delay and the
consequential lack of prejudice to (Taylor), as well as (Taylor's)
own illicit contribution to the delay,'' Blackmun said.
   He said the judge apparently threw out the case ``in order to
send a strong message to the government that unexcused delays will
not be tolerated. That factor alone ... does not suffice to justify
barring reprosecution in light of all the other circumstances
present.''
   The ruling is a victory for the Reagan administration, which
argued for reinstatement of the indictment.
   Under the Speedy Trial Act of 1974 any criminal defendant in
federal court must be brought to trial within 70 days of being
indicted. If not, the indictment can be dismissed.
   In Taylor's case, U.S. District Judge Barbara J. Rothstein
dismissed the indictment and blocked any effort to re-indict him on
the same charges.
   Taylor had been indicted July 25, 1984, on charges of conspiring
to distribute cocaine and possessing 400 grams of cocaine with
intent to distribute it.
   His trial was scheduled to begin Nov. 19, 1984, one day before
the 70-day deadline under the Speedy Trial Act.
   Taylor failed to show up for his trial, however, and was
declared a fugitive.
   He was arrested in San Mateo County, Calif., the following
February. Taylor then was placed in the custody of federal
authorities in San Francisco while he testified as a defense
witness in a federal narcotics prosecution.
   The federal grand jury that indicted Taylor issued a superseding
indictment on April 24, 1985.
   Judge Rothstein, in considering the time elapsed from Taylor's
disapperance until the issuance of the new indictment, ruled that
most of the delay was not the government's fault and therefore did
not apply to the Speedy Trial Act.
   But she said 15 days of the delay were due to the government's
actions and therefore the Speedy Trial Act deadline had been missed
by 14 days.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld her ruling throwing
out the case.
   The Supreme Court reversed that ruling today.
   Dissenting were Justices John Paul Stevens, William J. Brennan
and Thurgood Marshall.
   The case is U.S. vs. Taylor, 87-573.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
