<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Food     06-24 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Food,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency to Send Emergency Food Aid to Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations announced today it
will send $9.1 million in emergency food to help 1.5 million
drought victims in Vietnam.
   A news release from the U.N. World Food Program said its
officials had confirmed a serious deterioration in the food supply
in 12 provinces of northern Vietnam.
   The U.N. agency said it would provide 30,000 tons of cereals and
720 tons of vegetable oil. Hanoi earlier appealed for foreign food
aid.
   The food program said the current crisis was the lastest in a
series of natural disasters that have severely reduced Vietnam's
food supply. In 1987, the country was hit by typhoons, floods,
insect infestation and an erratic monsoon season.
   Since the beginning of 1988, food shortages have increased as an
unusually prolonged winter was followed by drought, the agency
said. A shortfall of about 700,000 tons of rice for the current
June harvest is expected.
   As a result of the shortages, food prices on the open market
have soared to levels beyond the purchasing power of most
Vietnamese, the news release said.
   The Vietnamese government has also admitted to mismanagement of
the agricultural sector as well as the economy as a whole. Over the
past year, Hanoi has allowed far greater freedom to farmers in
growing and marketing their crops.
</TEXT>
