<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Bhopal     06-24 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bhopal,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preliminary Hearings On Union Carbide Petitions Adjourned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high court today adjourned preliminary
hearings on petitions filed by Union Carbide Corp. in the Bhopal
gas disaster case, the Press Trust of India reported.
   Justice S.K. Seth of the Madhya Pradesh High Court in Jabalpur
set July 22 for the next hearing, the agency said.
   The Indian government has filed a $3 billion suit against Union
Carbide for the 1984 gas leak that killed nearly 3,000 people and
injured more than 20,000 in the southern city of Bhopal.
   The gas leak at a pesticide plant operated by a Union Carbide
subsidiary was the world's worst industrial disaster.
   Two petitions filed by Union Carbide lawyers concern an order by
the Bhopal District Court instructing the U.S.-based multinational
to pay interim relief to the gas victims.
   Seth on April 4 upheld the order and fixed the amount at $192
million. Union Carbide lawyers on May 2 petitioned the court to
review Seth's decision.
   The other application filed by Union Carbide concerned a June 16
order by Bhopal District Judge M.W. Deo.
   Union Carbide, headquartered in Danbury, Conn., argued that Deo
had pre-judged the case by ordering interim relief. The company had
asked that the case be tranferred to another judge.
   Deo declined to remove himself from the case.
</TEXT>
