<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0577,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Visits U.S. Caribbean Island</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 7th graf to CORRECT century mansion built to 16th sted
17th, bgng ``We've made...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson picked up six of
Puerto Rico's 57 delegates today and said their switch represented
``a victory for the people'' who gave him a primary win here.
   As Jackson opened a three-day visit to this Caribbean island,
the Boston Globe reported that the Democratic candidate has
indicated to aides that he would not accept the vice presidential
nomination if it is offered by Michael Dukakis.
   ``What he implied was that he was not going to tie his tail to
anyone else's kite,'' one aide, speaking on condition on anonymity,
told the Globe.
   Jackson breakfasted this morning in the Condado Beach Hotel with
his local campaign committee and said picking up the delegates
represented ``a victory for the people...a victory for democracy.''
   He said Thursday night he also wants to meet with Puerto Rican
delegates in hopes of persuading more of them to support him.
   Jackson won the island's non-binding primary on March 20, but
received none of the island's 57 delegates. They were chosen as
uncommitted, then pledged to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis by
Puerto Rico Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon.
   ``We've made steps in the right direction,'' Jackson said after
an hour-long session at the stately 16th-century Spanish governor's
mansion.
   Hernandez Colon said he and other party leaders decided there
were six delegates who weren't firmly committed to Dukakis and
preferred Jackson.
   ``We expect we will be able to obtain that support from them ...
in the interests of party unity and in the interests of the
fairness question,'' Hernandez Colon said.
   He said Jackson wants other delegates approached as well.
   ``We are willing to undertake such a search to see if additional
support can be gotten,'' the governor said.
   Jackson said he will push at next month's convention for a
change in delegate-selection rules. Hernandez Colon agreed that
Puerto Rico's system should be changed.
   Hernandez Colon explained that the vote for uncommitted delegate
slates, who didn't campaign for presidential candidates, was a
battle of local politics.
   His Popular Democratic Party, which supports the Commonwealth
status, won 55 of 57 delegates over the rival New Progressive
Party, which wants statehood.
   Hernandez Colon said he had conferred earlier with Dukakis
national campaign officials.
   ``They told me to do what we thought was best for party unity,''
Hernandez Colon said.
   Jackson reiterated his support for Puerto Rican
self-determination, which he described as giving the islanders the
right to choose their own status without fear of losing U.S.
support. He said he thought the issue of Puerto Rican status should
be addressed at the convention.
   Asked whether he sought support from the Puerto Rican governor
for himself as the party's vice presidential candidate, Jackson
replied: ``We did not discuss that, but between now and Saturday,
he could get that inspired.''
   Jackson said earlier in Washington he has made a decision on how
he would reply if offered the vice presidential nomination, but is
keeping it private for now. Hernandez Colon said Jackson ``deserves
serious consideration.''
   Hernandez Colon angered many Puerto Rican politicians in New
York by campaigning for Dukakis. Jackson was accompanied here by
state Sen. Olga Mendez of New York.
   The governor, who will head Puerto Rico's delegation to Atlanta,
met in New York two weeks ago with Puerto Rican political leaders
to explain why he supported Dukakis.
   The governor, who for years has had close ties with
Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, said he supported Dukakis
because he considered him a socially progressive governor who had
the best chance to win. Dukakis also is willing to support
increased autonomy for the commonwealth, Hernandez Colon said.
   The 3.2 million Puerto Ricans have U.S. citizenship and are
largely self-governing but subject to federal laws. They do not
vote in national elections and their delegate to Congress has no
vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
