<HEAD>CORE Investigator Claims Drug Use in Brawley Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to incorporate new information from CORE,
edit to conform, picking up 5th graf pvs, `McClease has ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Congress of Racial Equality
confirmed today that an investigator hired by his group has
uncovered evidence of drug use in the case of a black teen-ager who
claims she was kidnapped and raped by white men.
   Meanwhile, a man who says he is a surveillance expert either has
or soon will appear before a federal grand jury investigating
possible fraud in the Tawana Brawley case, according to reports
published today.
   The New York Times, citing unidentified sources, said
authorities had granted Samuel McClease immunity from prosecution
for illegal break-ins and other possible offenses in exchange for
his cooperation.
   The New York Post, also quoting unnamed sources, said that the
deal may include McClease's pleading guilty to some minor charges.
   McClease has said he was hired by the Rev. Al Sharpton, a
Brawley family adviser, to plant listening devices in the home and
office of one of the Brawley family lawyers, C. Vernon Mason, and
in Sharpton's own home.
   The private investigator hired by CORE said in a WKNY radio
interview Thursday in Kingston that he had evidence suggesting Miss
Brawley was involved in drugs and prostitution during her four-day
disappearance last November.
   ``Our best belief is that Tawana got involved in something
initially voluntarily,'' said Galen Kelley, a forensic psychologist
hired by CORE executive director Roy Innis last December. ``It had
to do with drugs ... you'd have to define it as prostitution.''
   Kelly said he would report his findings to the grand jury in New
York City. ``That's the report he has presented to me,'' Innis said
of Kelley's comments today from his Brooklyn office. ``That drug
thing comes up all the time.''
   McClease has said his tapes show that the advisers did not
believe Miss Brawley's story that she was kidnapped and raped by
six white men, but were using the case for personal and political
gain.
   None of the papers' sources could verify that the tapes included
the information McClease said they did. However, WCBS-TV reported
today that both U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, who heads the
federal investigation, and state Attorney General Robert Abrams,
who has been appointed special prosecutor in the Brawley case, have
heard the tapes.
   Miss Brawley, 16, and her family have refused to cooperate with
a state grand jury, which has been trying to learn what happened to
the Wappingers Falls girl during four days last November.
   The Post said that McClease turned over tapes of conversations
to the federal grand jury Thursday. The sources also said McClease
testified Thursday and was expected to resume testifying today.
   But the Times said it was unclear when McClease would be called
to testify.
   McClease said Sharpton feared as early as February that the
story was falling apart and wanted something he could use to
protect himself.
   Sharpton denies knowing, meeting or hiring McClease. The team of
Brawley advisers have called him a liar.
</TEXT>
