<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NavyDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0526 06-24 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys: Navy Won't Court-Martial Three Sailors in Trainee's
Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with admiral's spokesman
declining comment in 3rd graf, `A spokesman...'; SUBS 6th graf to
add battery charge, `Morris also...'; SUBS pvs grafs 7 though 9,
`Torchia and...' to CORRECT that Blevins has not made decision and
CORRECT spelling to Barry sted Berry. Picks up 10th graf pvs,
`Petty Officers...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy will drop manslaughter charges
against at least two of the six sailors charged in a recruit's
death, and has offered non-judicial punishment rather than a court
martial to three of them, defense attorneys say.
   Attorneys for Petty Officers 1st Class Richard E. Blevins and
David J. Smith, instructors at the Naval Rescue Swimmer School,
said they were informed Thursday of the decision by Rear Adm. David
R. Morris, chief of naval air training, in Corpus Christi, Texas.
   A spokesman for Morris, Lt. Lee Saunders, said today he couldn't
comment on the lawyers' statements because the admiral is still
investigating the case.
   Blevins, Smith and three other instructors were charged with
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery in the
March 2 death of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   Mirecki was literally scared to death when he was forced into a
swimming pool after trying to quit a rescue course at the Pensacola
Naval Air Station, according to testimony at an investigative
hearing two weeks ago.
   Morris also gave Blevins and Smith the option of non-judicial
punishment, which could mean a pay cut, restriction to the base or
extra duty on the conspiracy charge and an added charge of battery,
the lawyers said.
   Thomas A. Torchia, the officer in charge of the school, was
charged only with dereliction of duty and also is being offered
non-judicial punishment instead of a court-martial, said his
lawyer, Lt. Thomas C. Leighton.
   None of the three have decided whether to accept the unspecified
non-judicial punishment or opt for court-martial, which could clear
them of the charges, their attorneys said.
   Smith's civilian attorney, Barry Beroset, said he was told of
the admiral's decision in a telephone call from the prosecutor in
the case, Lt. Cmdr. Larry Wynne.
   Blevins' attorney, Lt. Steven H. Cohen, said today that Blevins
was given until Monday to make his decision. If he should opt for
the non-judicial punishment he would go before Morris on Wednesday
in Pensacola.
   Petty Officers 2nd Class Frankie D. Deaton, John W. Zelenock and
Michael W. Combe had faced the same charges as Smith and Blevins,
but lawyers for those three refused to comment on the disposition
of their cases.
   If court-martialed and found guilty, the defendants could have
been sentenced to prison and expelled from the service.
   Non-judicial punishment could include a 50 percent cut in pay
for two months, reduction of one pay grade, restriction to base for
60 days, extra duty for 45 days or any combination of those
penalties, Cohen told WEAR.
   Lynne Johansen, Mirecki's sister, said the family expected that
court-martials might not be recommended for all the defendants
following the investigative hearing.
   Mrs. Johansen said criminal proceedings were secondary to
finding out how her brother died, which the hearing accomplished,
and said changes in the training program were made to avoid a
recurrence.
   ``We still feel very satisfied in knowing many changes have been
made in the situation,'' she said in a telephone interview from
Appleton.
   The rescue swimmer school was closed March 29 and reopened
Monday after changes in procedures, including a ban against
instructors touching recruits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
