<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0842 06-24 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0842,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of Eugene O'Neill's `Ah, Wilderness!' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 3 grafs with what other critics said.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Ah, Wilderness!,'' Eugene O'Neill's only
comedy, is tinged with a poignancy that rarely surfaces in revivals
of this sweet-tempered play.
   That sadness comes through in the production starring Jason
Robards and Colleen Dewhurst which opened Thursday at Broadway's
Neil Simon Theater. It is a wistful, gentle remounting of a work
that celebrates the loss of innocence as well as the gaining of
self-knowledge.
   What makes the poignancy even more apparent is the pairing of
the play with ``Long Day's Journey into Night.'' They are running
in repertory at the Neil Simon as part of the First New York
International Festival of the Arts. ``Long Day's Journey,'' with
its miserly father, drug-addled mother and alcoholic sons, was the
reality of O'Neill's life. `Ah, Wilderness!'' is the fantasy.
   O'Neill once called the comedy ``a nostalgia for a youth I never
had,'' and a rosy-hued remembrance infuses the entire play. It's
set in 1906 _ six years before ``Long Day's Journey Into Night'' _
and takes place in a small Connecticut town during that most
American of holidays, the Fourth of July. Parades, picnics,
fireworks, family dinners with most of the clan gathered around the
table, all are part of the play's long, leisurely story.
   ``Ah, Wilderness!'' centers on the Miller family, particularly
the 17-year-old son Richard, a stand-in for the playwright. Richard
is a rebel and a romantic, fond of quoting Swinburne, Shaw and all
those other ``radical'' writers dismissed by his mother and
secretly admired by his father.
   The parents in ``Ah, Wilderness!'' are everything O'Neill wanted
in his own father and mother. Nate and Essie Miller are
good-humored people who may be stern but are also always forgiving.
Most of the other adults are equally understanding. There's quiet
Aunt Lily and the hard-drinking but genial Uncle Sid who is not
made unbearable or destroyed by liquor like some of the characters
in ``Long Day's Journey.''
   Robards excels as crusty but kind-hearted father and Dewhurst
manages to turn the role of the mother _ usually considered a minor
character _ into a protective hen who will battle for her baby even
if she disapproves of what he does. They are adept at getting
laughs out of the most inconsequential situation.
   The pivotal role of Richard is played by a ruddy-cheeked young
actor named Raphael Sbarge. He brings an open-mouthed innocence to
a character who could be insufferable but here is genuine and
appealing.
   There are effective cameos from Elizabeth Wilson as Lily; George
Hearn as a golden-voiced Uncle Sid, a happy drunk who knows how to
sing; Campbell Scott as Richard's pompous older brother, and Annie
Golden as a baby-faced lady of the evening who tries to seduce
Richard.
   The setting by Michael H. Yeargan also links the play to ``Long
Day's Journey into Night.'' That living room, designed by Ben
Edwards, was dark and dank and featured a view of Long Island
Sound. The same water view is in Yeargan's set but the living room
is filled with bright furnishings and framed by flowered wallpaper.
   Arvin Brown has directed the show at a slow pace. There are
three long acts, and he has filled each with a lot of stage
business. It is a deliberately old-fashioned approach to the play,
allowing the audience to savor each member of the large cast.
   ``Ah, Wilderness!'' ends on a hopeful, expectant note as Brown
and company conjure up a stunning tableau. Richard gazes dreamily
at a full summer moon while his father remarks to his mother,
``Spring isn't everything ... There's a lot to be said for autumn
... And winter, if you're together.''
   It's a togetherness O'Neill's family never achieved, but at
least he managed to unite his imaginery family in ``Ah,
Wilderness.'' Robards, Dewhurst and the rest of the cast bring them
vibrantly to life.
   Frank Rich, in The New York Times, said: ``... It's hard to
imagine contemporary theatergoers being held by `Ah, Wilderness!'
unless they see `Long Day's Journey' in close proximity. I would
visit the plays in reverse order of composition, for O'Neill's most
cheerful work is best enjoyed now not for its comedy but as a
chaser to the mature brew of his art.''
   Howard Kissel in the New York Daily News wrote: ``Arvin Brown's
production captures beautifully the sunlit quality of the play. At
times it moves slowly, but after all, this is a period when
motoring is still regarded as a sport.''
   Clive Barnes in the New York Post wrote that the play provided
``total enchantment. ... On the surface `Ah, Wilderness!' is no
better a play than `Life with Father' or `You Can't Take It With
You,' but listen deeper and the echoing resonance of O`Neill _ the
youth of commonplace language with the certainty of natural speech,
the depth of characterization and aptness of anecdote _ soars above
the conventional.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ThripInsects     06-24 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrip Insects,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Insect Called Pear Thrip Threatens Vermont Maple Syrup, Fall
Foliage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BENNINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lush, green mountainsides in southern
Vermont have been scarred with patches of brown, the work of tiny
insects that are threatening the state's maple sugar industry and
tourism.
   A bug known as the pear thrip is blamed for damaging nearly
500,000 acres of forest in Vermont this year. By comparison, 21,000
acres were damaged last year, said H. Brenton Teillon, chief of
forest protection for the state Department of Forests and Parks.
   Officials say the bugs that attacked millions of maple trees
this spring are the state's worst insect problem in more than 25
years. The current drought is putting still further stress on trees.
   The maples are a source of income for hundreds of Vermonters who
tap them to produce syrup and sugar candy. The state produced
370,000 gallons of maple syrup this year, leading the nation, and
that generated $12.5 million in income.
   The loss of a significant portion _ some foresters fear up to a
fifth _ of the maples could also mean far fewer dollars this fall
from tourists who come to view the foliage.
   From a window in a four-seat plane, state forester Pete
Norkeveck assessed the damage over Bennington on Thursday
afternoon. Some forestland had retained its brilliant green, but
there were wide swaths of shriveled brown foliage with tints of
gray and orange.
   ``Those trees are in real trouble,'' says Norkeveck. ``If we
don't get some rain in the next couple of weeks, we're looking at a
very high mortality rate. Even with some rain, a lot of them might
not survive.''
   Pear thrips have been in the United States since the early part
of the century, but historically they have been a problem mainly in
orchards.
   Norkeveck said the pear thrips attack a tree's flowers in early
spring. The bugs then enter a period of dormance.
   Experts are unsure why the problem flared up this year. They
cite a variety of possible factors, including the drought, a
heavier-than-normal blooming of the maples this spring, and a cold
snap at a key time this spring that may have been a boon to the
insects.
   Bob Twitchell of Landgrove said he was one of the first maple
growers to be affected. He first saw the defoliation in the early
summer of 1985. To reduce stress on the maples on his 60-acres, he
decided not to tap his trees the following spring, losing his main
source of income for a year.
   ``If you don't tap for one year, you don't have the resources to
continue,'' he said. ``A lot of people just do it as a part-time
thing and they don't depend on it as much. But if I let up for one
year, I'm done for.''
   The problem has grown only worse.
   ``It looks like winter. There's nothing there,'' he said. ``I
just don't know as there's anything I can do.''
   He's given up sugaring completely for lumbering, and talks of
selling off some of his property to make ends meet.
   A similar sense of worry and uncertainty was evident Thursday
among 50 maple sugar producers, landowners, state and Canadian
officials who met in Bennington to discuss the problem.
   To a lesser degree, the infestation has also affected parts of
other New England states, New York and Pennsylvania, foresters said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
