<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PortraitProtest     06-24 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portrait Protest,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Painter Sues Police, Aldermen Over Seized Portrait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union has filed a
lawsuit on behalf of an artist whose portrait of the late Mayor
Harold Washington in women's undergarments was seized by police
from an exhibition.
   The lawsuit, filed Thursday in federal court, seeks $100,000 in
damages from Police Superintendent LeRoy Martin, unidentified
officers and three City Council members: Allan Streeter, Dorothy
Tillman and Bobby Rush.
   Several black aldermen marched from City Hall to the School of
the Art Institute on May 11 to demand that the portrait by David
Nelson be removed from an exhibiton of students' work.
   Police seized the painting, saying the display could provoke a
riot.
   ``We all must follow the rule of law, not the rule of
aldermen,'' said ACLU attorney Harvey Grossman. ``The law is quite
clear. The police must control the audience, not the speaker ...
not the painting.''
   ``I am deeply offended and angry at the vigilante behavior of
the aldermen and the irresponsible conduct of police,'' Nelson said
in a statement. ``I am suing to vindicate my rights and to ensure
that Chicago aldermen and police do not become the censors of other
artists in the future.''
   Rush called the lawsuit ``frivolous.''
   ``I'm not sure what the absolute motivation is, whether it's an
attempt to enhance (ACLU) fund-raising activities or if it's
political, because there were only three aldermen targeted for the
suit,'' he added.
   Defendants are accused of depriving Nelson of his right to
freedom of expression under the First Amendment; his right to be
free from unreasonable seizure under the Fourth Amendment; and his
right not to be deprived of property without due process under the
14th Amendment.
   Washington died of a heart attack last November.
</TEXT>
