<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PandaPolicy     06-24 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panda Policy,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Imposes Temporary Halt On Panda Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service warned zoos
Friday it will not consider applications to import pandas for
exhibit while it tries to decide whether and how to restrict the
practice.
   A Federal Register notice said reported plans by 30 instititions
in the United States and abroad to show pandas on loan from China
are ``posing new, cumulative threats to the wild and captive
populations of the species.''
   Michigan's Department of Natural Resources was denied import
permits on Monday to show pandas at a state fair. Last week, a
court order barred the Toledo, Ohio Zoo from collecting fees to see
pandas there on loan from China.
   The Toledo pandas were imported under a permit granted by the
service.
   Pandas are an endangered species protected by treaty and may not
be imported without a permit from the service. Only a few hundred
live in the wild in China, and zoologists fear the populations,
devastated by the loss of bamboo forests, are not large enough to
be self-sustaining.
   Conservation organizations claim the enthusiasm for showing
pandas imported from China, which attract large fee-paying crowds,
could hurt the species. China's share of the fees from a panda loan
has been reported at $300,000 to $500,000.
   The zoos contend that the fees help Chinese panda breeding and
conservation programs.
   The service promised decisions as quickly as possible.
</TEXT>
