<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Moscow-Embassy     06-24 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moscow-Embassy,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Will Consult Congress on Fate of Moscow Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says it will begin
consultations with Congress this autumn on what to do about the
U.S. Embassy in Moscow, which may have to be torn down because it
is believed to be riddled with listening devices.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said consultations
with Congress will be necessary before a presidential decision on
the embassy, because appropriations to fix the problem will be
necessary.
   A final report on the matter is still pending from a team of
consultants, the BDM Corp. and MK-Ferguson Co.
   According to a preliminary report by the private engineers, it
would be better and no more expensive to tear down the entire
eight-story chancery building and erect a new structure, than
rebuild part of the building.
   Congressional investigations led by Reps. Olympia Snowe,
R-Maine, and Dan Mica, D-Fla., also have led to suggestions the
facility be razed.
   On the other hand, surveys commissioned by the Reagan
administration recommend the remodeling approach. Former Defense
Secretary James R. Schlesinger proposed that the top three stories
be rebuilt and that the most sensitive work be conducted in a newly
constructed annex.
   A study by Anne L. Armstrong, head of the President's Foreign
Intelligence Advisory Board, also said the building could be
salvaged.
   The United States began work on the new building a decade ago,
but it has not been occupied by American diplomats because of
structural flaws and evidence that the Soviet embedded listening
devices in the walls.
   In a tit-for-tat move, the Soviets have been denied access to
their new chancery building in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
