<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u n AM-`Bankrupt'Millionaires     06-24 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-`Bankrupt' Millionaires,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lotto Winners to Repay Debts from Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who filed for bankruptcy six weeks
before winning $4.6 million in the lottery say they'll pay their
debts even though they're not required to by law.
   ``We're not criminals,'' Jerome Jenks of Haines City said. ``We
want to clear up our credit.''
   The first of 20 yearly Florida Lotto checks for $229,000 was
issued to the Jenkses on Friday. Legally, their creditors can't
demand a nickel from the windfall.
   ``They can tell them to go fly a kite,'' Chief Bankruptcy Judge
Alexander Paskay said.
   The Jenkses listed debts of more than $17,000 when they filed
the Chapter 7 bankruptcy petition May 3.
   Jenks, 42, a $300-a-week night shift supervisor at a soap plant,
and his 38-year-old wife Theresa, a $290-a-week housekeeper at Walt
Disney World, said bankruptcy was their last resort when their
income dropped because of cuts in overtime.
   Chapter 7 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act anticipates
inheritances, among other windfalls that can change a bankruptcy
status, but lottery winnings acquired after filing for liquidation
can't be touched.
   ``Timing is everything,'' said Terry E. Smith, the trustee in
the case. ``A bankruptcy is a snapshot of an individual at a point
in time. It doesn't matter whether they get better off or worse off
later.''
   ``I love their luck,'' said A. Karl Stevens, the Jenkses'
lawyer. ``When a person files for bankruptcy, it's a fairly
degrading process.''
   The Jenkses were able to keep their home, a few household
possessions and their two cars as long as they kept up with the
payments.
   And they got to tear up their other bills _ more than $14,000
owed on credit cards, $3,473 owed to the Florida Central Credit
Union of Lakeland and a disputed $389 car-repair bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
