<HEAD>Mine-Damaged Frigate Being Readied for Trip Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mine-damaged U.S. missile frigate
Samuel B. Roberts has been refloated before it is loaded aboard a
special cargo vessel for the trip home for repairs, sources in the
United Arab Emirates said Friday.
   The shipping sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
they expected the operation to take place over the weekend. Heavy
swells apparently thwarted plans to do it Friday.
   The 3,600-ton frigate remained moored at a dock near the Dubai
shipyard where it underwent preliminary repairs after it hit an
Iranian mine in the central Persian Gulf on April 14.
   The ship will be put aboard the Mighty Servant 2, a 25,743-ton
Dutch semi-submersible cargo vessel chartered to take the frigate
to the United States.
   U.S. military officials declined to say when the crippled
warship would actually leave. Naval ship movements are kept secret.
   The Samuel B. Roberts hit a submerged mine after stumbling into
what U.S. officers said was a newly laid minefield 50 miles
northeast of Qatar.
   Ten sailors were wounded in the blast that ripped a 25-foot gash
in the hull. Senior U.S. officials have credited the other crewmen
with saving the ship by controlling fires and flooding.
   The United States retaliated by attacking two Iranian oil
platforms April 18, starting daylong fighting in which six Iranian
naval craft were sunk or damaged.
   About 30 of the Samuel B. Roberts' sailors will accompany the
ship to home port at Newport, R.I., a trip expected to take about
six weeks.
   About 140 other crewmen returned Monday to the United States.
   The frigate will be taken from Newport to the Bath Iron Works in
Bath, Maine, for further repair work.
   The Samuel B. Roberts was escorting shipping in the gulf, which
has been a target of spillover attacks in the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq
war.
</TEXT>
