<HEAD>Reagan Meets With Marionite Catholic Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan met with Marionite Catholic
Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir of Lebanon today and the religious leader
said Reagan promised to do ``all in his power to put an end to the
tragic situation'' in the war-torn country.
   Neither the patriarch nor the White House, however, indicated in
separate statements about the private meeting what commitments, if
any, were made.
   The White House said Vice President George Bush met separately
with the patriarch. The Most Rev. Pio Laghi, the apostolic nuncio,
or diplomatic representative of the Vatican in Washington, also
attended the meetings.
   The patriarch said he asked Reagan to help bring peace to
Lebanon. Asked how the president responded, he said, ``He promised
to make all in his power to put an end to the tragic situation.''
   Asked what specific steps were mentioned, he said, ``I can't say
what, because it is up to the president of the United States to
choose the means by which they might do something.''
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk issued a statement saying
that both Reagan and Bush ``reaffirmed U.S. support for the
restoration of Lebanon's unity, sovereignty, and territorial
integrity, and the withdrawal of all foreign forces from Lebanon.''
   The patriarch, asked whether he thought Syrian forces performed
a useful role in Lebanon, said, ``We are asking to see all the
non-Lebanese armed go out of Lebanon, so Lebanon will be pacified.''
   On the question of hostages held in Lebanon, he said, ``We know
that we have nothing to help in this way, but we talked about peace
in Lebanon. About the hostages, it is a very difficult thing. It is
not for me to say what we can do for them.''
   He said Marionite Christian leaders were in touch with Moslem
religious leaders on the question, but ``all Lebanon is taken
hostage.''
