<HEAD>Fort Worth Defense Contractor Helping Taiwan Develop Jet Fighters
^Eds: CORRECTS newspaper's name in 2nd graf; SUBS 6th graf, `Three
State ...,' with 4 grafs to add no comment from State Department
spokesman today, add background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of General Dynamics Corp.
have for the past three years secretly helped the Taiwan government
develop a new fighter plane, it was reported today.
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram said the aircraft is being designed
by a group of about 100 Taiwanese engineers and technicians, with
General Dynamics employees acting as advisers.
   The Americans are not directly involved in the aircraft design
or production, said a company official familiar with the program
who spoke on the condition he not be identified. ``We are not
building it or designing it. We are merely teaching them how to
design it,'' he said.
   The program has the approval of the State Department but has
operated quietly to avoid offending China. China and Taiwan do not
recognize each other.
   ``It's a touchy political problem. The State Department knows
about it, China knows about it, but as long as it doesn't get a lot
of publicity, they won't complain,'' the official told the
Star-Telegram.
   The nature of the U.S.-Taiwanese military relationship is a
highly sensitive issue that State Department officials are
reluctant to discuss.
   Under a 1982 agreement, the United States retains the right to
sell defense equipment and services Taiwan needs for defense. At
the same time, however, a 1972 agreement between China and the
United States imposes ``qualitative and quantitative'' restrictions
on what Taiwan is given.
   Neither agreement spells out in detail how the restrictions
apply to particular weapons systems.
   Alex Almasov, a State Department spokesman, today declined to
comment on the report about General Dynamics.
   General Dynamics spokesman Z. Joe Thornton told the newspaper
Thursday that he could not comment on the program.
   ``We can't talk about that. ... It's a sensitive issue,'' he
said.
   The unidentified General Dynamics official said that several
hundred employees have worked on the program, which is worth about
$200 million to the defense contractor and also involves other U.S.
companies.
   Work on the program is being done in a small, unmarked building
in Fort Worth, the Star-Telegram said.
   Col. Yi Chou, a weapons procurement officer in Taiwan's
representative office in Washington, D.C., said the Taiwanese
government has ``a team based at General Dynamics.''
   He declined to provide any details of the work being performed
in Fort Worth but said the team was headed by a Taiwanese military
officer.
   A press officer at the Chinese embassy said that he could not
comment on the Taiwanese aircraft program. However, Chiwei Zhang
added, ``Our government's general policy is that we oppose any
foreign country to supply arms to Taiwan.''
   General Dynamics' F-16 Fighting Falcon is one of the most
successful fighter aircraft in U.S. history, with more than 3,000
ordered by the U.S. Air Force, the Navy and 15 foreign countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
