<HEAD>Ousted Haitian President In Miami Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Manigat's arrival, picking
up 8th graf pvs, ``I do ...;' Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Haitian President Leslie Manigat's stopover
in Miami today on his way to an international forum of Christian
Democrats in Rome won't win him support from Haitians living in the
United States, a Haitian-American leader said.
   ``He thinks he'll look better in the eyes of the Haitians back
home, but he's not going to get a tribute here,'' said Roger
Biamby, head of the Haitian American Community Association of Dade.
   Biamby said Manigat hopes his visit to Miami will shore up his
credentials as a genuine opposition figure, but the strategy won't
work.
   ``We were not supporters of Manigat,'' said the Rev. Gerard
Jean-Juste, who heads the Haitian Refugee Center, a grassroots
organization in Little Haiti.
   Manigat arrived in Miami this afternoon aboard a private 10-seat
jet. As he walked with his wife to a U.S. Customs office, he
flashed a V sign to about 25 Haitians gathered at Miami
International Airport. They responded with applause.
   He had been in exile in the Dominican Republic since he was
overthrown Sunday by Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy.
   Namphy ran the country as head of an interim junta for two years
after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled into exile. He turned over
power in February to Manigat, who was elected the previous month in
military-run elections that were rife with fraud.
   ``I do understand that he is passing through Miami Friday on his
way to Rome ... where there is a meeting of the Christian Democrat
International Conference,'' said State Department spokesman Charles
Redman. ``He's going to be participating in that.''
   The United States is not involved in Manigat's travel plans and
no administration officials planned to meet with him, Redman said.
   Manigat, 57, will probably escape any protest demonstrations
because exiles in Miami don't want to be seen as backing Sunday's
coup. Instead, Haitian groups here plan to ignore Manigat.
   ``He should not be allowed to come to the United States. He's a
traitor to the Haitian people, he's a traitor to democracy,''
Biamby said, referring to allegations that Manigat was connected to
the violence that disrupted Haitian elections.
</TEXT>
