<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Blast     06-24 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Blast,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Killed, Five Injured in Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blast ripped through the refrigerated storage
section of a meat processing plant in central Russia, killing two
workers and injuring five others, it was reported Friday.
   The explosion in Yaroslavl occurred when a high-pressure pipe
burst during maintenance work, the news agency Tass said. Ammonia
from the pipe leaked into an adjacent building and ignited.
   Tass quoted rescue official Vladimir Vatin as saying the plant
and four nearby kindergartens considered to be in what he called a
``danger zone'' were evacuated, and residents of nearby houses were
warned of the danger of further blasts.
   ``The consequences of the accident could have been greater'' if
rescue services had not worked efficiently and promptly, Vatin said.
   Tass said without explanation that ``the accident was localized
by 1:30 p.m. and the all-clear signal was given in the area at 6
p.m.''
   It did not specify whether this meant people had returned to the
evacuated areas.
   Last month, a massive blast caused by an industrial explosive on
railway cars killed 88 people and injured more than 200 in an
accident near the industrial city of Gorky northeast of Moscow.
</TEXT>
