<HEAD>3,500 Candidates Register for Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,500 candidates from 16 political
parties have registered to run in nationwide parliamentary
elections, government officials said Friday.
   Friday marked the deadline for registration and the final
candidate count would be known Saturday, said Yuvarat Gamolvej,
deputy director of the Local Administration Department.
   The candidates will vie for 357 seats in the lower house in
elections July 24.
   There are 26 million eligible voters in Thailand.
   Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda dissolved Parliament in April
because ministers of the Democrat Party, the main party of his
coalition government, voted against government-backed legislation
to protect U.S. copyrights.
   Critics maintain the prime minister dissolved Parliament to
avoid a probable no-confidence motion by the opposition in May.
   Prem, a former army chief, has been prime minister since 1980.
He is widely expected to return to power.
