<HEAD>British Oarsman Fails to Complete Around-the-World Voyage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GWEEK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exhausted British adventurer gave up
his third attempt to row solo around the world and was rescued by a
French trawler off the coast of Brittany, the coast guard said.
   Geoff Cooper, 36, rowed away from the southwestern English port
of Gweek in his 16-foot boat on June 17, expressing confidence
despite previous failures.
   But he was exhausted Thursday when he was picked up 46 miles
south of the Cornwall region of England, said a Falmouth coast
guard spokesman. Cooper had said he planned to complete the
36,000-mile trip in three years.
   Cooper's 1986 attempt ended after 36 hours, when he injured a
wrist 37 miles offshore and was rescued by a helicopter.
   Last year, three British navy helicopters had to rescue him
during a practice trip.
