<HEAD>American Crews Help Fight Fires In Drought-Hit Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures U.S.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 American firefighters are helping
Canadian crews battle hundreds of forest fires raging across the
drought-parched prairie provinces and northern Ontario.
   Light rain on Friday helped subdue flames in one of the worst
blazes, near the mining center of Sudbury, Ontario, but the Natural
Resources Ministry said the fire was still out of control. About 18
squares miles of forest land have been destroyed there.
   Ontario is spending $622,500 a day to fight 230 fires, and 27
are burning out of control, the ministry said. About $166 million
worth of timber has been destroyed.
   The American firefighters, who call themselves the ``Hot
Shots,'' come from the National Interagency Wildlife Center in
Boise, Idaho.
   In Saskatchewan, officials evacuated 400 people Thursday near
Saskatoon after a fire broke out in Pike Lake Provincial Park. A
huge blaze in northeast Saskatchewan was dampened overnight by
light rain, but Norm Hook of the provincial Forest Fire Management
Center said: ``It's like a sleeping giant, just sitting there and
waiting for wind.''
   The federal government's Interagency Forest Fire Center in
Winnipeg said 5,500 forest fires have been reported across the
country so far this year, compared with 4,700 by this date in 1987.
   Although June thunderstorms have alleviated what threatened to
be the worst drought on the Canadian prairies since 1937, many
areas remain parched.
</TEXT>
