<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-American     06-24 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-American,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Engineer Goes on Trial For Murder of Prostitute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American engineer went on trial Friday
for the murder of a Spanish prostitute last year, and he said he
remembered only punching her in the nose during an argument over
money.
   The prosecution said David Baxter of St. Louis, an engineer with
McDonnell Douglas Corp., smothered Rufina Sanz, a 35-year-old
Madrid prostitute, in his hotel room and mutilated her body on
March 3, 1987.
   Baxter, 30, came to Spain two days before the murder to work on
a joint McDonnell Douglas-Spanish government project set up in
1983, after Spain agreed to buy 72 F-18 fighter bombers from the
St. Louis-based company.
   A forensic report said Sanz died of asphyxiation from having a
foot pressed across her throat.
   The report also said she was beaten and disfigured with a knife
before being thrown from a window onto a cement patio.
   The prosecution cited psychiatric reports indicating Baxter
suffered from ``a psychosexual illness of a sadistic nature'' that
led him to commit the murder.
   The prosecution said it considered Baxter's illness an
``extenuating circumstance'' that kept it from seeking the maximum
penalty of a 30-year prison term. It asked for a 20-year prison
term in the event of conviction.
   Baxter's defense attorney, Julian Perez Templado, cited the same
psychosexual illness outlined in the reports as evidence his client
``could not be held responsible for his acts.''
   Baxter, dressed in a blue suit and handcuffed, testified he met
Sanz and returned with her to his hotel room after drinking at
several bars late on March 2, 1987.
   He said he hit her in the nose in his room after they argued
over the price he was to pay for sexual favors.
   Baxter said he could not remember what happened after that. He
said he only remembered waking up 1{ hours later, just before
police entered his room and arrested him.
   Police found a suitcase full of sadomasochistic sexual equipment
in Baxter's room, which the defendant identified as his property.
   As permitted by Spanish law, attorneys for the victim's family
asked for the three-judge tribunal to find Baxter guilty and
sentence him to 30 years in prison. They also asked he be ordered
to pay an indemnity of $127,000.
</TEXT>
