<HEAD>Federal Officials Return for Third Time to Evaluate Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials have returned for a
third time to evaluate damage caused by the May explosions at the
Pacific Engineering & Production Co. plant.
   Three structural engineers and five federal officials are
touring the areas hardest hit, checking with homeowners about
damage and insurance coverage.
   Federal Energy Management Agency officials were in Henderson
immediately after the explosion and again three weeks later.
Following the second inspection, FEMA recommended denial of federal
aid for losses suffered in the explosions.
   Gov. Richard Bryan appealed the decision, saying the FEMA teams
had missed certain uninsured structural damage. Henderson officials
estimate uninsured losses in the city at $20 million, up from $17
million previously reported.
   While federal officials were reassessing the damage Thursday,
Kerr-McGee Corp. was conducting a media tour of their plant two
miles from the site of the blast.
   Kerr-McGee resumed production of the rocket fuel oxidizer
ammonium perchlorate last week. Kerr-McGee and Pacific Engineering
were the only plants in the country producing the rocket fuel
component.
   Meanwhile, a House Science, Space and Technology subcommittee
arrived in Henderson on Thursday night and viewed the Pacific
Engineering site, then toured Kerr-McGee. Officials are concerned
about the loss of the ammonium perchlorate production since it is a
critical element in the space shuttle and military rocket fuels.
   The May 4 blast killed two people, injured 326 and caused $73
million in property damage.
</TEXT>
