<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1646EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WasteSite     06-24 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waste Site,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA To Relocate Residents On Waste Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has
recommended permanently relocating people living near a
``Superfund'' hazardous waste site for only the fourth time in the
nation and the first time in New England.
   There is no immediate health threat to the residents of a mobile
home park built on the site of the former dump, but the site is ``a
chemical time bomb that needs to be cleaned up,'' EPA deputy
regional administrator Paul Keough said Thursday.
   ``There are other sites that certainly rank high from a
potential pollution standpoint,'' said Mike Deland, an EPA regional
administrator. ``There is no other site in Vermont or New England
that has people living on top of it.''
   EPA remedial project site manager Paula Fitzsimmons said the two
main classes of hazardous chemicals in the dump are polychlorinated
byphenyls, or PCBs, which are suspected of causing cancer, and
polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons or PAHs, basically oil and
petroleum-based products.
   Keough said there was a significant long-term potential for air,
soil and leachate contamination if residents remained and the site
were not cleaned up.
   In addition, he said, the area posed a threat to residents who
might inadvertently dig up contaminated soil while planting a
garden, for example.
   Officials said they will hold public hearings on the cleanup
proposal, with relocation to begin after a final agreement is
signed, possibly in September.
   About 60 people live at the Springfield Mobile Estates park.
   ``Some really don't want to move _ they're most elderly,'' said
resident Christine Chapman. ``There are those who tried to sell and
couldn't a couple of years ago because nobody would buy it on top
of toxic waste site. They're relieved.''
   The EPA estimated the cost of the cleanup and relocation to be
at least $12.5 million and to take 2{ years.
   The site would be dug up, covered with a protective cap and
fenced off as soon as all residents are moved. Leachate or
contaminated groundwater would also be collected and treated.
   Officials said the site would be checked every five years for 30
years to determine if the cleanup technology is working.
   Although the PCBs were not dumped in bulk, the PAHs were dumped
by huge tankers. These and other wastes were left at site from 1946
to 1968.
</TEXT>
