<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbandonedTwins     06-24 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abandoned Twins,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Story About Twins' Plight Spawns Offerins of Money, Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twin brothers have been getting
offers of money, jobs and college tuition, but they fear publicity
about their plight could pose problems for the father who abandoned
them five years ago.
   When Tony and John Gomez were 9, their parents divorced and
their mother left. When they were 13, their father returned to
Guadalajara, Mexico, leaving the twins to fend for themselves.
   They worked odd jobs and managed to pay the rent on a trailer
while attending school. They told few people about the arrangement.
   This month, the twins, now 18, were graduated from high school.
   Since their story was publicized, ``it's been phenomenal,'' said
Karen G. Marshall, principal of Sierra High School where Tony was a
C-plus student.
   ``People want to give money. Other people are offering jobs.
They have offers to go to college, both to community colleges and
to Cal State,'' she said Thursday.
   But, she added: ``It's starting to concern them. They are
concerned it will get their father in trouble as more people get
interested. We've tried to reassure both of them that what happened
is in the past. No one will go back and no one will get in trouble
over anything.''
   John was at work Thursday, but Tony was visiting with Ms.
Marshall.
   ``I didn't know it was going to be this big,'' he said. ``I'm
surprised people do care and want to interview us and see if our
story is real.''
   Tony plans to join the Navy late this year or early next year.
After boot camp, he plans to marry his fiance, Tara Lyn Ramirez,
17, he said.
   As for John, ``Someone is paying for his tuition for four years
of college and I'm proud of that. He's on his way. He starts school
Monday at Valley (Community College), then he'll transfer to Cal
State after two years,'' Tony said.
   The twins have a 17-year-old sister living in San Bernardino who
has lived with foster parents since she was 13.
   Over the years, the hardest thing to do without, he said, was
``a parent being there to congratulate you for graduating or
getting an award or at Christmas or other holidays.''
   But, he added, ``My brother was always there. We were always
there for each other.''
</TEXT>
