<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Malta-Protest     06-24 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Malta-Protest,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Tow Away Tanker That Protesters Used to Block Harbor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tugboats carrying police and soldiers
towed a U.S.-registered oil tanker back to dockside Friday after
protesters had tried to use it to block visiting British warships.
   On Thursday, shipyard workers sympathetic to the opposition
Socialist Party towed the 80,000-ton Copper Mountain to the mouth
of Valletta's Grand Harbor and left it there.
   No crewmen were aboard the Copper Mountain at the time. The
vessel, identified as owned by the Point Vale company of Delaware,
had been in drydock for months while the shipyard awaited payment
for repairs.
   The Socialists oppose the warships' port call, scheduled for
Saturday, saying that three of the ships carry nuclear arms and
that the visit would violate the tiny Mediterranean island's policy
of neutrality and non-alignment.
   The General Workers Union of Malta, which backs the Socialists,
on Friday called a strike to protest the port call. The union
covers 7,000 employees in Malta's drydocks and shipbuilding areas
and some 2,000 in other sectors.
   The police who brought the tanker back to berth hired two
private tugs since pilots of the state-run tugboats refused to work
in protest of the British visit.
   The Maltese Parliament on Thursday approved a motion reaffirming
that nuclear arms should not be allowed on Maltese territory and
declaring that other nations should respect this policy.
   Earlier Thursday, in an effort to block the arrival of any
protesters' ships, the pro-West Nationalist government gave notice
that a specific port permit would be needed to enter the harbor
during the weekend.
   The ships, led by the aircraft carrier Ark Royal, were to stop
in Malta on their way to Australia for bicentennial celebrations in
the Commonwealth nation.
</TEXT>
