<DOCNO> AP880624-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1513EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TradeTalks Bjt   06-24 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Talks, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Negotiators Make Some Progress, But Not on Farm Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAINERD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and its major trading
partners remained far apart Friday on the contentious issue of farm
subsidies, but negotiators reported progress in other areas aimed
at reducing protectionist pressures.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said differences had
been narrowed in a number of areas, including the procedures to
expand the compact that governs world trade to include services and
investments, two areas not now covered.
   ``We haven't solved all of the problems, but we believe we have
come a long way in achieving consensus,'' Yeutter said.
   His remarks came at a news conference that closed the two days
of meetings involving trade ministers from the United States,
Japan, Canada and the 12-member European Community.
   The discussions were held as part of continuing negotiations to
expand and strengthen the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade,
known as GATT.
   The United States has made the elimination of all farm subsidies
by the year 2000 its major goal in the GATT talks, but President
Reagan faced stiff opposition when he discussed his proposal
earlier this week at the seven-nation economic summit in Toronto.
   The summit countries ended up directing their trade negotiators
to work harder to narrow their differences in preparation for a
critical meeting of all 96 member nations of GATT in Montreal in
December.
   The differences on farm subsidies are so great that the trade
negotiators did not even have the issue on their formal agenda for
the talks held at a resort in the lake country of Minnesota.
   But the issue did dominate discussions between the bargaining
sessions and over meals, even though no progress was made,
officials said.
   The U.S. proposal is opposed by the European Community and
Japan, which pay high subsidies to their farmers.
   Even though the major countries of the world are spending $200
billion annually in the costly subsidy battle, the Europeans and
Japanese say it is unrealistic to talk about a complete phaseout of
subsidies. They said the discussions should be focused on reducing
subsidies instead, perhaps by cutting them in half.
   Yeutter hinted that the administration might be willing to back
off its demand for total elimination of subsidies by the end of the
century in favor of a longer phaseout period, but he would not
publicly state what compromise the United States might offer.
   ``We are not moving off any options. Maybe in 1990 we will make
some adjustments, but not in 1988,'' he said. The year 1990 is when
the current GATT round of trade liberalization talks is scheduled
to be completed.
   Yeutter and the other trade ministers tried to be optimistic
that the farm battle could be resolved.
   ``If you want to make progress, you have to work hard and
consistently,'' said Willy de Clerq, trade minister for the
European Community.
   John Crosbie, Canada's trade minister, said the trade ministers
may get together again after the U.S. presidential election Nov. 8
but before the Montreal meeting in December to work on unresolved
issues such as agriculture.
   Yeutter said he was encouraged with the progres between
negotiators during the two days of talks. He said he believed a
number of contentious issues ahd been resolved which would insure
substantial progress would be made in Montreal.
   The ministers agreed in principle to a common position on
strengthening GATT's procedures for settling trade disputes between
nations by speeding up the process.
   Yeutter said progress was also made on another Reagan priority
to find methods to increase the unrestricted flow of investment
around the world as well as some progress in trying to draft rules
to cover trade in services.
   Yeutter said the services question was far from being totally
resolved because of the difficulty of deciding which of 150
different sectors, from telecommunications and banking to
construction and insurance, should be covered by the rules.
   This was the 14th bargaining session between the four sides,
which represent the biggest markets in world trade. At the talks,
which began in 1983, the participants try to reach agreement among
themselves and then sell their positions to the other 92 members of
the GATT organization.
   In a show of solidarity, all four trade ministers wore T-shirts
at the news conference emblazoned ``Think Big,'' the motto for the
conference, which was aimed at promoting a global view of trade and
combatting protectionist sentiments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Military     06-24 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Military,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Body to Discuss Military Ranks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of the National People's Congress
convenes Saturday to consider restoring military ranks abolished by
Mao Tse-tung more than 20 years ago.
   The weeklong session of the congress' Standing Committee also
will take up proposals to confer medals on retired soldiers, said
Zhang Husheng, director of the committee's information bureau.
   The National People's Congress is China's legislature.
   It is widely believed the army will formally reinstate ranks on
either Aug. 1, Army Day, or Oct. 1, National Day. Mao did away with
the titles in 1965 to create an egalitarian, proletarian army.
   Zhang spoke at the first news briefing ever held by the Standing
Committee. He said it was part of efforts to ``increase openness''
of government proceedings.
   The 155-member Standing Committee handles day-to-day affairs of
the 3,000-member congress, which meets once a year. The committee
is meeting for the second time since the congress held its 7th full
session in March.
   Zhang said the committee will study proposals submitted by the
Central Military Commission, headed by senior leader Deng Xiaoping,
on re-establishing the military rank system.
   The committee will also take up draft rules on defining the
roles of officers in the People's Liberation Army and will discuss
education.
   Zhang said ranks were ``conducive to commanding and control of
our army and required by modernization and standardization of our
army.''
   Deng has sought to bring back ranks to help create a more modern
and efficient fighting force. Since 1985 the army has been reduced
in size from 4 million to 3 million soldiers, and more effective
weaponry has been introduced.
   Although policies are still set by the ruling Communist Party,
the congress in recent years has become a forum for debate and
discussion of those policies.
   Zhang said the Standing Committee will hold news briefings once
every two months and will make the contents of its meetings as open
as possible.
   He said the committee also plans to set up a reception room
where ordinary congress members can express opinions. It will meet
in a larger room in the Great Hall of the People to accommodate
more non-voting members and a visitor's gallery, he said.
</TEXT>
