<HEAD>Guerrilla Incidents Kill 26; Dutch Woman Arrested For Rebel Links</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 26 people died in violence
related to communist rebels, and government troops arrested a Dutch
woman suspected of having links to the insurgents, the military
said Friday.
   Army Lt. Col. Rodolfo Lorayes said troops at a checkpoint
outside the southern town of Bayugan arrested Conny Tromp on
Thursday after she failed to produce proper identification papers.
He said Tromp, 22, showed only a photocopy of her visa, which
expired in April.
   The soldiers took the woman to army headquarters in the
provincial capital of Butuan for questioning.
   Bayugan is near a mountain boundary where communist New People's
Army rebels are known to operate. Col. Napoleon Deocariz, commander
of the army battalion in Butuan, said Tromp's presence in the area
was ``quite questionable.'' He said soldiers had reported seeing a
Caucasian at the scene of a nearby firefight recently.
   Tromp is the third foreigner arrested near a New People's Army
zone this month. On June 8, government soldiers arrested Swedish
national Stellan Hermansson and West German Protestant minister
Klaus Schmidt at a checkpoint in Quezon province for allegedly
aiding communist rebels in the area.
   In Manila late Thursday, government troops killed an alleged
communist rebel in a shootout in the suburban district of
Paranaque, the military said.
   Reynaldo Floriano, allegedly an NPA rebel facing three counts of
murder, drew his gun and fired on troops when they approached him,
a military report said. The troops fired back, killing Floriano,
the report said.
   In the southern province of Davao del Norte, rebels attacked a
paramilitary outpost and killed seven militiamen Thursday, the
military's Southern Command based on Mindanao island reported.
   Army soldiers who arrived to reinforce the detachment later
clashed with the same guerilla band in San Vicente town, leaving
six rebels dead. An army soldier was killed and four civilians
caught in cross fire were wounded in the incident, the military
said.
   Government troops killed three other rebels in a separate clash
in Misamis Occidental, also in Mindanao, the military said.
   On the central island of Bohol, guerillas were reported to have
killed eight people who refused to support the rebel movement, the
government-run Philippine News Agency said.
   The agency quoted the provincial commander of Bohol as saying
that guerrillas executed five people in Batuan town at dawn
Thursday.
   Twelve hours later, another group of rebels entered the house of
a former guerrilla supporter in Balilihan town and opened fire on
its occupants, killing three people and wounding six, the news
agency said.
</TEXT>
