<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   06-24 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0680 to fix slug line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arafat's Foes Shell Beirut Camps, 10 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-backed guerrillas on Friday
bombarded Yasser Arafat's loyalists in a bloody struggle for
control of two Palestinian refugee camps. Police said 10 people
were killed and 34 wounded.
   At one point, police said five shells a minute were hitting the
Chatilla refugee camp as Col. Saeed Mousa's radical Fatah-Uprising
tried to crush Arafat's Fatah guerrillas. They said Chatilla's only
hospital was hit dozens of times.
   A Fatah spokesman charged that Mousa's fighters ``started
shelling the camps indiscriminately'' to sabotage mediation efforts
by Libyan officials. ``They are massacring our people,'' said the
Fatah spokesman, who refused to be named.
   A truce announced in Tripoli on Thursday called for the warring
factions to return to positions they held before fighting broke out
May 1 in Chatilla and the nearby Bourj el-Barajneh camp. It was
reached in a meeting between Libyan officers and representatives of
neutral Palestinian groups.
   Since May 1, 112 people have been killed and 502 wounded in the
fight for control of the refugee camps on Beirut's southern
outskirts.
   A Palestinian official said Mousa's gunners used 240mm mortars
to shell Chatilla, the first time they have used the heavy weapons
in the fighting.
   The official quoted a doctor in Chatilla as saying most of the
hospital's medical and surgical equipment were damaged.
   ``We're crippled. We don't have the means to carry out even
minor operations. Even oxygen bottles and gauze supplies have been
blown up,'' the official quoted the doctor as saying.
   Fatah-Uprising said in a statement that Arafat provoked the
clashes to ``sabotage Syria's role in Lebanon ... in order to be
accepted in the American-Zionist arrangements.''
   Syria has 7,500 troops deployed in west Beirut to control
unrest. Last month, Syria sent 2,400 troops into south Beirut to
end a bloodbath between the Shiite Moslem militias Amal and
Hezbollah. At least 300 people died in the battle for control of
the southern slums, where Western hostages are believed held by
factions of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah.
   Mortar rounds and rockets fired by Fatah-Uprising gunners were
raining down on the camps at a rate of five a minute around dawn, a
police spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations,
said Fatah defenders entrenched in the rubble of the two
shantytowns responded with heavy weapons fire.
   The fighting raged through the day as smoke from burning
buildings billowed over the camps. Ambulances evacuated the wounded
to hospitals in west Beirut.
   Fatah, the main component of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, pushed Mousa's followers out of the camps in earlier
fighting.
   The dissidents, regrouped along the Syrian-controlled edges of
the shantytowns, have launched several abortive attacks in an
attempt to regain their lost bases.
   The police spokesman said Mousa's gunners concentrated their
shelling on the tiny Chatilla camp.
   ``They hammered Chatilla all day. They're turning what's left of
the camp into a pile of rubble,'' he said.
   The camps have been badly damaged by fighting that began when
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982 and besieged west Beirut and the
camps in an attempt to drive out Palestinian guerrillas.
   Pro-Israeli Christian Lebanese militiamen massacred hundreds of
civilians in Chatilla and the nearby Sabra camp in September 1982.
   Syrian-backed Shiite Moslems besieged the Beirut camps in 1985,
pounding them for more than two years in an abortive effort to
prevent Arafat from rebuilding the power base he lost when the
Israelis invaded.
   What was left of Sabra was bulldozed by the Shiites, but
Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh held out until the Shiites lifted
their siege.
   Mousa broke away from the PLO in 1983 in a Syrian-backed mutiny
by radicals opposed to Arafat. The latest fighting came despite a
reconciliation between Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad in
Damascus last April to end their five-year feud over who would
control the Palestinian movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
