<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1820EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATOTroops     06-24 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO Troops,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allies Reach Agreement On Units To Defend Norway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO agreed Friday to create a
multinational army unit to replace a 5,000-man Canadian air and sea
brigade that had been earmarked to reinforce northern Norway in
times of crisis.
   The decision caps a year of study and internal NATO controversy
about how to respond to the disbanding of the Canadian Air-Sea
Transportable brigade, which had been committed to Norway for 19
years.
   The Norwegian government had criticized the Canadian move,
saying failure to replace the brigade would weaken the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's ability to stop attacks on its
northern flank.
   Canada said in June 1987 it would offset the move by adding to
its forces in West Germany.
   The alliance's Defense Planning Committee adopted outlines of a
plan for creating an army unit of U.S., West German and Canadian
troops that would be designated as early reinforcements for Norway
in times of tension.
   A NATO announcement said Gen. John R. Galvin, the chief
commander of alliance forces in Europe, was negotiating terms of a
``composite force'' for Norway. It said details would be worked out
later.
   ``This will enhance NATO's overall deterrence in a time of
tension ... demonstrate alliance solidarity and reinforce the
defense of this vitally important region in a crisis,'' the
announcement said.
   The problem of reinforcing northern Norway stems from the Oslo
government's long-standing policy of prohibiting the stationing of
foreign troops on its soil in peacetime. It also prohibits alliance
military maneuvers in the northern Finnmark county that borders the
Soviet Union.
   In Oslo, Prime Minister Gro Harlem Bruntland told a news
conference Friday she was pleased with the alliance decision.
   ``The outlined solution represents a net strengthening of the
allied contribution to the defense of Norway,'' she said.
   Norway's concern about the withdrawal of the Canadian force has
been heightened by its fear of growing superpower military strength
in the north.
   Besides Turkey, Norway is the only NATO member to share a border
with the Soviet Union.
   A 13,000-man U.S. Marine amphibious brigade and a 5,000-man
Dutch-British landing force already are committed to reinforcing
central Norway in wartime.
   When the possibility of West German troops being included in a
replacement unit for the Canadian brigade first was raised publicly
last fall, some Norwegian press reaction was negative.
   Nazi troops occupied northern Norway for five years and
destroyed many villages and factories before withdrawing in May
1945. Resentment is still evident in some parts of the sparsely
populated north.
   The day after a foreign press report in September 1987 said
German combat troops could be returning to northern Norway for the
first time, Norway's most widely read newspaper, Verdens Gang, ran
a photograph of a column of German soldiers above the headline,
``Unwelcome in Norway.''
   Government officials have never suggested they would not accept
a German contingent in a new multinational reinforcement unit. In
March, Defense Minister Johan Joergen Holst called German
participation ``welcome.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0187 </DOCNO>
