<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-24 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLIANCE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Reinders is completing ``Carhenge,''
his replica of England's Stonehenge made of old cars welded
together in a field.
   Reinders said Thursday he has spent nearly $10,000 on the
project.
   Reinders, 60, a retired oil consultant who lives in Houston,
added 10 cars this week to the 22-car sculpture he erected last
summer on U.S. 385 north of Alliance.
   ``I'd be hard pressed to explain why all of the excitement about
Carhenge,'' Reinders said. ``Something about this is imaginative.
People see it as creative, unique, and novelty, but art _ I don't
know.''
   Reinders said that he talked to a couple who said they saw a UFO
land in the center of Carhenge.
   ``If Stonehenge has some purpose, then I think Carhenge has some
purpose,'' Reinders said. ``I was hoping UFOs would see and
recognize it as a possible landing strip. If these people saw it,
then I can only hope it was true. I wasn't here.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SHELBY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles and Sandy Goldthrite have learned
the value of homework.
   About 2{ years ago they paid $4 for a glass paperweight at a
yard sale.
   This week, Sotheby's auction house sold it for $8,250, meaning a
nice tidy $7,500 for the Goldthrites.
   ``We'd been reading up on French paperweights,'' Mrs. Goldthrite
said Thursday. ``We thought it might have been one of those.''
   It wasn't. But the 4-inch-long, cornucopia-style paperweight was
made in New England about 1860.
   The Goldthrites, who operate a booth at the Shelby Antiques
Mall, say they'll keep following a strategy that pays _ Saturday
yard sales.
   ``We start out at 6 a.m. and go straight through noon,'' Mrs.
Goldthrite said. ``We hit them all. Maybe we'll get lucky again.''
</TEXT>
