<HEAD>Sheriff's Deputy Gives Escapee Free Ride</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMYRA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's deputy who gave a fast-talking
jail escapee a ride across the state line has been suspended, the
sheriff said.
   ``There will be disciplinary action on this matter,'' Marion
County Sheriff Dan Campbell said Thursday.
   James Ellis Wofford, 21, of Hannibal, was still at large after
getting a ride to Quincy, Ill., from Deputy Harold Lee, Campbell
said.
   Wofford was being held on charges of passing a bad check and
tampering with a vehicle when he escaped from the county jail in
Palmyra Wednesday. When his escape was discovered, his description
was broadcast to deputies and other authorities, Campbell said.
   Lee reported seeing a man walking along U.S. 24 on Thursday,
Campbell said. The man's clothing, except for the color of his
shirt, matched the description of the escaped prisoner, Lee told
Campbell.
   ``He expected the suspect to run, but the guy didn't run. He
just walked back to the officer's car,'' Campbell said. ``The
suspect said, `I've been walking half the night.' He said he missed
his ride in Hannibal and was en route to Quincy. He said his family
would be worried about him.''
   Lee believed the hitchhiker's story and gave him a ride to
Quincy, the sheriff said.
   When they arrived, Lee told Campbell, it became apparent that
the man wasn't sure what house he was looking for.
   ``At that time, Lee attempted to secure him inside the
vehicle,'' Campbell said. ``They struggled inside the vehicle and
the suspect was able to get free.''
