<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     06-24 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bradley Apparently Doesn't Want No. 2 Spot on Ticket, Dukakis Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANTUCKET, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis all but ruled
out Bill Bradley as a prospective running mate on Friday, saying
the New Jersey senator had told the campaign he wasn't interested,
and adding ``I respect that.''
   Beginning a four-day vacation at a borrowed vacation home on
Nantucket Island, Dukakis said Bradley had told Paul Brountas, the
Dukakis senior adviser who is leading his search for vice
presidential candidate, that he ``apparently'' wasn't interested.
   ``In any event, we're going to keep in touch,'' Dukakis said.
   He said rival Jesse Jackson, reported to have said privately he
would turn down the vice presidential nomination, had not sent that
word to the Dukakis campaign.
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' he said of the Jackson
report in The Boston Globe, which was attributed to unnamed sources.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor who is awaiting the
presidential nomination at the Democratic National Convention next
month, said that if any of the prospective vice presidential
candidates ruled themselves out ``clearly and unequivocally, to me,
then obviously I'm not going to press the point.''
   ``I might push a little bit if somebody seemed to me to be a
good prospect,'' he said. ``But if they came back and said, `Look,
we've thought about it. We decided this isn't the time _ '''
   He was asked if that was the case with Bradley, a senator who
has campaigned with Dukakis and is clearly a personal favorite of
the governor.
   ``Well, apparently so,'' he said. ``We haven't talked personally
about it. ... He's somebody I have a lot of respect for. Apparently
he said that to Paul, and I respect that.''
   Dukakis flew to Nantucket Island off Cape Cod with his wife,
Kitty. He said he plans to read and relax over the weekend before
returning to Boston on Monday evening.
   Mrs. Dukakis is recovering from spinal surgery she underwent
three weeks ago. She wore a plum-colored scarf around a neck brace
when she and her husband appeared before reporters and
photographers on the lawn of the picturesque home where they are
staying. She took off her neck brace briefly to show the scar left
by the operation.
   ``Want to see my scar?'' she said, drawing laughs from the crowd
of reporters.
   The couple is staying at a brown, wood-frame Colonial home
overlooking an inlet off Nantucket Harbor. The home, where the
Dukakises have stayed before, is situated up a tree-lined drive and
not visible from the road.
   The home is owned by Bernard and Grace Grossman, famiily friends
for some 20 years. Bernard Grossman is a former executive of a
well-known Boston-area lumber company.
   Unlike Repulican nominee-to-be George Bush, who owns a shoreside
family estate at Kennebunkport, Maine, Dukakis owns no vacation
home.
   The governor relaxed on a lounge chair, while wearing a cotton
sweater, pants and deck shoes without socks. Rarely is he seen in
public without his usual attire: a suit and black wing-tipped shoes.
   ``It's an incredible place,'' he said, looking at the view and
recalling that he and Kitty came to Nantucket on their honeymoonn
25 years ago. ``We've been coming back ever since.''
   He said it was to Nantucket that they came in the fall of 1978
after he lost a bid for re-election ``to heal our wounds.''
   He said this time he brought two bags of reading material and
planned to spend his four days reading and walking.
   He had little to say about the series of events that buffeted
his campaign over the past several days, including the disclosure
that the FBI is conducting a preliminary inquiry into the state's
decision to locate a new prison on land owned by longtime
acquaintances of the governor. He said he planned no investigation
of the case by the governor's office.
   He again defended his decision to sign a bill imposing a 5
percent increase in the state tax on cigarettes as a move to
counter the state revenue shortfall, pointing to previous tax cuts.
   ``We've run into this rather modest shortfall and when you do
that you have to respond to it,'' he said.
   Dukakis provided little insight to his vice presidential
deliberations beyond his comments on Bradley. ``There's no list,''
he said. ``We're trying to expand the circle as broadly as
possible.''
   Aides said he planned no meetings or serious discussions on the
vice presidential choice during his vacation. Brountas did not
accompany him to the island, and campaign manager Susan Estrich
flew home to Los Angeles for the weekend.
</TEXT>
