<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Diplomat,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Nominates New Ambassador to Chad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Friday announced his
intention to nominate Robert L. Pugh, a career Foreign Service
officer, to be ambassador to the Republic of Chad.
   Pugh, 56, will succeed John Blane, if confirmed by the Senate.
   Pugh entered the Foreign Service in 1961 and served as an
international economist at the State Department from 1961-63. He
served as political-military officer in Ankara, Turkey, from
1964-67 and as principal officer of the American consulate in
Isfahan from 1967-69.
   More recently, Pugh was deputy chief of mission at the U.S.
Embassy in Beirut from 1982-84. Since 1985 he has been U.S.
ambassador to the Islamic Republic of Mauritania.
   Pugh graduated from the University of Washington in 1954 and
served in the U.S. Marine Corps from 1954-61.
