<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     06-24 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extremists Gun Down 12 in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists shot to death 12 people
in attacks across Punjab state, including a Sikh boy and two Hindu
priests, the United News of India reported Friday.
   A Hindu businessman, Prem Chand Aggarwal, was robbed and killed
by Sikh gunmen Friday in Batala town in Gurdaspur district, a major
stronghold of Sikh terrorists.
   UNI said that a 13-year-old Sikh boy, Jaswant Singh, was killed
in Amritsar by Sikh extremists. A woman also was killed in Amritsar.
   Sikh separatists shot and killed two Hindu priests in Hoshiarpur
district Thursday night, UNI said. The victims were identified as
Charan Singh and Ram Lal.
   Two policemen were killed by Sikh radicals in Asur village in
Amritsar district late Thursday, UNI said.
   Another police constable was killed after he chased a gang of
militants in Ludhiana city. Another policeman was seriously injured.
   Three other Sikhs and a Hindu also were killed in separate
attacks, UNI said.
   In addition, a person injured in a bomb explosion in Amritsar on
Tuesday died of his injuries, UNI said. That raised the death toll
from the bomb blast to 26. Police said Sikh militants planted the
bomb.
   According to police figures, the deaths raised to 1,389 the
number of people killed in Punjab this year by Sikh militants
fighting for a separate homeland in the northern state.
   Sikhs are 2 percent of India's 800 million people and claim they
are discriminated against by the majority Hindus. Sikhs are a
majority in Punjab.
   Most victims of Sikh violence are Hindus, but militants also
target moderate Sikhs who don't support their cause.
</TEXT>
