<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Strike,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Base Workers End Monthlong Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek workers at a U.S. air base on this
southern island ended a monthlong strike Friday, a union
representative said.
   The 250 workers walked off the job May 23 to press for a 15
percent pay increase and special allowances from their employers,
Pacific Architects and Engineers.
   The strike at the Gournes Air Base, 10 miles outside the city of
Heraklion on the island's northern coast, affected the delivery of
food, fuel and water to the installation, the U.S. Air Force said.
   ``The Greek Labor Ministry said they would give us special
allowances that equal the 15 percent pay hike we wanted. But it
doesn't mean we are happy,'' said the union representative,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the California-based firm, which employs truck drivers
and operates power, water and sewage plants on the base, has not
agreed to sign a collective wage agreement with the workers.
   ``We might go on strike again if they don't sign,'' he added.
   No representatives of the private U.S. firm were available for
comment.
   Gournes, a communications monitoring base, is one of four
American installations that has been operating in Greece since the
early 1950s
   There is a U.S. Sixth Fleet supply base in Souda Bay, Crete, and
two more installations near Athens _ an Air Force support base
adjacent to Athens airport and a Navy communications base 22 miles
east of the city.
</TEXT>
