<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-USBases     06-24 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US Bases,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators End Another Round of Bases Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and American negotiators ended their
seventh round of talks on an agreement for U.S. military bases
without any significant progress, officials said Friday.
   ``There still continues to be a difference of views on the
issues being discussed,'' government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos
said.
   The negotiations ended Thursday, a day earlier than scheduled
because the Greek negotiators had previous commitments, Kostopoulos
said.
   The talks, which began in November 1987, are on the renewal of a
five-year operating agreement for four U.S. bases. The accord
expires December 31, 1988.
   Greece has said a new agreement must be linked to American help
with ``national interests,'' a reference to Greece's longstanding
disputes with Turkey.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz said last week that he
believed the negotiations would be ``resolved satisfactorily.''
   The next round of talks will take place at the end of July,
Kostopoulos said. He didn't specify the date.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist government is expected to
give the United States a formal notice in July on closing the bases.
   Such a notice has to be issued five months before the accord
expires. It is not expected to result in closure of the bases.
   Four U.S. military bases have been operating in Greece since the
early 1950s _ two near Athens and two on the southern island of
Crete.
</TEXT>
