<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Meglin     06-24 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Meglin,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dance Teacher to Judy Garland and Mickey Rooney Dies at Age 98</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANA POINT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethel Meglin, a dance teacher who
helped nurture the childhood careers of Judy Garland, Mickey Rooney
and Shirley Temple, has died. She was 98.
   Mrs. Meglin died Tuesday at her home in this seaside community
55 miles southeast of Los Angeles, said her daughter, Marilyn Peitz.
   Mrs. Meglin was president of Ethel Meglin Dance Studios Inc. and
founder of the Meglin Kiddies, a group of child performers who
included Ann Miller, Gwen Verdon, Jane Withers, June Lang and
Rooney. Judy Garland joined the school in 1927 and Shirley Temple
in 1931.
   ``It gave them the talent and the incentive to continue on and
decide whether they wanted to be an actor, actress or dancer. It
gave them an interest in pursuing a career in the theatrical
world,'' said Miss Lang.
   A former dancer with the Ziegfeld Follies in New York, Mrs.
Meglin began teaching after she and her husband, Richard, moved to
California. As her reputation grew, her school became the largest
of its kind, with 52 franchises across the United States.
   The Meglin Kiddies sang on local radio stations and appeared in
several movies, including ``An American in Paris'' with Gene Kelly
and in the early 1950s, on Mrs. Meglin's local television show,
``The Meglin Review.''
   The last Meglin Studio, in Hollywood, closed in 1963 after the
death of Richard Meglin. Mrs. Meglin retired because of illness.
   She is survived by her daughter. A funeral Mass is scheduled
Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
