<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     06-24 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Government, Public Office Changes Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership's nominee for president
is not a Communist Party member for the first time since the party
took power in 1948, informed sources said Friday.
   A communique Friday from the party Central Committee did not say
Bruno F. Straub is not a party member but the sources confirmed it
on condition their names not be revealed.
   The Central Committee named Straub, 74, a biochemist and member
of Parliament, on Thursday to replace Karoly Nemeth, 67. Its
decision adds to the radical change under way in Hungary, whose
leaders say they want to reform political and economic life.
   Nemeth, officially on sick leave from the ceremonial post since
June 1, was dropped May 22 from the Politburo and the Central
Committee.
   Straub will leave his post as chairman of the parliamentary
committee on regional development and environmental protection,
said the committee statement, carried by the official news agency
MTI. It also announced new ministers of culture and justice, a new
Parliament speaker and other new officials.
   Parliament is to meet next week to approve the changes.
   Politburo member Janos Berecz called Straub, who specializes in
enzyme research and is a member of the Hungarian Academy of
Sciences, ``an outstanding intellectual.''
   Berecz also said the Central Committee proposed that Imre
Pozsgay, a leading reform advocate, be reassigned as a minister
without portfolio.
   Bela Koepeczi, the veteran culture minister, is to retire and be
replaced by Tibor Czere, a professor at the University of Heavy
Industry of Miskolc, an industrial town in northern Hungary.
   Justice Minister Imre Markoja, 57, will be replaced by Kalman
Kulcsar, deputy secretary-general of the Hungarian Academy of
Sciences.
   Istvan Staudinger, a Budapest city official, is to become the
speaker of Parliament, taking over from Istvan Sarlos, 67.
   Sandor Gaspar, who has been dropped from the Politburo and
ousted as trade union boss, will lose the vice presidency, his last
public post. Sarlos will get the job.
   Karoly Grosz, premier and Communist Party chief, will visit
Moscow in July, the Soviet news agency Tass reported. Grosz, 57,
replaced Janos Kadar as party leader May 22 at the end of a
three-day party conference in Budapest.
</TEXT>
