<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghan     06-24 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Fire Rockets into Kabul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's communist
government fired rockets into Kabul on Friday, wounding people,
destroying buildings and starting a large fire at the airport, the
official news agency Tass reported.
   It did not say how many people were wounded in the Afghan
capital or whether any were killed. The dispatch said firefighters
took two hours to put out the airport blaze, but did not say
whether aircraft were damaged or destroyed.
   Afghan soldiers were on alert, taking ``special measures to
eliminate the forces that fired at Kabul,'' the agency said.
   Life in Kabul was normal despite clouds of smoke over the
airfield, Tass said, reporting that downtown streets were crowded
and trade was brisk at the public market.
   The Red Army is withdrawing its estimated 115,000 soldiers from
Afghanistan under an agreement signed April 14 in Geneva, but the
Moslem insurgents were not a party to the pact and have continued
fighting.
   Guerrilla war began after a communist coup in April 1978 and
Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979. The
Soviet withdrawal began May 15 and is to be completed in nine
months.
</TEXT>
