<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LibelTrial     06-24 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libel Trial,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Hears Case Of Williamsburg Editor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has heard the case of a
newspaper editor accused of criminally libeling two state
legislators in an editorial, but announced no decision.
   Williamsburg County Court officials said a decision about the
charges against editor Jim Fitts will be announced when the next
session of court begins Monday, which is the usual procedure.
   State Rep. B.J. Gordon and an attorney for fellow plaintiff
state Sen. Frank McGill, who is recovering from cancer treatment,
would not comment on their 30-minute appearance before the grand
jury Thursday.
   Gordon did, however, disagree with civil libertarians who have
said the state's criminal libel law is outdated: ``If it's
outdated, then the Ten Commandments are outdated.''
   The case has drawn interest because criminal libel laws _ which
can send journalists to jail _ are unusual in the United States.
Critics say they can be used to stifle free-flowing political
debate.
   The charge carries a penalty of up to $5,000 in fines or a year
in jail or both.
   Only four times in 40 years has the law has been used in South
Carolina. Similar laws exist but are rarely used in 23 other states
and the District of Columbia, said Jane Kirtley, executive director
of the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press in Washington,
D.C.
   ``I think that criminal libel laws are a relic of the past,''
Ms. Kirtley said. ``It seems to me that punishing people for
speaking is not an American concept.''
   Fitts was arrested and jailed May 20 on the charge of criminal
libel after he wrote a column critical of Gordon, McGill and their
re-election bids in the June 14 primaries, which both men won.
   In his column in the May 17 issue of The Voice, a black-oriented
newspaper with a circulation of about 2,300, Fitts wrote in part:
``I will say to you without fear of contradiction, if every black
in Williamsburg County would start stealing today and steal every
day for the rest of their lives, they could not steal as much as
those two have stolen during their time in power.''
   Fitts would not be specific Thursday when asked what he thought
the two men had stolen, other than to say he thought they had
stolen the pride of people in Williamsburg County.
   And he said the issue was economic, not racial. Fitts and Gordon
are black. McGill is white.
   Neither Gordon nor McGill's attorney, Kingstree lawyer Wallace
Connor, would say whether would consider settling out of court.
   Both said the law was necessary because civil suits are often
uncollectable because of the defendant's inability to pay. And as
long as the law is on the books, it should be obeyed, they said.
   Fitts said McGill and Gordon represent the haves in the county
who oppress the have-nots.
   ``It's not a racial issue,'' he said. ``I'm just challenging a
sytem that has been programmed for years to control the people.''
   Gordon's response was to note that he's been elected to office
for nine consecutive terms.
   Fitts' bond initially was set at $40,000. After two days in
jail, he was released May 22 on a personal recognizance bond.
   Gordon said Thursday his intent was not to silence the press,
but to make sure the law was obeyed.
   ``Freedom of the press is not to go around with freedom and
accuse people of commiting crimes,'' he said. ``That is not freedom
of the press.''
   Despite the pending charges, Fitts continued speaking out
Thursday, and said McGill and Gordon intended to quiet his
outspokenness.
   ``I think the intent was to silence me,'' Fitts said, but he
added that the effort is unsuccessful. ``I can't stop telling the
truth.''
   Gordon said he was secure in the decision to press charges.
   ``Have I done the right thing? It's not what I did,'' Gordon
said. ``My conscience is clear.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     06-24 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviets,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Demands Property In Jerusalem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union claims an Israeli hotel built
an access road on Soviet-owned property in downtown Jerusalem and
is suing it for tresspassing, an attorney said Friday.
   It was the first property suit brought by a Soviet consular
delegation that arrived in Israel last summer after a 20 years of
minimal contact between the two countries. The Soviet Union broke
diplomatic relations during the 1967 Middle East war.
   Israeli officials say they are willing to negotiate the Soviet
claims and hope the talks will not disrupt what they see as a thaw
in Soviet-Israeli relations.
   The disputed property is a parking lot near the Tirat Bat Sheva
Hotel on King George Street, said Yacov Miron, an Israeli attorney
for the Soviet delegation.
   ``The area is registered as a Soviet government property and we
demand it back,'' Miron told The Associated Press.
   Most of the Soviet property in Israel was bought in the 19th
century by the Russian Orthodox Church or by government-affiliated
bodies of imperial Russia.
   Last July, the Soviet Union sent the eight-member consular team
to Israel to examine property holdings and renew passports for the
estimated 2,500 Soviet passport holders here.
   Israel has demanded a reciprocal visit by an Israeli delegation
to Moscow. Earlier this month, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze said the Israeli delegation would receive visas in
July.
   Two weeks ago, Soviet delegation head Georgy Martirosov informed
Israel's Foreign Ministry it had completed a survey of Soviet
property being used by Israel.
   The ministry said the Soviets were expected to present demands
for rental payments.
   Miron said the parking lot was registered in the name of the
Soviet government in 1949 after Israel was created.
   ``The area was first seized by the Jerusalem municipality, which
turned it into a municipal parking lot,'' he said. ``Then the hotel
made a access road through it.''
   According to the Israeli news agency Itim, the hotel is using
some 200 square yards of the area. Hotel officials refused comment.
   Miron said the complaint followed letters sent to the hotel and
the Jerusalem municipality which demanded evacuation of the area.
He said the municipality had not responded.
   In the complaint, which was filed Thursday, the Soviets demand
the parking lot be evacuated.
   Miron said other property claims may follow but did not
elaborate. He declined to say what the Soviets intended to do if
they got the area back.
   ``They just want it back,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalMoney     06-24 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Money,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Making Fund-Raising Comeback, While GOP Fortunes Slump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fortunes of the Republican Party have been
in a slump while the Democrats, still lagging far behind in overall
dollars, inch their way up the fund-raising laddder, Federal
Election Commission figures showed Friday.
   The FEC summary of 15-month totals for this election cycle
through March 31 showed the three national-level Republican
committees had raised $97 million, compared with $127 million at
the same point in 1986, $137 million in 1984 and $116 million in
1982.
   The Democrats, meanwhile, have raised a total of $29 million in
this cycle, compared with $24 million in 1986, $37 million in 1984
and $13 million in 1982. The figures are based on committee reports
to the FEC and do not include so-called soft money that the parties
raise for non-federal campaign spending.
   Kathryn Murray, communications director of the Republican
National Committee, acknowledged Friday that the RNC hit a rough
stretch in 1987. But she said the committee already has turned the
corner to move back into bonanza fund-raising days _ although not
on a par with the 1984 election cycle when President Reagan ran for
re-election.
   ``We're sure (Democratic National Committee Chairman) Paul Kirk
would change checkbooks with us any day,'' she said, adding that
she expects the second quarter of this year to come it at over $10
million.
   While still not as strong as the $15 million during the same
period in 1984, that will top any other RNC second quarter, she
said.
   When broken down by committee, the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee and Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
both have shown steady growth over the years, while their
Republican counterparts have lagged.
   The reason the overall Democratic total is lower in this cycle
than in the 1984 presidential year is due to the drop in receipts
to the Democratic National Committee between 1984 and 1986.
   In 1984, the DNC had collected $26 million in the first 15
months of the cycle. In 1986 receipts dropped to less than $11
million at the same point, and this year are back up to nearly $13
million, the FEC report shows.
   The Democrats now are carrying a total debt of $3.7 million
compared with less than $1 million for the GOP.
   DNC spokesman Mike McCurry said the Democrats are pleased with
their progress this year, even the FEC numbers show the 15-month
DNC receipts are only half what they were in 1984.
   ``The party going into this general election cycle is in a
strong financial position, rather than trying to play catch up,''
as in past years, he said.
   The RNC's Murray said GOP hopes have been stirred by the fact
that the first quarter of 1988 brought in $12.6 million, almost as
good as the $13 million in 1986. The $17 million raised during the
same period of 1984 was an aberration that showed Reagan's
extraordinary popularity, she said.
   Generally, the RNC and DNC have their biggest fund-raising
successes in presidential years, while the senatorial and
congressional committees are active in the off-year congressional
races.
   In total contributions and support of congressional candidates,
the Democratic committees spent $1.2 million as of March 31,
compared with $744,186 spent by the Republicans.
   The disparity was most notable in the war for the U.S. Senate
where the Democrats have considerably fewer resources but spent
more in support of their candidates than the Republicans.
   For campaign costs paid directly by a national committee rather
than by a candidate's own campaign, the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee spent $420,173 on its candidates as of March 31,
compared with $2,814 spent by its GOP counterpart, the FEC data
showed.
   Tom Mason, spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial
Committee, acknowledged serious fund-raising problems over the past
several months, and said the committee's ill fortunes were not a
surprise.
   After the 1986 elections, when the Republicans gave up control
of the Senate by losing nine seats, enthusiasm among GOP
contributors waned, he said.
   He said the presidential campaign also has drained away
potential donors to Senate races.
   Mason tried to put a good face on the financial picture,
however, saying that while gross intake is down, the net money
available to help candidates has improved in recent years because
the NRSC has ``taken a sharper pencil to the cost of fund-raising.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ManassasBattlefield     06-24 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manassas Battlefield,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warner Vows To Push For Plan To Offset Impact Of Shopping Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan by Sen. John Warner, R-Va., to close
roads through the Manassas National Battlefield Park was killed by
a Senate panel Friday, but Warner vowed to revive the plan in talks
with House members.
   ``I'm going to do my best to try and go forward with planning
roads,'' Warner said after the Senate Appropriations Committee
rejected his request for $2.8 million to study ways to cut off two
heavily traveled roads that run through the historic Civil War
battlefield.
   Warner's compromise plan, which is similar to a previous
Interior Department proposal, is part of a federal effort to reduce
the impact of a proposed 1.2 million square foot shopping center on
the nearby national park.
   Warner does not oppose the commercial complex, but believes that
closing roads within the park would lessen the development's impact
on the battleground.
   Historians and preservationists argue that the complex, which
also would include 1.7 million square feet of office space and 560
homes, would forever violate the sanctity of the still-rustic
battlefield.
   Three measures now under consideration in the House would either
authorize the federal government to purchase the land or scuttle
the shopping center plan by preventing federal highway money from
being used for roads to and from the development.
   Before Warner's plan can again be considered, an amendment that
would prevent federal money from being used for highway
construction associated with the development must be dropped from a
House appropriations bill.
   Congressional rules stipulate that if that amendment, offered by
Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., Warner's amendment could then be
reconsidered in future talks between House and Senate conferees.
   Mrazek is not likely to drop his amendment, at least until the
outcome of the land-purchase bills is clear, said Tad Boggs, a
spokesman for the congressman.
   Plans to purchase the property offered by Rep. Frank Wolf,
R-Va., and a similar measure by Mrazek and Rep. Michael Andrews,
D-Texas, would also close two roads running through the park and
build new roads around it.
   Buying the 542-acre development site and adding it to the
4,600-acre battlefield park is not an option, at least in the
Senate, Warner said.
   The mall site is currently valued at $13.5 million, but the
ultimate selling price would likely be three times higher _ a
figure approaching the federal government's annual appropriation
for park purchases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
