<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-PeacePlan     06-24 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Peace Plan,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central American Presidents Plan to Meet in El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If President Jose Napoleon
Duarte's health permits, he and four other Central American
presidents will meet here for the anniversary of the regional peace
plan, the government said Friday.
   Foreign Minister Ricardo Acevedo Peralta said President Oscar
Arias of Costa Rica, author of the peace accord, suggested the
two-day August summit be held in San Salvador in deference to
Duarte, who has terminal liver cancer.
   ``We have accepted in principle, depending on the health of
President Duarte,'' Acevedo told a news conference.
   The presidents of Guatemala, El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras
and Costa Rica signed the agreement Aug. 7, 1987 in Esquipulas,
Guatemala. It led to a truce in Nicaragua but has not ended civil
wars in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Duarte has been undergoing treatment since May 31 at Walter Reed
Army Medical Center in Washington. He is to come home in next
month, but to return to the hospital in August.
   Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount said: ``I thanked
President Arias for the gesture and told him we were honored, but
no one knows what the state of President Duarte's health will be.
It is so speculative that I also said an alternative site for the
meeting should be sought.''
</TEXT>
