<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria-Waste 1stLd-Writethru a0624 06-24 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria-Waste, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nigeria Sets Up Vigilante Groups To Monitor Toxic Waste</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout, Italy offers to remove waste, Liberia
reports dumping offer. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nigeria has posted vigilante groups
at ports and jetties to prevent foreign ships from dumping toxic
waste in that West African country, its state radio reported.
   In Rome, the Italian government said Friday it has offered to
arrange for removal of a shipload of waste dumped in Nigeria by an
Italian company.
   Liberia's health minister reported receiving three requests from
companies in industrialized nations to dump toxic waste there.
Several West African nations have reported approaches by American
and European companies offering millions of dollars to use them as
dumping grounds.
   Nigeria radio, monitored in Abidjan, said the vigilantes were
posted to protect the population from poisonous and radioactive
wastes.
   It made the report Thursday as U.S. experts tested barrels of
waste that were part of a 2,000-ton load dumped near Koko, a town
150 miles southeast of Lagos, by an Italian firm allegedly acting
for 10 European companies.
   Nigeria has recalled its ambassador to Italy, seized an Italian
ship and ordered its crew to remove the waste.
   The military government also arrested 15 people, including
several Italians, and said anyone found guilty of links to the
dumping risks death by firing squad.
   Bruno Bottai, secretary-general of the Italian Foreign Ministry,
said the offer to arrange the waste's removal was contingent upon
release of the Italian cargo ship Piave and its 24 crew members.
The ministry said it had not received a response to the offer.
   Italian officials said Franco Raffaelli, owner of the shipping
company accused of dumping the material, had agreed to provide a
vessel and crew to pick it up.
   Martha Sandolo Belleh, the Liberian health minister, said she
rejected the three requests to dump toxic waste in her country, the
independent Daily Observer of Monrovia reported.
   It quoted her as saying one company offered to build a hospital
and supply it with drugs worth $1 million. She would not identify
the companies or the countries in which they were located, the
newspaper said.
</TEXT>
