<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-CivilRights     06-24 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Civil Rights,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Backs Move To Support 1976 Civil Rights Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis supports
the effort of a broad coalition of members of Congress, state
officials and others urging the Supreme Court not to overturn a key
1976 civil rights decision, a spokesman for the Democratic
presidential candidate said Friday.
   The spokesman, Gene Sperling, said, ``The governor's position is
that he wants to congratulate'' those who asked the court to
sustain the ruling.
   Sperling added that the probable Democratic nominee ``is
disappointed that the Justice Department did not join in the
bipartisan effort'' supporting the 1976 decision.
   The attorneys general of 47 states, 60 U.S. senators and 112
House members joined with civil rights groups in asking the
justices to leave undisturbed the 1976 ruling that has been used to
fight racial discrimination.
   The Reagan administration Justice Department is sitting out the
controversy, declining to take sides in the case.
   The court rocked the civil rights commuity last April when it
announced it will consider overturning the 1976 decision that
allows people to sue private citizens accused of racial
discrimination.
   The justices will hear arguments on the issue in their next term
beginning in October. A decision is expected sometime in 1989.
</TEXT>
