<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabyKidnapped     06-24 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Kidnapped,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five-Day-Old Baby Home From Hospital Following Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE HOBBS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five-day-old Jason Ray McClure was
buckled into a car seat and taken home Friday, five days after he
was spirited from his mother's hospital room reportedly in a brown
paper bag.
   Two women charged in his kidnapping appeared handcuffed before a
judge who appointed an attorney and returned them to jail on
$500,000 and $100,000 bonds.
   ``I hope everybody keeps saying prayers for all the missing
children in the world because they need help too,'' said Renee
McClure as she left High Point Regional Hospital with her infant
son.
   Mrs. McClure's baby was taken from her room Monday morning by a
woman dressed in white who said she had to weigh the baby.
   Police found Jason on Wednesday, hidden in a closet in a High
Point house. His hair had been cut to alter his appearance, police
said.
   ``Jason is doing fine,'' Mrs. McClure said, hugging nurses who
helped her load Jason and three carts of flowers and gifts into a
van for the ride home to Lexington.
   Brenda Joyce Nobles, 37, was charged with first-degree
kidnapping and her 19-year-old daughter, Sharon Slaydon, was
charged with aiding and abetting kidnapping. The child was found in
their home, according to police.
   Judge Lawrence C. McSwain set a July 6 court date for the women
Friday and kept bond at $500,000 for Mrs. Nobles and $100,000 for
Ms. Slaydon.
   Meanwhile, the Greensboro News & Record reported Friday that
Mrs. Nobles had shown a neighbor a baby she said she had delivered.
   ``She said the doctor had let her come straight home after
having the baby,'' neighbor Linda Drake told the newspaper. ``I
knew she couldn't have kids, 'cause she told me she had had herself
fixed.''
   Mrs. Nobles had had a hysterectomy, according to Annie Jackson,
her great aunt.
   Ms. Drake notified police about the mysterious baby Tuesday
night because ``I would want somebody to do the same thing if that
was my baby,'' she said.
   The newspaper also reported that an unidentified law enforcement
source said the kidnapper had picked out Jason during visiting
hours the night before she spirited him away in a brown paper bag.
   ``She went over Sunday during visitation hours, looked at
babies, excluded blacks, females, and picked a white male,'' the
newspaper quoted the source as saying.
   The source said the kidnapper returned the next morning, changed
into a nurse's uniform carried in a brown paper bag and then went
to Mrs. McClure's room. She told Mrs. McClure Jason needed to be
weighed, then put him in the bag and carried him from the hospital.
   Authorities said Thursday that the kidnapping was ``almost a
textbook case'' of the emotionally troubled baby-snatcher.
   ``Our theory is ... what the FBI psychologists told us from the
beginning (before the baby was found) _ she had deep-seated
emotional problems, a terribly deep desire that she needed to
fulfill by having a baby,'' police Capt. Ronald McGuire said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
