<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CapitolBombing     06-24 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Bombing,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kunstler Says Case Is Political Effort to Silence Dissent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Kuntsler and other lawyers
defending six members of a left-wing group charged with setting off
a bomb in the U.S. Capitol derided the prosecution Friday as a
political effort to silence dissent.
   Prosecutors ``want to teach a lesson to all dissidents ... that
the penalties are very high if you commit crimes against the
government,'' Kuntsler said after he appeared with the defendants
and their lawyers before U.S. District Judge Harold Greene.
   Asked about Greene's reputation as a fair judge, Kuntsler said:
``His actions belie it. He's a product of the system.''
   ``A fair trial is impossible anyway for anyone like them, we can
only do the best we can do,'' said Kuntsler, who represents
defendant Laura Whitehorn.
   Earlier, Kuntsler was asked about Greene's reputation as a
liberal judge, to which he replied: ``To me, a liberal means
neo-fascist.''
   During the hearing, Greene denied a motion to remove a clear,
plastic wall between the spectators and the court that the defense
claims is intended to intimidate the defendants and prejudice
jurors once the case goes to trial.
   ``These women and men were accused by the government to, in
essence, criminalize their political beliefs,'' said defense lawyer
Russell F. Canan.
   By installing the shield and TV cameras, the government ``is
using the courtroom as simply just another tool for political
surveillance,'' Canan said.
   The strident political rhetoric by defense lawyers signaled
their intention to turn the proceeding into a trial of the politics
of the Reagan administration rather than the charges that the
defendants set off bombs in the Capitol and three other locations
in Washington.
   ``We are not terrorists nor criminals; we are anti-imperialist
political prisoners and we are guilty of no crimes,'' said the
statement by defendants Marilyn Buck, Linda Sue Evans, Susan
Rosenberg, Alan Berkman, Timothy Blunk and Whitehorn.
   ``The politically motivated indictment against us is part of a
program of repression against the most active elements in the
Central American solidarity movement that has grown among the
people of the U.S. over the past years,'' the statement said. ``We
will fight these charges but we will not allow ourselves to be part
of a governmental show trial.''
   The six plus fugitive Elizabeth Duke are charged with setting
off a bomb that blew a large hole in a wall outside the U.S. Senate
chamber on Nov. 7, 1983. They also are accused of detonating bombs
at three Washington military facilities in 1983 and 1984.
   Buck, Evans and Whitehorn also are charged with leading a
campaign of ``armed propaganda'' against ``imperialist rule'' by a
secret left-wing group that set off bombs in four locations in New
York City between 1983 and 1985.
   The other defendants are named but not charged as participants
in the alleged conspiracy ``to oppose, obstruct or change the
foreign and domestic policies of the U.S. government through
violent and illegal means.''
   None of the blasts caused any injuries.
   But after the Capitol bombing, a group calling itself the Armed
Resistance Unit issued a communique to National Public Radio
threatening possible future violence against ``individual members
of the ruling class and government.''
   ``We do not choose to kill any of them at this time. But their
lives are not sacred,'' the communique said.
   Rosenberg and Blunk are serving 58-year sentences for possession
of 600 pounds of ammunition and explosives. Evans is serving terms
totaling 45 years for illegal weapons charges.
   Buck, who was not in court Friday, is awaiting sentencing in New
York for murder and armed robbery in connection with a botched 1981
holdup of a Brink's armored car that left a guard and two policemen
dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0231 </DOCNO>
