<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0740 06-24 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0740,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Day of Peace Talks Go `Pretty Roughly'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds five grafs with Angolan assertion about U.S. position.
Hyphen in second Van-Dunem is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa and Angola ended a day of
U.S.-mediated peace talks Friday still widely separated, with
neither side indicating it was willing to back down on positions
unacceptable to the other, sources said.
   South Africa is insisting on the withdrawal of Cuban troops from
Angola as a precondition for independence for South-West Africa,
also known as Namibia. Angola is demanding an end to South African
military and logistical aid to Angolan rebels.
   The talks are aimed at bringing peace to Angola, where civil war
has raged for 13 years, and to bring independence to Namibia, which
is controlled by South Africa.
   After a two-hour formal opening session, delegations dispersed
to discuss proposals put forward by South Africa and the joint
Angolan-Cuban group, sources close to the conference said.
   Further formal talks were scheduled for Saturday morning, the
second and final day of this third round of negotiations that began
in London last month.
   ``The talks went pretty roughly,'' a Cuban source said.
   Reports in the South African press said South Africa's foreign
minister, R.F. Botha, angrily led his delegation out of the
conference hall. South African, Cuban, Angolan and American
delegates denied it.
   The talks are taking place at three tables, with Chester
Crocker, assistant U.S. secretary of state for African affairs,
sitting at the head table as mediator.
   Delegates refused to talk officially on the substance of
proposals presented Friday, confirming only that the formal talks
would resume Saturday.
   But sources close to the conference, who insisted on anonymity,
said Botha insisted that, as a precondition for Namibian
independence, Cuba announce a date by which it would withdraw its
more than 50,000 troops from Angola.
   The sources said the Angolan delegation, headed by Foreign
Minister Afonso Van Dunem, demanded that South Africa halt its aid
to Angolan rebels.
   The sources also said that should a fourth round of talks be
needed, Angola and Cuba would insist that they be held in New York.
   The first two rounds of talks were in May in London and
Brazzaville, Congo.
   In New York on Friday, a senior Angolan official, Pedro
Van-Dunem, minister of state for petroleum and economy, asserted
that the United States had introduced a new ``double linkage'' in
its negotiating position.
   He told reporters that in a meeting Wednesday with Angolan
representatives, Secretary of State George P. Shultz not only
reiterated a U.S. call for a Cuban withdrawal from Angola, but also
pressed the Angolans to negotiate with the Angolan rebel group, the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA,
which has U.S. support.
   Van-Dunem said such negotiations are ``out of the question.''
   Asked about Van-Dunem's statement, a State Department official
in Washington said it has long been the U.S. view that direct
discussions between the Angolan government and the UNITA forces are
needed for a settlement.
   ``It's not a condition that we are laying down. It's just a
fact, given the reality of the situation on the ground,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-PrisonProbe     06-24 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Prison Probe,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts AG Says Dukakis Was Victim of Reagan Administration
Leak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic attorney general of Massachusetts
said Friday he believes that reports of an FBI probe of a state
prison project were probably a ``leak from the Reagan
administration,'' whose own top legal officer blasted leaks and
warned associates to keep quiet.
   State Attorney General James Shannon said he believes the FBI
investigation was leaked ``for political purposes.'' In Washington,
the reporter who first revealed the FBI probe said Shannon was
wrong.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III, meanwhile, addressed the issue
of news leaks involving Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis at a Friday meeting of top Justice Department managers.
Spokesman Patrick Korten said Meese reminded his deputies there is
to be no ``leaking of information'' about any current
investigations.
   Meese described any leaking as ``highly unprofessional conduct
and extremely injurious and extremely unfair,'' according to Korten.
   On Thursday, the Washington Times cited ``law enforcement
authorities and others'' and said the FBI was conducting a
preliminary inquiry into ``the conduct'' of Dukakis and
high-ranking members of his administration in connection with the
1986 selection of a multi-million prison site in central
Massachusetts.
   The FBI confirmed the probe but said Dukakis was not a
``subject'' of the investigation.
   ``I don't know who did it,'' Shannon told reporters at a news
conference on civil rights. ``But when you see what is clearly a
leak from federal law enforcement authorities ... there are clearly
conclusions you're likely to jump to _ that it was a leak from the
Reagan administration.''
   Shannon supports Dukakis' campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination but holds office independently of the
governor and is not part of the Dukakis administration.
   Jerry Seper, who wrote the piece, said of Shannon's remarks:
``That's just absolutely false. No one from the Reagan
administration, the Justice Department, and no one from the FBI
leaked this story to the Washington Times.
   ``The story resulted from asking questions in Massachusetts of a
lot of people over several weeks.''
   Shannon said he called the FBI office in Boston after reading a
version of the Times story.
   ``They made perfectly clear to me that it's the most preliminary
of inquiries,'' Shannon said. He praised James Ahearn, the special
agent in charge of the Boston office, for issuing the statement
clarifying that Dukakis was not a ``subject'' of the FBI's inquiry.
   The case centers on a proposed prison that has met with vigorous
opposition in the community of New Braintree. Opponents charge that
the property owners _ one of whom is an acquaintance of Dukakis'
and a donor to his political campaigns _ stand to make millions of
dollars in profit from the sale.
   FBI officials have had no comment since releasing a carefully
worded statement that said the Boston field office is conducting an
inquiry into the proposed land deal and noting later in elaboration
that it is too soon in the inquiry for anyone to be called a
``subject.''
   Shannon said he has long been aware of complaints about the
siting process at New Braintree and that he has referred all
charges of impropriety to the state inspector general.
   ``I assume that what the FBI is doing is the same thing _ you
get an allegation and you have to ask some questions,'' Shannon
said. ``We felt that because allegations had been made, the proper
way was to have the inspector general take a look.''
   If the inspector general found grounds for a criminal
investigation, he would refer the matter back to the attorney
general's office, Shannon said, and that has not happened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
