<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Australia     06-24 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Australia,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hawke Departs After Warning Against Australian Backlash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke flew to
Texas Friday after warning top officials here that current American
farm support policies could produce a backlash in his country
damaging to U.S.-Australian military cooperation.
   During a two-day Washington visit, Hawke gave that message to a
meeting of both houses of Congress, to President Reagan at the
White House and to the two leading candidates to succeed Reagan _
Republican Vice President George Bush and Democratic Gov. Michael
Dukakis of Massachusetts.
   He said he believes that Bush, like Reagan, backs ending the
farm supports and he would be disappointed if Dukakis doesn't also.
   The Australian leader was scheduled to speak at the University
of Texas in Austin before returning home.
   Hawke spent his last half day in Washington golfing with
Secretary of State George P. Shultz on the fashionable Burning Tree
course and meeting an array of U.S. economic and business officials
at an Australian Embassy lunch.
   The guests included Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng,
Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman David S. Ruder,
Chairman Beryl W. Sprinkel of Reagan's Council of Economic
Advisers, Deputy Secretary of State John Whitehead and Washington
Post chairman Katherine Graham, the embassy said.
   Between meetings with Bush and Dukakis late Thursday, Hawke
asked Americans to recognize that the Australian military bases and
satellite tracking stations shared with U.S. forces have an
important role in the vital verification process of U.S.-Soviet
nuclear disarmament, including the treaty under negotiation to
reduce strategic long-range arms by 50 percent.
   The prime minister told a television interviewer he rejects
linking the future of the bases to U.S. farm subsidies damaging the
Australian economy but that, realistically, Australian public
opinion would link them.
   ``I'm simply saying, honestly and objectively, that if there
were to be an increase in this adverse impact upon our farmers, who
are unsubsidized and the most efficient in the world, there will be
a growth of resentment'' of the United States,'' Hawke said on the
MacNeil-Lehrer TV Newshour.
   He added: ``It would be wrong to close down those facilities
(military bases), but politicians, in the end, can't resist the
will of the people''
   The impact of subsidized U.S. wheat exports has been
considerable, Hawke said, declaring that the share of the world
wheat market for unsubsidized Australian wheat dropped from 20 to
12 percent during the three years of the U.S. wheat export subsidy
program while the U.S. share rose from 29 to 43 percent.
   ``Bush understands and, I think, supports my position,'' said
Hawke. ``I would be disappointed if (Dukakis) didn't adopt the same
position,'' he added in the interview, which took place before his
talk with Dukakis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
