<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1923EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Manigat-Wife     06-24 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manigat-Wife,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manigat Knew Namphy Would Take Action Against Him, Wife Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leslie Manigat, the
deposed president of Haiti, knew when he fired Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy as military commander that the general would retaliate,
Manigat's wife said Friday.
   Myrlande Manigat said several ranking army officers advised her
husband to put Namphy in jail, but the president decided instead to
confine him to house arrest without a telephone or other means of
communication.
   Manigat knew Namphy ``would take action, but not in that
manner,'' she said in a televised interview, referring to the
palace guards who freed Namphy on Sunday and put him back in the
National Palace.
   Manigat, who arrived in the Dominican Republic with his family
the day after the coup and flew to Miami on Friday, has said he was
ousted because he tried to end corruption in the army and the
government.
   ``The confrontation with Gen. Namphy was inevitable sooner or
later because he and my husband had nothing in common morally, in
terms of humaneness, intellectually, in their values, in nothing,''
Mrs. Manigat said.
   Namphy led the junta that ruled Haiti for two years after
dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled in February 1986. He turned over
power to Manigat on Feb. 7 after Manigat won a presidential
election with the army's help, and proclaimed himself presidend
Monday, after the coup.
   The night of the coup, many ambassadors called Manigat and told
him to hide, Mrs. Manigat said. Two ambassadors offered refuge in
their embassies but he ``refused to leave and said they had to come
arrest him,'' she said, without elaborating.
   After seing Namphy on television announcing the takeover with
all the ranking officers at his side, Manigat told his family:
``You have to prepare for anything, all is lost. ... We can't count
on the armed forces to overcome a military coup,'' she said.
   When soldiers arrived with tanks and began shooting at the
Manigat house, she said, the 20 people inside prepared to fight but
Manigat told them to surrender ``because you can't resist a tank
with a rifle.''
   The group shouted their surrender and went outside.
   ``They put us in line and started shooting again and I thought
they were going to kill us all, but they didn't,'' Mrs. Manigat
said. ``I think it was a psychological action to make us think they
were going to.''
   The Manigats and their daughter were taken to the airport and
flew to the Dominican Republic around midday.
   ``When I found myself in the hotel in Santo Domingo, when we
were alone, I simply started to cry without being able to control
myself,'' Mrs. Manigat said. ``It was a kind of relief ... to be
safe, to be in a friendly place and to no longer be alone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Soviets     06-24 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Soviets,0874</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canada Finds Itself Embroiled in Rare Spy Drama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada doesn't have spy scandals very often, but
it suddenly finds itself embroiled in an espionage drama involving
sophisticated U.S. naval technology, the banishment of 19 Soviets
and reprisals from Moscow.
   Yet nobody was supposed to know about it.
   As the Canadian Embassy in Moscow awaited the Kremlin's next
move Friday, officials here remained silent on exactly what the
Soviets they expelled were trying to do.
   In the latest retaliation by the Kremlin, the Soviet government
newspaper Izvestia on Friday accused three Canadians diplomats who
have been expelled or barred from the Soviet Union of specific acts
of espionage. Izvestia said one of them had collaborated with U.S.
diplomats who were also ejected as spies.
   According to intelligence sources, the Soviet spy ring was
trying to infiltrate the Paramax Electronics plant in Montreal,
where weapons guidance, communications and sonar systems for a new
generation of Canadian frigates are being supplied under a $830
million contract.
   Paramax is a subsidiary of the Detroit-based Unisys Corp., a
major defense contractor with access to highly classified
electronic warfare technology already in use in the U.S. Navy.
   Another target was the U.S. naval base at Argentia,
Newfoundland, where 400 members of the Naval Security Command
monitor the movement of Soviet submarines, the sources said.
   There was also an attempt to penetrate the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police intelligence service and its successor, the Canadian
Security Intelligence Service, according to Foreign Minister Joe
Clark. He refused to detail other alleged Soviet transgressions.
   In a statement to Parliament Wednesday, Clark announced eight
Soviets had been expelled and nine others formerly assigned here
were barred from returning.
   ``We are confident that Canadian security was not compromised,''
Clark said.
   The Soviets retaliated immediately, expelling two Canadian
diplomats and barring three others from returning to the Soviet
Union.
   Clark, proclaiming the innocence of his envoys, then escalated
the incident by expelling the senior military attache at the Soviet
Embassy in Ottawa, Col. Grigori Roublev, and barring a former
second secretary from returning.
   Paul Frazer, a spokesman for Clark, said he was aware of the
accusations in Izvestia but had no comment.
   The Canadian Press news agency quoted Izvestia as saying Ken
Moodie, former assistant air attache at the Canadian Embassy in
Moscow, was ``caught red-handed'' posing as a tourist at a military
installation in the Siberian city of Novosibirsk.
   Izvestia also named John DiGangi, a former second secretary in
Moscow, and Cmdr. Ray Steele, a naval attache who was scheduled to
leave Moscow today, Canadian Press said in its report. Izvestia
said DiGangi carried out instructions given by three U.S. diplomats
who were expelled for spying, but did not elaborate, the news
agency reported.
   Canadian officials rejected the charges, the news agency said.
   Intelligence Service spokesman Jerry Cummings and government
officials told The Associated Press the spy story was never
supposed to get out.
   It became known because a French-language reporter in Ottawa,
Normand Lester of Radio-Canada, got a tip from an intelligence
source that there was a mass exodus of Soviet diplomats last week,
with children suddenly withdrawn from schools and apartments
emptied overnight.
   Lester knocked on doors to confirm the exodus and broke the
story Tuesday, as Prime Minister Brian Mulroney was hosting the
seven-nation Economic Summit in Toronto.
   At his summit-closing news conference, Mulroney confirmed that a
group of Soviet representatives had been kicked out for spying but
gave no details.
   According to informed sources, the saga began June 11 when a
25-year-old Canadian of Hungarian descent, Stephen Joseph Ratkai,
was arrested in Newfoundland and charged with obtaining classified
U.S. military documents intended for the Soviet Union.
   The sources said Capt. Boris Tatarintsev, assistant naval
attache at the Soviet Embassy in Ottawa, left the country
immediately after Ratkai's arrest.
   Tatarintsev was one of the original eight diplomats on the
expulsion list made public Wednesday.
   Government officials would not confirm Tatarintsev's involvement
in the U.S. naval base case, but the sources said authorities
suspected him of working for the GRU, the Soviet military
intelligence agency, and of having overall responsibility for both
the Argentia and Paramax operations.
   The Soviet Embassy refused to return calls from the AP to answer
questions about Tatarintsev, but embassy spokesman Viatcheslav
Bogdanov earlier claimed none of the Soviets named were spies.
   Sources said Canadian authorities worked a double agent at
Argentia to prevent Soviet infiltration. Clark said a Russian
translator at the International Civil Aviation Organization in
Montreal provided information on some of the spying operations. The
translator, Yuri Smurov, has now defected with his wife and
daughter.
   Canada had military and commercial reasons for wanting to keep
the expulsions secret.
   Its navy is seeking U.S. approval for the transfer of nuclear
propulsion technology incorporated in the British Trafalgar-class
submarines it may buy. Lax security could make the Americans veto
the transfer.
   In addition, a public rift between the Soviet Union and Canada
might endanger Soviet purchases of Canadian wheat and potential
pipeline and dam projects for Canadian engineering firms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
