<DOCNO> AP880624-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0768 06-24 0988</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0768,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Criticizes Dukakis; Says `I Won't Raise Your Taxes'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates on unity rally with new graf 3, beginning ``Bush
repeated,'' and 7 new grafs at end, starting with graf 29 ``As
he,'' on more from Bush, quotes from Dole and Robertson, Bush
statement on drought</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush attacked Democrat
Michael Dukakis on Friday for increasing taxes in Massachusetts and
said, ``I will not raise your taxes, period. He just has, in his
home state.''
   The vice president indicated he would go even further than
President Reagan in ruling out all forms of new taxes, including
excise taxes.
   Bush repeated his criticism of Dukakis' tax increase at a GOP
unity rally, telling applauding Republicans: ``I promise you I'll
not raise taxes as a first, second or last resort. ... We don't
need more taxes, we need a president who can hold the line against
congressional overspending.''
   Bush told a news conference the Massachusetts governor ``refuses
to rule out a tax hike for the nation. We know what that means.''
   Bush said that differences between him and Dukakis ``were
brought into high relief by the announcement yesterday by the
governor of Massachusetts of a $115 million tax hike for his
state.''
   Dukakis on Thursday announced he would sign a package designed
to close an estimated $200 million state budget shortfall,
including a new $40 million tax on cigarettes.
   `I'm just pointing out a fundamental difference that I have on
the federal level in terms of what the governor himself has said.
It makes me wonder what his commitment is,'' Bush said.
   ``In his (Dukakis') announcement, he said this represented a
sharp contrast with the policies of the administration. I couldn't
agree more,'' Bush said.
   Asked whether he would rule out all forms of tax increases, even
excise taxes, Bush said he would _ although he would not extend
that pledge to ``user fees'' like those charged for entering
national parks.
   Bush's vow went further than the tax opposition voiced
repeatedly by President Reagan.
   The administration has supported about $200 billion in tax
increases during the past seven and a half years, including excise
taxes and a tax hike Reagan agreed to last winter as part of a
budget deficit-reduction compromise with Congress.
   Asked if he was concerned his stand would lock him in if
elected, Bush said he was not. ``I think it's reassuring to the
working men and women in this country.''
   Bush said he had a ``plain as day'' difference with Dukakis _
``tax cuts vs. tax hikes.''
   Bush was asked why he was criticizing Dukakis for a tax increase
in his state when, the week before during a campaign swing through
Illinois, he declined to criticize GOP Illinois Gov. James Thompson
for supporting a tax-increase package.
   ``Dukakis is running for president of the United States. Jim
Thompson is not,'' Bush said.
   New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, who traveled to Cincinnati with
Bush, told reporters on Air Force Two that ``I don't know why
anybody's surprised'' that Dukakis signed a tax increase.
   ``Everytime he's had a problem, he's run to a tax increase,'' he
said.
   Bush was here for a unity rally and a series of Republican
meetings, including a session with Republican women.
   Sitting beside Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., and Maureen Reagan,
the president's daughter, Bush said the gender gap problem dogging
his campaign would close once he begins to speak out more on issues.
   ``We want to emphasize the strength of family,'' Bush said in a
portion of the meeting open to reporters. ``I think this gap will
go away.''
   Recent polls have shown that women voters prefer Dukakis over
Bush by 20 or more points.
   Bush told reporters: ``I think we've got a good message for
women, and I want to do a better job of getting that message out of
family and caring and equal opportunity and peace and jobs.''
   At the same time, Bush said he remains against the Equal Rights
Amendment but ``for women's rights.''
   Bush said he would soon unveil a child care program that would
be a major part of his campaign platform.
   Republican party Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf, meanwhile, said
Reagan is eager to stump for Bush. But Fahrenkopf said Bush's
current problem in the polls partly stems from the fact that he is
the vice president.
   ``Being a vice president and running for the presidency is a
difficult position to be in,'' the party chief said.
   On the subject of a vice presidential choice, Bush said he had
assigned campaign aide Bob Teeter, his chief pollster, to develop a
process for coming up with a list of potential names.
   However, he said he still had not begun considering specific
choices.
   As he has been doing at nearly every stop during the past week,
Bush took another jab at the Massachusetts prison furlough program,
under which some convicts were released on weekend passes.
   Although the program was modified earlier this year to stop
furloughs for first-degree murderers, Bush said, ``the Dukakis
furlough program still applies to convicted drug dealers _ giving
them a chance to maintain their contacts in the criminal world and
peddle their illicit wares.''
   Two vanquished GOP rivals, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and Christian
broadcaster Pat Robertson, praised Bush at the rally.
   ``The Republican Party is united and we are not about to see the
country go for a mediocre liberal like Michael Dukakis,'' Robertson
said.
   Quipped Dole: ``I'd accept the nomination but it's already
gone.''
   Bush also met with Dole and a group of local farmers to discuss
the drought afflicting most of the nation's central farm belt.
   ``We should be prepared, if conditions continue to deteriorate,
to provide more disaster relief as needed,'' Bush said in a
statement after the meeting. ``These programs should be funded from
savings from the reduced cost of this year's farm programs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
