<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Musician,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rock Musician of UB40 Group Jailed For Crash That Killed Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bass guitarist for the rock group
UB40 was jailed after pleading guilty Friday to causing the death
of his brother by reckless driving.
   Earl Falconer, 29, had almost twice the legal limit of alcohol
in his blood following the road crash in November 1987 that killed
his brother, Ray.
   At Birmingham Crown Court, Judge Michael Dillon sentenced
Falconer to 18 months imprisonment, with 12 months suspended, and
banned him from driving for three years.
   Defense attorney Colman Tracey said Falconer was filled with
remorse and has not driven a car since.
   ``It was a great piece of good fortune there were not multiple
deaths in this accident,'' Dillon said in passing sentence.
   UB40, whose hits include ``Red, Red Wine'' and a remake of Sonny
and Cher's ``I Got You, Babe,'' had planned a world tour starting
next month. It was not immediately clear whether the tour would be
affected.
   Court testimony revealed that Falconer had approached traffic
lights in Birmingham, central England, at speeds estimated between
60 mph and 80 mph. Witnesses said he overtook a car moving away
from the lights, collided with it and lost control.
   His car demolished some concrete flower planters, a road sign
and a lamppost before slamming into a factory wall. Ray Falconer,
who was sitting in the back seat of his brother's car, was killed
instantly.
</TEXT>
