<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Videotapes     06-24 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Videotapes,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Says Officials Have Videotapes of Alleged Bribery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators probing possible
corruption in defense contracts have videotaped evidence of
Pentagon officials allegedly taking bribes from consultants for
inside information, NBC News reported Friday.
   NBC, citing sources it did not identify said the officials in
the videotapes are Victor Cohen, a deputy assistant secretary of
the Air Force, and James Gaines, a deputy assistant secretary of
the Navy.
   The consultants on the videotapes, NBC reported, include Melvyn
Paisley, a former assistant secretary of the Navy whose office was
searched by federal authorities last week.
   Paisley's attorney, E. Lawrence Barcella, denounced the
officials who provided the information to NBC.
   ``This is just a further example of the government trying their
case in the press rather than waiting for specific allegations to
try in court,'' Barcella said in a telephone interview Friday
night. ``If they want to try a case about leaking government
information, they should stop leaking information.''
   Federal authorities are investigating whether defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former military men,
bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that could be
vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   NBC said officials close to the case said Cohen would clear his
calendar and leave the Pentagon whenever a defense consultant would
call. The meetings were recorded and videotaped and money changed
hands, NBC quoted the sources as saying.
   Gaines also was videotaped meeting with consultants, and highly
confidential documents relating to Pentagon contracts allegedly
changed hands, NBC said.
   Michael Schatzow, the attorney for Gaines, said Friday night
that he would have no comment on the NBC report.
   ``I'll just wait and allow everybody who's been reporting these
stories to wait and be embarrassed later,'' Schatzow said.
   A phone call Friday night to the home of Cohen's attorney,
Seymour Glanzer, was answered by a woman who said he was out for
the evening.
   The Washington Times reported Friday that a congressional staff
member who requested anonymity said that Henry Hudson, the U.S.
attorney for the Eastern District of Virginia who is heading the
investigation, told members of Congress that the FBI had videotaped
some of the alleged crimes under investigation and agents had
``extensive'' tape and wiretap evidence.
   Both Cohen and Gaines have been temporarily reassigned to other
duties since their offices were searched last week by investigators.
   Gaines already has begun cooperating with prosecutors, and Cohen
is negotiating with the government on whether to do the same,
sources told The Associated Press earlier this week.
   Schatzow would not confirm that Gaines is cooperating with
authorities.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Thursday that investigators
believe Gaines was a principal supplier of Pentagon documents to
Paisley, who was Gaines' boss until he left the government in 1987.
   Paisley and Gaines worked together at Boeing Co. in Seattle in
the 1970s.
</TEXT>
