<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham     06-24 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Says He Will Challenge Impeachment Conviction; Blasts
McCain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Record Session, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham said Friday he
will go to court to overturn his impeachment conviction and return
to office.
   ``We think that it's important to challenge this,'' Mecham said,
contending that leaving his conviction unchallenged would leave all
public officials open to impeachment.
   Mecham said he will not seek any political office this year but
will go to court in an effort to have his April 4 impeachment
conviction overturned.
   Mecham, in an interview on KTSP-TV, also blasted first-term Sen.
John McCain, a fellow Arizona Republican who has been mentioned as
a possible running mate for Vice President George Bush, the certain
GOP nominee.
   McCain, a first-term senator, called for Mecham's resignation in
January.
   ``No, John isn't qualified to be vice president,'' Mecham said.
``He doesn't have the intellect, he doesn't have the stature, he
doesn't have the honesty, he doesn't have the character that it
takes, and he certainly doesn't have the political foundation.''
   McCain, who was speaking Friday night in Watertown, S.D., on
Bush's behalf, said, ``Former Gov. Mecham is entitled to his
opinion. ... Nothing surprises me.''
   McCain said he was not seeking the vice presidential nomination,
noting that other qualified candidates come from states with more
electoral votes. He has said he backs Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.,
for the GOP second spot.
   Mecham and McCain are members of the Arizona delegation to the
national GOP convention in New Orleans Aug. 15-18.
   Mecham was convicted by the Senate on impeachment charges of
misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund, which he said
he did not believe was state money, and trying to thwart an
investigation of an alleged death threat. He was acquitted June 16
on criminal charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   The former governor said he probably would take his challenge to
federal court, although the decision will be up to his lawyers. He
also said it was uncertain how soon it will be filed.
   Gov. Rose Mofford, the Democratic former secretary of state who
succeeded Mecham, said earlier Friday she plans to run for
re-election in 1990.
</TEXT>
