<1ST_LINE>u w AM-StarWars-Theft 2ndLd-Writethru a0758 06-24 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Star Wars-Theft, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0758,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Theft of Computers From Star Wars Office Probed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs bgng, `The thefts,' to
UPDATE with method of entry to facility</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Department and FBI investigators are
probing the thefts of two small computers on two consecutive nights
from the Star Wars offices in the Pentagon, a tightly controlled
security area.
   Pentagon officials who asked not to be identified said Friday
the theft of one privately owned computer and one government-owned
computer occurred two months ago and appeared to be ``an inside
job.''
   The thefts did not compromise any classified programs, but were
troubling because of the emphasis placed on physical security by
the Strategic Defense Initiative Organization, the Pentagon unit
responsible for the Star Wars anti-missile program, the sources
added.
   The thief or thieves entered the facility by sabotaging the
security system protecting the Star Wars office, local television
station WJLA reported Friday. Videotape cameras failed to record
the theft because they had not been loaded _ a common occurence in
the high security office, the ABC affiliate, citing unidentified
Pentagon investigators for the information.
   Maj. Bill O'Connell, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement
that ``one privately owned stand-alone personal computer was stolen
from offices within the SDIO's Pentagon complex in early April.''
   ``Since that theft, the Defense Criminal Investigative Service
and the FBI have been conducting an investigation. The
investigation to date leads us to conclude that no national
security information was compromised in any way.''
   Late Friday, the spokesman released a second statement, saying
agents were investigating ``a potentially related matter
(involving) the disappearance of an IBM compatible AT class
personal computer ... from the SDIO computer training center.''
   ``No classified materials of any sort are used in the training
facility.''
   O'Connell declined to elaborate, but a source said the thefts
occurred over the weekend of April 9 and 10.
   The first theft, involving a Commodore personal computer owned
by a ``mid-level manager'' in the kinetic energy program, occurred
between Friday evening and Saturday morning. The second theft
occurred between Saturday evening and Sunday morning, the official
said.
   Kinetic energy weapons are designed to destroy enemy missiles
through the sheer force of impact.
   According to the source, investigators believe an SDIO employee
with the proper door-security card and clearances entered the
basement complex through the main doors, where a guard was on duty,
but then left with the computers through another security door that
is under television surveillance but not guarded.
   The Star Wars office complex is one of the few areas of the
Pentagon building that is off-limits to those without a special
security pass in addition to the normal building pass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
