<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Talks     06-24 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Urges Renewed Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government
publicly urged the U.S.-supported rebels Friday to agree to renew
talks here next week to end Nicaragua's more than six-year-old
civil war.
   A statement by the presidential press office also suggested that
if the rebels refuse, a special preparatory meeting be held in
Miami to discuss prolonging the current cease-fire which ends June
30.
   The proposal coincides with a visit Secretary of State George P.
Shultz is making to Nicaragua's neighbors _ Guatemala, Honduras, El
Salvador and Costa Rica _ June 29-July 1 to discuss with the chiefs
executives of the four countries the situation in Central America.
   It also coincides with calls in Washington for the Reagan
administration to renew U.S. military aid to the Contras, as the
rebels are known. Shultz will not visit Nicaragua.
   The statement said the government made the proposal in a message
that Gen. Humberto Ortega, the Defense Minister, sent earlier
Friday to Alfredo Cesar, director of the Contra umbrella group
called Nicaraguan Resistance.
   Representatives from both sides have been negotiating one and
off since March 21 to end the war, agreeing so far only on a
provisional cease-fire. But they have been unable to agree on how
to make it permanent, and on Contra demands the Sandinistas
undertake democratic reforms before the rebels lay down their
weapons.
   The original 60-day truce ended May 30, and was extended by
tacit agreement for 30 days more, while the negotiations continued.
But the Contras broke off the last round of talks June 9 in
Managua, claiming the Sandinistas were not negotiating on good
faith over the reforms.
   Earlier this week, Ortega sent a message to the Contras urging a
new round of four days of talks in Managua beginning Sunday. The
rebel leaders have not replied.
   Ortega's brother, President Daniel Oretega, and other top
officials have been claiming the Shultz visit to the region is in
preparation for either direct or indirect U.S. military
intervention in Nicaragua.
   President Ortega repeated that claim Friday night, when he
publicly urged Sandinista soldiers to ``be ready to repel North
American aggression and quash the (Contra) mercenary forces.''
   Ortega spoke at a rally of 30,000 Sandinista supporters in the
main plaza of Masaya, a city 19 miles south of the capital.
   ``Today we face an enemy more powerful that Somoza and his
National Guard, and that is the government of the United States
which is trying to destroy the Nicaraguan revolution and does not
accept the reality of our democratic and revolutionary process,''
Ortega said.
   The Sandinistas seized power in July 1979, after overthrowing
the dictatorship of President Anastasio Somoza.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
