<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Legere Adv28   06-24 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Legere, Adv 28,0713</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mayflower Descendant Bares It All in Playboy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayflower descendant Phoebe Legere thinks her
ancestors might be rocking and rolling in their graves over her
nude photo spread in Playboy.
   She also plays with a rock band, stars in an upcoming horror
movie, lightens her blond hair, wears too much makeup and likes
body-revealing outfits.
   But the 26-year-old entertainer is ambivalent about her debut as
a centerfold, and was initially reluctant to even do the spread.
   She said the magazine ``niced'' her into doing the pictures. At
the time, she said, she felt devastated by the loss of a singing
job and the failure of her first record, which helped put her
$30,000 in debt.
   ``I was going through some very sad times,'' she said in an
interview. ``I felt a little degraded I guess, and I guess I wanted
to degrade myself even more. I guess I felt like I was just a piece
of flesh anyway and I thought maybe I should make enough money to
pay for my own funeral.''
   Someone at Playboy saw her picture on a promotional ad for a
performance at Carnegie Hall, and the magazine began courting her.
   She recalled telling the editors: ``Under no circumstances will
I perform nude. I'm a Mayflower descendant, a Vassar graduate (with
a 4.0 average), an intellectual. I'm a feminist.''
   She instead offered them erotic drawings she had done.
   ``They said ..., `Well this is fine but if you show us one
nipple we're going to make you very rich.' I said, `Absolutely not.
I'm an accomplished musician. I went to the New England
Conservatory (of Music).'''
   She eventually agreed to do it.
   ``They just wore me down,'' she said. ``I guess I just wanted a
little attention. I didn't have a boyfriend at the time. I was a
little lonely and that's about the size of it.''
   But life is pretty good these days for Legere. She has a part in
``Toxic Avenger II'' for Troma Productions, a New York-based
company of low-budget campy horror movies. Six of her songs will be
in the movie.
   She also has her own line of lingerie, designs her own clothes
and appears with her rock band, Blond Fox.
   In the recent movie, ``Mondo New York,'' which critics trounced,
she performs one of her own works, ``Marilyn Monroe.''
   Legere is no longer the innocent 17-year-old who came to New
York from Lexington, Mass., to attend Vassar College and take her
shot as a musician.
   ``I was totally preppy,'' she recalled. ``I was the flat shoe,
with my hair in a braid and no makeup and very politically
correct.''
   And, she said, it got her nowhere. So looked for inspiration to
the excesses of nightlife in the East Village.
   ``It wasn't until I started learning from the models and the
drag queens around me that I really began to attract attention,''
she said.
   She started to dress differently. She padded her face with
excessive makeup, lightened her blond hair and showed off her body.
And her popularity grew.
   But while she said she developed ``an appreciation of my own
anatomy,'' she says she remained true to her upbringing and her
ancestry, including Isaac Allerton and his daughter, Remember, who
rode the Mayflower to freedom.
   Legere said she seeks ``a kind of freedom of expression, freedom
to be beautiful and to make beauty, not just conform mindlessly to
some commercial notion of what music should sound like or what
women should look like.''
   She never quite felt comfortable in Massachusetts.
   ``There was great pressure to conform, to be normal. Blend.
Don't call attention to yourself. Wear brown,'' she said. ``All I
ever wanted was to be a great musician.''
   Still, if large-scale success comes her way, she might have to
tone down her act.
   ``I sort of imagine that when I get to the top I'll go back to
not wearing any makeup and wearing my hair in a braid,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues June 28</NOTE>
