<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-24 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0612</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew at a strong 3.6 percent
rate in the first three months of 1988, prompting the Reagan
administration to boost its growth forecast for the remainder of
the year.
   After the October stock market collapse, many private economists
expected a slowdown or recession this year. But booming growth in
the last quarter of 1987 and continued strength this year had
analysts revising their forecasts.
   Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of the president's Council of Economic
Advisers, raised the administration's GNP forecast for all of 1988
to 3.5 percent on Thursday. He also predicted consumer price
inflation would hold steady at 4.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After-tax profits at the nation's businesses
declined by 1.0 percent in the first three months of 1988, the
poorest performance in a year, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that profits dipped to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $144.2 billion, down $1.4
billion from the last three months of 1987.
   It was sharpest drop since first quarter 1987, when profits fell
3.7 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic-made cars and light trucks rose
12.8 percent in mid-June from a year ago, resuming a robust pace
after a brief slowdown earlier in the month, domestic automakers
have reported.
   Domestic car sales were up 11.9 percent and domestic light truck
sales gained 14.3 percent from mid-June 1987, automakers reported
Thursday. The sales rate picked up considerably from early June,
industry analysts said.
   In the eight selling days of June 11-20, automakers sold 222,262
domestic cars and 127,195 domestic light trucks, up from 223,376
cars and 125,193 trucks in nine days a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRAINERD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter says
the already-costly farm subsidy battle could escalate further
unless progress is made on eliminating all subsidies by 2000.
   Yeutter said Thursday that Congress could increase export
subsidies, just as it did in 1985, if it appeared that current
global trade negotiations on the matter are at a stalemate.
   ``Sometimes one must have a higher level of confrontation in
order to achieve progress,'' Yeutter told a news conference held
during trade talks with America's largest trading partners.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats have mounted an ambitious attempt to
put a layoff notice bill on President Reagan's desk by July 4 while
holding a revised trade bill hostage to overriding an expected
White House veto before the Republican National Convention.
   But, using a combination of speeches and long periods of silence
on the Senate floor Thursday, Republicans thwarted Democratic
efforts to win passage of the layoff-plant closing notice bill by
the end of this week.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, on Thursday re-introduced _ without
the plant closing provision _ a trade bill vetoed by Reagan last
month. A similarly stripped-down bill was introduced in the House
last week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-time associate of former Defense
Secretary Caspar Weinberger who was brought to the Pentagon to
control procurement says he quit in frustration last fall because
Weinberger and President Reagan failed to support his management
reforms.
   ``I differ 100 percent with the (former) secretary of defense
who said the system is fine but we have a few bad apples,'' said
Richard P. Godwin, former undersecretary of defense for acquisition.
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Godwin, the former president
of Bechtel Civil and Minerals Inc., called the Pentagon procurement
process a ``national crisis,'' as serious for the country as drug
trafficking and the AIDS epidemic.
</TEXT>
