<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rowntree PLC has agreed to a sweetened, $4.5
billion buyout offer from Swiss foods giant Nestle SA, ending the
months-long ``candy bar war'' for the British confectioner.
   Nestle's 2.55 billion-pound offer accepted Thursday edges out
rival bidder Jacobs Suchard AG, a Swiss chocolate and coffee
concern, to create the world's second-largest confectioner behind
U.S.-based Mars Inc.
   The bid for Rowntree, maker of the Kit Kat candy bar, is the
largest offer for a British company by a foreign concern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
voted to impose the first fine under its decency standards on a
Missouri television station for broadcasting a ``pandering and
titillating'' sex comedy during prime time.
   The FCC voted 2-1 Thursday to levy the maximum $2,000 fine on
KZKC-TV, a UHF station in Kansas City, for showing the movie
``Private Lessons'' at 8 p.m., a time at which the agency said
children were likely to be watching.
   The movie, broadcast May 26, 1987, included scenes of a
bare-breasted woman that the FCC said ``were neither isolated nor
fleeting.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer electronics aren't just for yuppies,
according to an industry group that released a Gallup survey that
found nearly two-thirds of American homes owned a videocassette
recorder.
   Ownership of VCRs has mushroomed to 65 percent of U.S.
households, the Electronic Industries Association, which sponsored
the nationwide telephone survey of 1,008 adults this spring, said
Thursday.
   Televisions, which topped the popularity list, were owned by 99
percent of the households surveyed.
</TEXT>
