<TEXT>
   The heads of the three major television
networks have asked Congress to ensure that America's system of
free local broadcasting be preserved in the race for high
definition TV now being developed.
   The three network chiefs said Thursday that any decisions that
will move the U.S. television industry to an improved picture
quality should protect the 140 million TV sets currently in use.
   Broadcasters fear they could be left out if others in the TV
industry, such as cable TV and makers of videocassette players,
adopt a high definition TV transmission standard that is not
compatible with existing TV sets.
