<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices closed higher as
supply-and-demand concerns persisted in the energy futures market.
   July unleaded gasoline contracts rose 0.66 cent Thursday to
close at 51.06 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   ``Supplies in the Northeast are somewhat tight and we're heading
into the peak demand period,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior broker and
analyst with E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc. Gas supplies
are a concern because of the approaching July 4 weekend, the
traditional beginning of the summer driving season.
   ``It was really kind of a featureless market except for the
strength in gas,'' Lebow said.
   Crude and home heating oil futures were mixed.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, fell 7 cents to close at $16.37 per barrel. The July
contract for home heating oil rose 0.32 cent to close at 43.94
cents a gallon.
   Gasoline prices also had rallied on Tuesday and Wednesday,
setting the only positive tone in the energy futures market.
