<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MediaForecast     06-24 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Media Forecast,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Expects 10.1 Percent Annual Growth in Communications Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growth in the communications industry over the
next five years should exceed the expected growth in the overall
economy and expansion in other leading industries, according to an
investment banker that specializes in media deals.
   The industry is expected to grow at an average annual rate of
10.1 percent through 1992, down from its 10.9 percent expansion
pace for the previous five years, the firm Veronis, Suhler &
Associates Inc. reported Tuesday.
   The firm's report covers revenue forecasts for radio,
television, newspapers, magazines, recorded music, books, films and
information services.
   Veronis Suhler said gross revenue in the communications industry
should rise to $218 billion in 1992 from $134.9 billion in 1987.
   The report said the overall economy is expected to grow at a 7.5
percent rate annually over the next five years.
   Veronis Suhler said the communications industry's growth will
exceed what it expects will be the annual growth rates for 11 other
major industries over the next five years, including 9.6 percent in
health and medical services, 8.5 percent in educational services
and 8.4 percent in electronic equipment.
   It was the second annual five-year forecast from the investment
firm. Last year, it forecast a 10.3 percent growth in the
communications business for the period 1987 through 1991.
   A slowdown in the expansion of fast-rising home video, cable and
business information segments accounted for the lower expansion
projection for the next five years.
   Television broadcast ad spending is expected to rise 11.5
percent a year to $40.4 billion by 1992, the report said. That
includes 8.5 percent annual growth in spending on the broadcast
networks to $13.3 billion in 1992, it said.
   ``Network television will continue to lose both audience share
and share of advertising dollars over the next five years,'' the
report said.
   Television stations revenues should grow at an annual rate of
12.8 percent to $25.1 billion by 1992, the report said, while
barter syndication, a system under which programs are exchanged for
the rights to sell commercials on the shows, will account for
another $2 billion in revenue.
   Veronis Suhler said the increased availability of quality
programming should enable independent stations to compete more
effectively with network affiliates.
   Cable television revenues are expected to grow at a rate of 9.2
percent a year to nearly $16 billion by 1992, including $13.5
billion from subscription fees and $2.5 billion from advertising,
the report said.
   By 1992, Veronis Suhler estimates that 57 percent of the homes
with televisions will have cable in 1992, up from 50 percent in
1987.
   Higher basic cable fees are expected to propel a 10.4 percent
annual growth rate in basic cable over the next five years. But
those higher basic cable fees and competition from rental cassettes
should limit pay cable growth to less than 4 percent a year, the
report said.
   Radio revenues are expected to grow by about 10 percent a year
to $11.65 billion by 1992.
   Veronis Suhler said newspaper revenues are expected to rise at a
rate of 10 percent a year to $60.9 billion, including 10.9 percent
annual growth in advertising revenue and 6.2 percent annual growth
in classified advertising.
   Book publishing revenues should rise 9.4 percent a year to $18.1
billion in 1992, with the biggest increases expected in elementary
and high school textbooks and in professional books, the report
said.
   Magazine revenues are expected to rise at an annual rate of 8.4
percent to $21.4 billion, including a 9.0 percent annual rise in
consumer magazines and a 5.9 percent rise each year in business
magazines.
   The remainder of the revenue projection for 1992 includes $30.3
billion in filmed entertainment, $11.6 billion in business
information services and $8 billion in recorded music.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
