<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AutoSales Bjt   06-24 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Combined Domestic Sales Up 12.8 Percent in Mid-June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic-made cars and light trucks rose
12.8 percent in mid-June from a year ago, resuming 1988's robust
pace after a brief lapse in early June, automakers reported.
   Domestic car sales were up 11.9 percent and domestic light truck
sales gained by 14.3 percent from mid-June 1987. The sales rate
picked up considerably from early June, industry analysts said
Thursday.
   In the eight selling days from June 11-20, automakers sold
222,262 domestic cars and 127,195 domestic light trucks, up from
223,376 cars and 125,193 trucks in nine days a year ago.
   The two periods are compared on the basis of sales per day
rather than total sales during the period.
   ``It's certainly a marked improvement over the first 10 days of
June,'' said Chris Cedergren, analyst with J.D. Power and
Associates in Agoura Hills, Calif.
   Cedergren said the strong mid-month sales mean that the
early-June lag wasn't a sign of a longer-term slowdown.
   Meanwhile, the National Automobile Dealers Association on
Thursday released an updated 1988 U.S. sales forecast of 15.2
million cars and light trucks, imported and domestic.
   The projection is similar to others, including Ford Motor Co.'s
current 15.6 million forecast which unlike the NADA forecast
includes several hundred thousand heavy trucks.
   NADA spokeswoman Jennifer Hunt said the group based its decision
to increase its forecast from 14.7 million vehicles was based on
current sales trends and a quarterly survey of dealer attitudes
that found the highest level of optimism in three years.
   Mid-June domestic car sales rose from a year ago for all makers
except Volkswagen, which closes its only U.S. plant at the end of
the month, and Nissan, which is building more trucks than cars this
year at its Tennessee plant. Nissan's domestic truck sales jumped
50.6 percent from a year ago.
   Chrysler Corp., the nation's No. 3 automaker, gained the most
among the Big Three in sales and market share.
   Chrysler's combined domestic car and light truck sales rose 24.5
percent and its share of the combined market rose to 17.3 percent
from 15.6 percent from mid-June a year ago.
   Chrysler car sales were up 21.7 percent from a year ago and
truck sales jumped 27.6 percent, helped along by record Jeep sales
for the period.
   General Motors Corp., the nation's largest automaker, sold 12.5
percent more domestic cars and light trucks than a year ago. Car
sales rose 9.1 percent and truck sales were up 20.3 percent.
   GM's share of the combined market held nearly steady at 46
percent as a drop in car share was balanced by a gain in the
industry-leader's share of the hot truck market.
   Ford Motor Co., the No. 2 U.S. maker, sold 10.2 percent more
domestic cars but 0.8 percent fewer domestic light trucks than a
year ago, for a total 5.7 percent increase in combined sales.
   Ford's share of the combined market fell to 31.2 percent from
33.3 percent a year ago, with its car share dropping slightly to
30.1 percent of the market and truck share falling five percentage
points to 33.2 percent.
   Ford spokeswoman June Larsen said Ford trucks are in short
supply. Ford is planning to increase production at its truck plant
in Wayne by adding a second shift.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
