<HEAD>One-Month Export Ban Imposed On Company For COCOM Violation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small Japanese trading company convicted of
illegally selling security-sensitive electronic equipment to China
will be barred from exporting its products for one month, the
Ministry of International Trade and Industry said Friday.
   An MITI official said the ban against the Shinsei Koeki Co.
stemmed from the company's conviction Monday in a district court,
and will begin July 1.
   The court found Shinsei Koeki guilty of selling two sets of
electronic measuring equipment to China between June 1985 and
November 1986 without government permission. It fined the small,
Tokyo-based trading company 200,000 yen, or about $1,550.
   The high-technology equipment is among 178 strategic items
restricted by the government under the rules of the Coordinating
Committee for Multilateral Export Controls, a Paris-based watchdog
body on trade with communist countries.
</TEXT>
