<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UnionCarbide     06-24 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Union Carbide,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Restructures Some Business Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp.'s plans to restructure
its three worldwide businesses could be a prelude to the company's
spinning off one of the companies to raise capital and reduce debt,
analysts said.
   Some analysts also said after Union Carbide announced the
planned restructuring Thursday that the company also could be
trying to protect itself from lawsuits stemming from the 1984 gas
leak in Bhopal, India.
   Union Carbide Chairman Robert D. Kennedy also unveiled plans to
spend $450 million to expand and add product lines at the company's
plants in Seadrift, Texas, and Taft, La.
   Kennedy announced the new strategies after Union Carbide's board
approved a management recommendation seeking the new structuring.
The plan would have Union Carbide become the holding company for
the newer companies.
   The restructuring must be approved by shareholders.
   Carbide remains deeply indebted after fending off a hostile
takeover two years ago by GAF Corp., analysts said. As of March 31,
Carbide reported total debt of $3.2 billion compared to total
capitalization of $5.1 billion.
   The 63 percent ratio of debt to capital is about twice that of
Carbide's competitors and the company may hope to reduce that,
analysts said.
   ``It gives them increased flexibility to raise capital in the
future,'' said Leslie Ravitz, a financial analyst with Salomon
Brothers Inc. in New York. ``It opens up the potential to spin off
pieces of their business to the public or to a third party.''
   James Wilbur, a vice president with Smith Barney, Harris Upham
and Co. Inc., said there has been speculation that Carbide might
want to restructure so it can go public with one division while
keeping the others private.
   Wilbur said it was possible the company was restructuring as ``a
defensive strategy ... to get the Bhopal monkey off the operating
division's back,'' although he viewed that as the the least likely
motivation.
   Wilbur also said the restructuring could be strictly
organizational.
   ``Carbide has long been an amalgam of different companies,'' he
said. ``The feeling may have been that it (had become) too
centralized for the nature of its business.''
   Ravitz said Carbide has a history of going through a
restructuring every several years and dismissed any link to Bhopal.
   The Indian government has filed $3 billion in lawsuits against
Carbide on behalf of all victims of the Bhopal gas leak. At least
2,660 people died in the accident, the world's worst industrial
disaster.
   The board also approved a proposed joint venture with Allied
Signal's UOP subsidiary. The deal will combine UOP with Carbide's
catalysts, absorbents and process systems businesses.
</TEXT>
