<DOCNO> AP880624-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Agriculture     06-24 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Agriculture,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Finalizes Farm Price Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12 European Economic Community nations,
overcoming a Greek veto threat, on Friday finalized an accord to
limit spending on support prices for EEC farmers this year to $31.9
billion, or two-thirds of the total EEC budget.
   The long-awaited agreement could blunt criticism by the United
States that Europe does not do enough to rein in farm subsidies.
   While the 1988-89 farm package generally freezes prices at last
year's levels, it cuts prices for some of the EEC's 10.3 million
farmers by as much as 5 percent, officials said.
   The deal was clinched after Greece lifted its June 17 veto to a
compromise deal keeping the farm budget at last year's level.
   The agreement calls for a gradual dismantling of the EEC's
so-called monetary compensatory amounts, or MCAs, which comprise a
highly complex system of border taxes on exports of farm produce
from countries with weak currencies.
   Greek MCAs now range from 29.1 to 48 percent. Last week, the
EEC's executive commission, proposed to offer Greece a 14.5 percent
cut, including an immediate 10-point reduction.
   Early Friday, Greece accepted an immediate dismantling of its
MCAs by 15 to 20 points. This adds at least $116 million to the
farm budget but officials were confident they could keep overall
spending at last year's levels.
   The agreement in effect means lower support prices for EEC
farmers for the second straight year. Last year, prices declined by
3.5 percent on average as part of a package that also generally
froze subsidies.
   In consultations with the United States, the EEC will likely use
Friday's accord to underscore that Europe is serious about curbing
farm subsidies after years of runaway spending that has brought the
community to near bankruptcy.
   The United States, long a critic of the EEC's farm subsidies,
has suggested an end to all such subsidies by the year 2000.
   While the EEC agrees that farm subsidies must be reduced to
prevent the build-up of huge, unmarketable surplus stocks of food,
it has rejected the proposal to do away with farm subsidies
altogether as dangerous and undesirable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
