<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Rowntree-Nestle     06-24 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rowntree-Nestle,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suchard Sells Rowntree Stake to Nestle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacobs Suchard AG on Friday bowed out of the
battle for Rowntree PLC, selling its 28.4 percent stake in the
British confectioner to rival Nestle SA for 690 million pounds, or
$1.2 billion.
   Suchard's decision hands control of Rowntree to Swiss foods
giant Nestle, ending a months-long takeover battle and creating the
world's second-largest confectioner after Mars Inc.
   Suchard, which had ranked second worldwide, will fall to third
place.
   On Thursday, Rowntree accepted Nestle's improved offer of 2.55
billion pounds, or $4.5 billion. Vevey, Switzerland-based Nestle's
original offer amounted to 2.1 billion pounds, or $3.7 billion.
   Zurich-based Suchard, which has interests in chocolate and
coffee, said it agreed to sell its 64.2 million Rowntree shares at
Nestle's offer price of 10.75 pounds, or about $18.81 a share.
   Nestle later confirmed it had purchased the Suchard block,
giving it control of about 51 percent of Rowntree's outstanding
stock.
   Suchard said it would allow its 2.32 billion-pound offer for
Rowntree to lapse, adding that it could not afford to top Nestle's
bid.
   Analysts expect Suchard will reap more than 200 million pounds
in profits from the sale.
   They speculate that the confectioer now might turn its attention
to Cadbury Schweppes PLC, the British confectioner and soft drinks
company in which General Cinema Corp. of the United States holds an
18.4 percent stake.
</TEXT>
