<HEAD>Maxwell Invests In Belgian Publishers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Robert Maxwell said Friday
that he has agreed to invest up to one billion Belgian francs, or
$26 million, in the Belgian printing and publishing group Dupuis.
   The group, one of Europe's leading French-language comic strip
publishers, is currently controlled by Groupe Bruxelles-Lambert,
but Maxwell told a news conference the deal will give him a stake
of about 50 percent in the company.
   Societe Generale de Belgique, the country's largest holding
company, and Maxwell announced earlier this week that they are
launching a new company specializing in communications.
   Maxwell said that his investments in Belgium could in the future
make him the largest single foreign investor in the country.
   ``We are in the business of acquiring Belgian media properties
but only if we are invited and it won't be on a controlling
basis,'' Maxwell said. ``We aren't going to tell them how to do
their business.''
   Maxwell said that his investments in Belgium will involve both
Societe Generale and Groupe Bruxelles Lambert. They are the
country's two largest holding companies, competing in most fields.
   The 65-year-old Maxwell is chairman of British Printing &
Communication PLC, which has interests in printing and publishing.
   He is planning to launch a new European newspaper, and expects
the first million test copies will be issued before the end of
July. He said that the Dupuis facilities may be used for printing
some of the editions of the paper ``if the capacity is available.''
   He also owns Pergamon Press, a publisher of scientific journals,
and publishes the Mirror group of newspapers, which include the
Daily Mirror, two national weeklies and two big Scottish newspapers.
</TEXT>
