<HEAD>Leveraged Buyout of Retailer Completed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior management of Montgomery Ward & Co. have
completed their leveraged buyout of the Chicago-based retailer from
Mobil Corp.
   In a two-step transaction, the management group, led by
Montgomery Ward chairman Bernard F. Brennan, paid Mobil $1.6
billion in cash for the 315-store company and assumed $2.3 billion
in debt.
   In the second step, the retailer sold its credit card subsidiary
to General Electric Capital Corp. for $1 billion in cash. General
Electric Capital will assume $1.8 billion in debt, primarily
customer receivables, from the credit card operation.
   ``We're returning as a Chicago-based, independent company,''
Brennan said Thursday before taking over the 116-year-old company
that was purchased by Mobil in 1976.
   Montgomery Ward plans to open about 225 new shops during the
next five years under its specialty format emphasizing automotive
services, home furnishings or electronics and appliances.
   For the first quarter, Wards earned $19 million, it highest
first-quarter profit, on revenue of $1.23 billion, up from $8
million on revenue of $951 million a year earlier.
   For all of 1987, the retailer earned $130 million on sales of
$4.64 billion.
