<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-PowerRates     06-24 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Power Rates,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Limits States' Authority to Lower Electric Rates in
Mississippi Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a ruling that will cost
Mississippi consumers $326.5 million, today limited severely
states' authority to lower the electric rates public utilities
charge as a result of agreements with federal regulators.
   The court, by a 6-3 vote, said Mississippi authorities are
required to pass through to retail electricity customers a
utility's federally determined share of the costs of constructing
the Grand Gulf 1 nuclear power plant.
   ``States may not regulate in areas where (the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission) exercised its jurisdiction to determine just
and reasonable wholesale rates or to insure that agreements
affcting wholesale rates are reasonable,'' Justice John Paul
Stevens wrote for the court.
   ``Mississippi, therefore, may not ... conduct any proceedings
that challenge the reasonableness of FERC's allocation'' of costs,
Stevens said.
   Mississippi Power & Light Co. provides electric service to about
330,000 customers in the western half of Mississippi.
   Its electric generation and transmission facilities are planned,
constructed and operated on a coordinated basis with those of three
affiliated utilities _ Arkansas Power & Light Co., Louisiana Power
& Light Co. and New Orleans Public Service Inc.
   In all, the companies provide electricity to customers in four
states _ Mississippi, Louisiana, Arkansas and Missouri.
   Each of the four companies is a subsidiary of Middle South
Utilities Inc., an interstate public utility holding company.
   Middle South in 1974 formed a new subsidiary to finance,
construct and operate a nuclear generating station, Grand Gulf 1,
near Port Gibson, Miss. It cost $3.6 billion to complete _ about
500 percent more than originally anticipated _ and began operations
July 1, 1985.
   After three years of proceedings, the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission decided that the costs of Grand Gulf 1 ``should be
shared equitably by all four operating companies and their
customers.''
   It ruled that MP&L should be required to pay for 33 percent of
the nuclear power plant's cost.
   The Mississippi Public Service Commission and various other
governmental agencies and officials from Mississippi, Arkansas,
Louisiana and Missouri appealed the commission's ruling. But the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here upheld most of it last year.
   The federal commission's decision required MP&L to pay enormous
amounts of money for Grand Gulf 1 power, and to get the money MP&L
asked the state Public Service Commission to approve a rate
increase.
   The state commission approved a $326.5 million increase
stretched over a 10-year period but state Attorney General Edwin
Lloyd Pittman and the Mississippi Legal Services Coalition
challenged the state commission order.
   The state Supreme Court overturned the rate increase, refusing
to accept as reasonable the federal commission's allocations of
cost.
   ``Since Mississippi cannot use 33 percent of Grand Gulf's power,
the (federal commission's ruling) providing for the allocation of
33 percent of its cost would seem to be imprudent,'' the state
court ruled.
   The state court's ruling was reversed today.
   MP&L had told the justices that the state court's ruling
conflicts with their 1987 ruling in a case from North Carolina and
Tennessee.
   In it, the justices said states must allow as reasonable
operating expenses the costs incurred by a utility as a result of
paying a wholesale price determined by federal energy regulators.
   Today's decision against Mississippi relied heavily on the 1987
ruling.
   ``Mississippi's effort to invade the province of federal
authority must be rejected,'' Stevens wrote for the high court.
   Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall and Harry A.
Blackmun dissented.
   The case is Mississippi Power & Light vs. Mississipi, 86-1970.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   06-24 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Lowers First-Quarter Growth Estimate, Raises Outlook
For Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: leads with 6 grafs with report on personal income in May,
picks up 2nd graf, Separately, the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income, held back by a decline in subsidy
payments to farmers, rose a modest 0.3 percent in May, the
government said today.
   But because of a decrease in federal tax payments, which
followed a big tax bite in April, Americans' disposable personal
income shot up 1.5 percent in May, the Commerce Department said.
That followed a 1.0 percent decline in after-tax income in April,
the biggest drop since April 1987.
   Before-tax income had edged up 0.1 percent in April after a 1.2
percent surge in March.
   Today's report said both the April and May increases look weaker
because March income was boosted by profit-sharing payments to auto
workers and retroactive Social Security payments. A lag in federal
payments to farmers also held back the May advance.
   Excluding those special factors, the government said personal
income would have advanced 0.8 percent in April and 0.4 percent in
May.
   On Thursday, the Commerce Department said the U.S. economy grew
at a 3.6 percent annual rate in the first three months of the year,
still strong although less than the previously estimated 3.9
percent rate.
   Separately, the president's Council of Economic Advisers said it
was confident enough in the economy this year to boost its growth
forecast for all of 1988 to 3.5 percent from the original estimate
of 2.9 percent.
   ``Our rosy forecast wasn't rosy enough,'' Beryl Sprinkel,
chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers, told reporters. ``The
economy is doing better than even we expected.''
   In another report, the Commerce Department said the after-tax
profits of U.S. corporations fell 1.0 percent in the first quarter,
the poorest showing since the first quarter of 1987.
   Frenzied trading in Chicago pushed the July contract for
soybeans to a 15-year high, but prices fell sharply when
uncertainty about the weather caused a nervous wave of selling.
   Corn and wheat futures also retreated on the Chicago Board of
Trade, while oats rose to record highs on fears of further damage
to the drought-ravaged crop.
   ``We're trading hysteria right now,'' Cathy Leow, a New
York-based grain analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.,
said of the soybean market's erratic performance.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 3.91
points to 2,148.29, following a nearly 70 point rise over the
preceding two sessions.
   After the October stock market collapse, many private economists
expected a slowdown or even a recession this year. But the economy
boomed.
   The administration is looking for a sixth straight year of
economic expansion, the longest in peacetime since the Civil War,
to bolster the chances for a Republican presidential victory in
November.
   Sprinkel said the expansion ``gives every indication of
continuing...on into next year.''
   A price index tied to the GNP rose at an annual rate of 1.4
percent, slightly lower than the previously estimated 1.7 percent
and well below the 2.7 percent pace of the fourth quarter.
   The concern now is that too much demand _ from American
consumers as well as from overseas buyers _ will strain factory
capacity, causing shortages and driving up prices later this year.
   In other economic news, automakers reported that sales of
domestic-made cars and light trucks rose 12.8 percent in mid-June
from a year earlier, resuming 1988's robust pace after a brief
lapse earlier in the month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     06-24 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0263</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated further early today,
at least temporarily discounting the news of a rising dollar and
