<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower, Then Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, then steadied and began
climbing back again.
   The corn, soybean and wheat markets sold off sharply Thursday
after some meteorologists increased the amount of rain in their
weather forecasts for the parched Midwest.
   Scattered showers dampened southern Minnesota and northern Iowa
overnight and those rains were expected to move eastward today and
Saturday, bringing rain to parts of Illinois, Wisconsin, Michigan
and Ohio, analysts said.
   The rainfall is light and not widespread, but analysts said it
put a scare into the heavily overbought grain markets Thursday and
should keep a lid on futures prices today.
   ``It's a very modest improvement in the weather and a lot of
people seem to think the market has topped out for the time
being,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Prices for near-term deliveries of oats rose sharply at the
opening on reports of severe, irreversible drought damage to the
oat crop.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 3{ cents lower with July
at $3.79 a bushel; corn was 2} cents to 6 cents lower with July at
$3.42 a bushel; oats were 6 cents lower to 15 cents higher with
July at $3.63 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 12{ cents lower
with July at $10.24 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
to lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent to .68 cent higher with August at
62.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent to 1.05 cent
higher with August at 70.80 cents a pound; hogs were .95 cent lower
to .45 cent higher with July at 44.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.12 cents lower to .65 cents higher with July at
39.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
