<HEAD>WTIC Agrees To Buy Taft Cable For $420 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo., (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Tele-Communications Inc. has
agreed to buy Taft Cable Partners, which owns 17 cable television
systems in Michigan and New England, for about $420 million.
   The acquisition, announced Thursday, would raise Western
Tele-Communications' subscriber count by 210,000 to a total of
560,000 if it is approved by various regulatory agencies.
   ``We feel very fortunate to be able to purchase this particular
group of cable systems,'' said Western Tele-Communications Chairman
Jeffrey A. Marcus. ``(Taft Cable) has almost 130,000 subscribers in
Michigan which will fit into our concentration of systems in
Minnesota, Wisconsin and Iowa.''
   The company also announced a vote by shareholders to change the
name of Taft Cable to WestMarc Communications Inc.
