<1ST_LINE>u f PM-PlantClosing 1stLd-Writethru f0014 06-24 0985</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,1012</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Says Severance Can't Substitute for Notices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 7 grafs to update with vote on GOP amendment; picks
up 2nd graf pvs, Senate Democratic; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats today defeated a Republican
attempt to exempt employers from giving workers and local officials
advance warning of large layoffs and plant closings if they provide
60 days' severance pay to laid off employees.
   On a 59-31 vote, the Senate rejected an amendment by Sen. Dan
Quayle, R-Ind., that would remove the obligation of employers to
provide advance notice under a Democratic-sponsored bill if the
severance pay is provided.
   ``The practice of paying severance pay in lieu of notice is a
common one and ought to be encouraged,'' Quayle said. ``The earlier
an employee can go out and develop some new skills and not be
pinned down to a job that no longer is going to be there, the
better off that employee will be.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, the primary author of the legislation,
said the amendment would defeat the bill's primary purpose.
   ``This bill is about giving notice, it's not about requiring
severance pay,'' Metzenbaum said. ``The object is not to put an
additional financial obligation on employers.''
   The vote was the first in three days of Senate debate on the
bill as Republicans attempted to stall a Democratic effort to link
enactment of the layoff notices to winning passage of a trade bill
later.
   Senate Democratic leaders had hoped to get a vote this week on
the plant closing-layoff measure, which has been separated from the
trade bill that President Reagan vetoed last month. House leaders
on Thursday promised immediate action as soon as the Senate
finished its vote.
   But GOP opponents, using lengthy speeches and long periods of
silence, thwarted any votes Thursday while declining to offer
amendments they had promised throughout the day to introduce.
   ``We're trying to make a case on this and the strongest case we
can make is on one clearly defined amendment,'' said Senate
Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``We wanted to have that vote
first.''
   However, Republicans agreed to allow votes today on other
amendments aimed at weakening the notice requirements.
   After caucusing in Dole's office, Republicans decided to have
Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., offer an amendment to strip the word
layoffs from the bill and make the mandated 60-day advance notices
apply only to plant closings.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, complained that advance notices in
cases of layoffs will ``tilt the delicate labor-management
balance'' that now exists in favor of unions.
   ``It makes it almost impossible for a business to lay off 50
people when it needs to and it will discourage union leaders from
negotiating productivity improvements,'' he said.
   Mrs. Kassebaum, however, declined to offer the amendment
Thursday out of fear that opponents would vote it down immediately.
Then she said she would be out of town Friday, effectively
forestalling any action on her amendment or a final vote on the
bill itself until at least next week.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said Mrs. Kassebaum's amendment
would create a loophole big enough to allow an employer to lay off
980 of 1,000 employes at a plant without giving them any notice.
   ``This is a killer amendment,'' said Senate Majority Leader
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va. ``Not only does it kill this bill but it
will kill the trade bill.''
   Democrats still hoped to send the plant closing bill to the
White House by July 4 for an expected veto by Reagan while holding
a revised trade bill hostage to overriding the veto.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, with the backing of 71 other
senators, on Thursday reintroduced _ without the plant closing
provision _ the trade bill vetoed by Reagan last month. A similarly
stripped-down bill was introduced in the House last week.
   Reagan cited the provision requiring employers to give workers
and local officials 60 days advance notice of layoffs of 50 people
or more as his main objection to the trade bill. But he indicated
he would sign a trade bill that did not include the layoff
provision.
   ``We may not get any, but we're not going to settle for half a
loaf,'' Byrd said Thursday. ``I've maintained all along that the
president doesn't want a trade bill.''
   Organized labor leaders agreed to removal of the layoff notice
provision from the trade legislation only on the condition that
Congress would act on it before reconsidering the trade bill.
   Since recent polls indicating that more than 80 percent of
Americans favor requiring businesses to provide workers with
advance notice of layoffs and plant closings, the issue has become
a major campaign topic.
   ``Our COPE people out in the field wanted another up-or-down
vote on plant closing alone before the election,'' one labor
official said, speaking of the AFL-CIO's Committee on Political
Education offices in the 50 states.
   Without enactment of mandatory layoff warnings as a separate
law, the AFL-CIO has threatened to withdraw its pivotal support for
any trade bill that does not include the provision.
   ``We would have no reason to support it, nor oppose it,'' said
Rex Hardesty, a spokesman for the federation.
   Other supporters of the trade bill, including many business
groups, acknowledge that the political impetus behind it might
falter without labor's support.
   Republicans admit the strategy has put them on the defensive.
   ``The judgment has been made by the majority that this is a
`hot' issue that ought be brought up and maybe we can singe a few
Republicans in the process,'' said Dole. ``Who might win in
November suddenly has become the issue, not the merits of this
bill.''
   At least one Republican senator standing for re-election, Sen.
John Chafee of Rhode Island, said he has switched during the past
month from opposing the mandated notices to supporting them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0294 </DOCNO>
