<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SocieteGenerale 1stLd-Writethru   06-24 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Societe Generale, 1st Ld-Writethru,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Agrees To Sell Part Of His Generale Stake</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 2-3 to UPDATE with De Benedetti projecting
earnings; uppicks 4th graf pvs: Under terms ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian financier Carlo de Benedetti
ended his battle for control of Societe Generale de Belgique on
Friday by announcing plans to sell most of his stake in Belgium's
largest holding company.
   Despite the outcome, De Benedetti said his bid for Societe
Generale had been a financial success. In an interview with Italian
television, he estimated he earned about $1 billion from the sale
of his stake.
   ``I would like to repeat every six months what I did in the last
six months,`` De Benedetti said at a news conference where he made
the announcement.
   Under terms of a settlement, De Benedetti's French investment
firm Cerus SA will sell 7.75 million Societe Generale shares to a
rival Franco-Belgian group. Cerus currently owns 14.25 million of
million Societe Generale's 42 million outstanding shares.
   In return, De Benedetti will boost his holding in Cie.
Financiere de Suez, a Paris-based financial services group and his
chief rival for control of Societe Generale. Suez's main ally is
Groupe AG, Belgium's largest insurance firm.
   The agreement marked the end of a bitter battle for Societe
Generale, which started in January when de Benedetti acquired 18.6
percent of the company and vowed to buy at least 15 percent more.
   The sale will reduce Cerus's holding in Societe Generale to 16
percent, thus handing control of the company to Suez and its
allies. The Franco-Belgian group currently holds about 55 percent
of Societe Generale's stock.
   In return, De Benedetti will obtain an undisclosed cash payment,
will raise his stake in Suez to about 4 percent from the current 1
percent, and will be made one of three vice presidents of Societe
Generale.
   De Benedetti said he did not believe he miscalculated his
strategy, particularly as he still will play an important role in
the new management of Societe Generale.
   The two sides said Societe Generale would continue to trade on
the Belgian stock market becuse they wanted ``once more to give the
public greater access to the capital of Societe Generale.''
   Most of Societe Generale's stock was acquired by the two groups
earlier this year at the height of the takeover battle when the
price of Societe Generale reached record levels of 8,000 Belgian
francs per share.
   Societe Generale stock closed at 4,495 francs on Thursday.
   A special shareholders meeting will be held soon to approve the
new management structure of the holding company.
   The two groups said the board would be invited to appoint De
Benedetti, Suez Chairman Renaud de la Geniere and Groupe AG
Chairman Maurice Lippens as vice chairmen of Societe Generale.
   Societe Generale, which has stakes in more than 1,200 companies,
controls about a third of Belgium's economy.
   Both De Benedetti and the Franco-Belgian group have said they
want to turn the company into a pan-European holding company ahead
of the European Economic Community's plans to eliminate trade
barriers by the end of 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
