<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TradeTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0015 06-24 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0789</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 6 grafs to show meeting concluded, picking up 5th
graf pvs, The discussions; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<HEAD>Issue of Farm Subsidies Still Separates Allies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAINERD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, Canada, Japan and the
European Community concluded a round of trade talks today with
negotiators saying they had reslved some questions but remained far
apart on the contentious issue of farm subsidies.
   At a news conference concluding the two days of meetings, U.S.
Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said that much more work was
needed before the farm subsidy issue could be resolved and at least
for the present the United States was not willing to modify its
demand for the elimination of all subsidies by the year 2000.
   ``We are not moving off any options. Maybe in 1990 we will make
some adjustments, but not in 1988,'' he said. Yeutter and the other
trade ministers pronounced themselves pleased with the progress
made on some other, less contentious issues during the two days of
talks at a resort in the Minnesota lake country.
   They said they had narrowed the differences separating them on
expanding the rules governing global trade to include trade in
services and investment, two high priorities for the United States.
   Yeutter called the talks ``productive and well-focused'' and
said they would help pave the way for successful conclustion of a
meeting of all 96 countries involved in the current trade talks to
be held in Montreal in December.
   In addition to services and investment, officials reported
progress on other issues such as protection of intellectual
property rights and reform of the process by which trade
disagreements get settled.
   The discussions by the four countries were aimed at narrowing
the differences between them before a critical trade conference in
Montreal in December.
   One area where officials said progress had been made was in
reforming the process by which the 96-member General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade resolves disputes between countries.
   ``Everybody is in favor of a better dispute settlement
mechanism,'' said Willy de Clercq, trade representative for the
European Community. ``We have to make the system run smoother and
quicker.''
   An American official, who spoke on condition his name not be
used, suggested that the countries meeting in Montreal could well
agree to the removal of some trade barriers as early as 1989.
   The current round of trade liberalization talks began in 1986 in
Uruguay and is scheduled to end in 1990. The Montreal meeting is
aimed at settling as many issues as possible and providing momentum
for the two remaining years of negotiations.
   But on the No. 1 priority of the United States, reform of
agricultural subsidies, all sides agreed they are far apart,
reflecting the heated debate that took place between Reagan and the
other six summit countries at the just-concluded Toronto summit.
   The $200 billion subsidy war has contributed to surplus
production and slumping prices, but the allies rebuffed Reagan's
call for totally scrapping subsidies. The final economic communique
simply repeated language calling for further negotiations aimed at
reducing subsidies, rather than eliminating them.
   Yeutter said that Congress could very likely increase export
subsidies, just as it did in 1985, if current global trade
negotiations on the matter appear to be at a stalemate.
   ``Sometimes one must have a higher level of confrontation in
order to achieve progress,'' he told reporters here.
   ``I am not making legislative threats. I am just giving you an
assessment of what could happen,'' Yeutter said.
   In another form of pressure, Treasury Secretary James A. Baker
III said earlier this week that country-by-country trade deals,
such as the U.S.-Canada free trade agreement, might be the way to
force other nations to capitulate in their opposition to
eliminating farm subsidies.
   Baker said that if the United States and Canada join together,
the two countries ``may be able to dislodge obstacles in special
areas of common concern such as agriculture.''
   All countries agree in principle that farm subsidies are a major
drain on their treasuries, but Europeans claim that political
pressures make it impossible to totally eliminate farm support
programs.
   Western Europe, the world's largest food importer in 1970, is
now second to the United States in the amount of food it exports.
   The United States is still the world's largest exporter of farm
commodities, accounting for about 40 percent of the volume of wheat
and feed grains sold on world markets. But since reaching a record
of $41.7 billion in 1981, U.S. farm exports steadily declined to a
low of $26.6 billion in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
