<HEAD>London Shares Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished lower Friday on the London
Stock Exchange as the market paused to catch its breath after a
strong rally over the past week.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 7.6
points, or 0.4 percent, lower at 1,871.3, below the day's best
level of 1,875.4. The session low of 15 points down came in early
trading.
   Volume was 589.0 million shares, up from Thursday's 558.9
million.
   ``The market's become very tired and emotional,'' one equity
analyst said, adding that ``it's been a reasonable week of gains
and now people are thinking that perhaps it's a bit overdone.''
   Analysts said Monday's release of British trade data for May
kept players on the sidelines. Dealers also said there was a
lingering fear that British interest rates may have to be raised
next week to support the sagging pound.
   The biggest feature of the market was news that Jacobs Suchard
AG of Switzerland withdrew from the bidding war for British
confectioner Rowntree PLC by agreeing to sell its 28.4 percent
stake in Rowntree to winning Swiss bidder Nestle SA for 690 million
pounds, or around $1.2 billion.
   On Thursday, Rowntree announced it had accepted a sweetened
Nestle offer of 2.55 billion pounds, or around $4.5 billion.
