<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Farmers-Batus 1stLd-Writethru f0107 06-24 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Farmers-Batus, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0107,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Adopts `Poison Pill' Takeover Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new grafs 5-7 to UPDATE with reaction from Batus; picks
up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, Last week, ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc., battling a
hostile $4.5 billion takeover bid by Batus Inc., announced Friday
that it had adopted a ``poison pill'' defense.
   Farmers' board of directors will issue shareholder rights
entitling holders to buy additional stock in the insurance company
at half price in the event an outsider acquires 20 percent or more
of the company's stock. Also, if the company were bought,
shareholders would be entitled to buy stock in the acquiring
company.
   Such plans, common among companies worried about takeovers, are
called ``poison pills'' because they dilute the value of the
holdings of the buying company, forcing a hostile bidder to spend
more in order to swallow the target company.
   Batus, a conglomerate based in Louisville, Ky., whose operations
include the maker of Kool cigarettes and retailers led by New
York's Saks Fifth Avenue, is offering to buy Farmers' stock for $63
a share. It has failed to persuade Farmers' management to negotiate
a friendly merger and the companies are battling in hearings before
insurance regulators in nine states who must approve a buyout.
   Batus said Friday that Farmers' adoption of the ``poison pill''
defense was ``a desperate attempt by the board to further
obstruct'' Batus' takeover bid.
   ``The adoption of this poison pill is not in the best interest
of the shareholders and policyholders, since it is intended to
retain Farmers' board's entrenched position,'' the company said in
a written statement. ``Obviously, Farmers board is responding in a
self-serving manner to increasing pressure from shareholders which
will inevitably lead to the successful completion of the
acquisition.''
   The statement also said that Friday's action ``is also a clear
signal that Farmers' board does not in reality believe it will be
successful in stopping the acquisition at the state regulatory
level.''
   Last week, California became the first state to reject Batus'
application. Batus challenged the decision by the California
Insurance Department in Los Angeles Superior Court this week.
   Earlier this month, Batus said it had received offers to sell
from holders of 28 percent of Farmers stock.
   Farmers shareholders rights are to be issued July 5 and are
valid for 10 years unless recalled by management.
   If the plan is triggered, each share of Farmers stock would
carry the right for its owner to pay $160 for $320 worth of Farmers
stock.
   Batus is a subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC of Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Rowntree Bjt   06-24 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowntree, Bjt,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jacobs Suchard Walks Away from Candy Bar Wars with Hefty Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacobs Suchard AG conceded defeat on Friday in the
takeover battle for British confectioner Rowntree PLC to Swiss
foods giant Nestle SA, which now will displace Jacobs Suchard as
the world's second-largest confectioner.
   But Jacobs Suchard, which agreed to sell its 28.4 percent stake
in Rowntree to Nestle for 690 million pounds, or $1.2 billion, is
walking away with a hefty profit, which analysts estimate at more
than 200 million pounds.
   Jacobs Suchard is now expected to turn its attention to Cadbury
Schweppes PLC, the British confectioner and soft drink company in
which General Cinema Corp. of the United States holds an 18.4
percent stake.
   On Thursday, Rowntree, the York, England-based manufacturer of
candies such as the Kit Kat bar, announced that its board had
accepted a sweetened Nestle offer of 2.55 billion pounds, or 10.75
pence a share.
   Jacobs Suchard said it would allow its own rival offer for
Rowntree of 2.32 billion pounds, or 950 pence a share, to lapse,
and Nestle later confirmed it had purchased Jacobs Suchard's entire
stake. That gives Nestle about 51 percent of all Rowntree's stock.
   Jacobs Suchard's decision to bow out gave control of Rowntree to
Nestle, ending a months-long takeover battle which created a huge
controversy in Britain and was dubbed the candy ``bar wars.''
   Critics have objected to the purchase of a 263-year-old British
company by a foreign one and have feared an acquisition would
result in layoffs.
   The merger of Rowntree into Nestle will create a confectioner
that ranks only behind Mars Inc. of the United States, the world's
biggest confectioner. Jacobs Suchard falls to third place.
   Zurich-based Jacobs Suchard, which has interests in chocolate
and coffee, said it agreed to sell to Nestle its 64.2 million
Rowntree shares at Nestle's offer price.
   Jacobs Suchard said the increased Nestle offer was higher than
the maximum price it could afford.
   Nestle, based in Vevey, Switzerland, had raised its offer 21
percent from 2.1 billion pounds, or 890 pence a share, and 13
percent above Jacobs Suchard's offer.
   The Rowntree takeover battle began April 13 when Jacobs Suchard,
which makes the Toblerone chocolate bar, snapped up nearly 15
percent of Rowntree's shares in a ``dawn raid.''
   That move prompted Nestle to jump in with its original offer
April 26. Suchard countered with its bid a month later.
   Analysts speculated Jacobs Suchard will try to reach a friendly
agreement with Cadbury Schweppes or will try to split up the
company with General Cinema, taking the confectionery business for
itself and leaving the soft drink operations with the U.S.-based
company.
   General Cinema, whose headquarters are in Chestnut Hill,
Massachusetts, has interests in movie theaters, soft drink bottling
and retailing.
   Cadbury is ``the last one that's publicly available if you want
to be among the top three world confectionery companies,'' said
Michael Landymore, a food companies analyst with the London
investment firm Henderson Crosthwaite Ltd.
   Richard Allan, a food companies analyst with Kleinwort Grieveson
Securities Ltd., said Cadbury ``is the most obvious alternative.
It's the only apparent major play in the chocolate confectionery
business left with Suchard.''
   Analysts said Jacobs Suchard's other alternatives are to acquire
small independent producers piecemeal, spend a lot of money
developing business in the Far East, where it sees the biggest
opportunities in the long term, or it could decide to develop in a
totally different direction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
