<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed To Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
to higher Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a volatile
session that saw corn and soybean prices yo-yo as bulls and bears
wrangled over the weekend weather outlook.
   ``This thing has more lives than a cat. It kept coming back and
coming back,'' Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., said of the market's erratic performance.
   Reports of scattered showers in the Farm Belt and indications
that the pattern could continue into the weekend dampened the
buying enthusiam that has driven prices up sharply this month. But
the market's resilience suggested prices could skyrocket on Monday
if the weekend is dry, Lespinasse said.
   Soybeans opened lower, climbed higher, fell sharply, then came
back to finish higher for the session but substantially lower than
the 15-year high of $10.99{ a bushel reached Thursday. Corn futures
followed a similar path but closed mixed.
   Wheat was slightly higher and 1988 oat futures, which reached
record highs earlier this week, soared the daily limit for the
fifth consecutive session on estimates that the drought in the
northern Plains has claimed 50 percent to 70 percent of the crop.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 5 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.82 a bushel; corn was 5{ cents
lower to 1{ cents higher with July at $3.42{ a bushel; oats were 8
cents lower to 15 cents higher with July at $3.63 a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 10 cents higher with July at $10.33 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
