<DOCNO> AP880624-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Africa-Debt     06-24 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Africa-Debt,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Welcome Relief, But Say It's Too Little Too Late</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Africans have cautiously hailed the
decision by the world's seven richest nations to ease the
continent's massive debt burden, but they're not expecting it to
solve their economic woes.
   ``We have reservations about the blueprint on Africa's debt,''
the Times of Zambia said in a typical African editorial reaction to
the Toronto economic summit that ended Tuesday.
   ``But there can be no doubt that it was the most significant in
the series, particularly for Africa.''
   The continent's leaders have refrained from commenting publicly
about the 14th economic summit of the United States, Britain,
Canada, France, Italy, Japan and West Germany, evidently wanting
time to assess the implications of the final communique.
   In it, the industrialized powers pledged to do more to lift the
crippling debt burdens of the poorest nations, particularly in
Africa, but made no new initiative to help Latin American debtors.
   The leaders who gathered for three days in Toronto backed a plan
offering a variety of options that will benefit most sub-Saharan
countries, such as lowering interest rates and scrapping some loan
repayments.
   But those measures fall far short of persistent African pleas to
Western creditors to write off most of their $200 billion in debts,
and reschedule others, at a time when servicing saps most of their
export income.
   French President Francois Mitterrand had appealed to summit
leaders to follow his government's example of cancelling a third of
all debts owed by sub-Saharan nations.
   On the eve of the Toronto talks, former Tanzanian President
Julius Nyerere reflected most African leaders' repeated appeals
when he told reporters in Rome: ``It is not possible for a minority
of northerners to control the wealth of the world and hope to live
in peace. Sooner or later it (the debt crisis) is going to
explode.''
   Nyerere, chairman of the South Commission set up in 1986 to
promote economic cooperation between Third World countries, urged
the rich nations to defuse a ``poverty bomb'' by writing off all
debts.
   Leaders like Nyerere argue that they have been virtually
bankrupted by foreign-fixed low prices for their exports and high
costs of imports, particularly oil. But they resist some calls to
arbitrarily cancel the debts, fearing they will be denied future
credits and trade.
   Some Western economists also cite natural calamities like
drought and famine and man-made tragedies such as civil war,
rampant corruption and government mismanagement for Africa's
economic ills.
   But all agree that most of the continent's 550 million people
suffer from lack of development and limited spending on schooling,
health and housing.
   The Toronto plan for the poor nations calls for creditor
countries to reschedule official debts, according to the final
communique.
   But it did not hold the seven powers to any particular pledges,
offering them instead options including reduced interest rates on
short-term loans, extended repayment periods at higher interest
rates, partial cancellation of loans or a combination of all those
measures.
   ``It marked the end of the disturbing silence which those
countries that Africa owes money had long maintained on the debt
issue,'' the ruling party-owned Times of Zambia noted in its
editorial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0309 </DOCNO>
