<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Steel     06-24 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Steel,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Decides To Free Steel Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community decided Friday
to free its steel market, ending a protection system that imposed
maximum production quotas on steel companies for the past eight
years.
   Taking advantage of an improving market and under pressure from
the European Commission, which is in charge of steel policy, the 12
EEC industry ministers decided to lift by July 1 the quotas applied
to four products: coils, cold-rolled sheets, heavy plates and heavy
sections.
   Quotas will remain on heavy-section steel.
   The EEC steel industry, which already lost 280,000 jobs since
the quota system was started in 1980, is bound to lose between
80,000 to 100,000 more, said European Industry Commissioner
Karl-Heinz Narjes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
