<DOCNO> AP880624-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 1719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-24 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Continues Upward Surge; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its upward surge Friday,
piercing key psychological resistance points to reach levels
against many major currencies not seen in eight months.
   Gold prices fell. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid price of $443 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, down
sharply from $447.90 late Thursday.
   Traders said activity was hectic, particularly following a
report that quoted an unnamed U.S. official as saying the dollar
could rise as high as 138 Japanese yen before diminishing the
competitiveness of the nation's exports.
   The report said ``a 5 percent increase (in the dollar) would not
be that big a deal, and we traded right up to that point,'' said
Stephen Flanagan, an assistant vice president at Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co.
   While the dollar gyrated up and down, Flanagan said the
currency's basic upward direction is ``being sparked by some very
large buying.''
   He said the dollar is ``seeing good investor demand from
Japan,'' where investors are attracted by relatively higher U.S.
interest rates as well as strong recent rallies in the stock and
bond markets.
   Still, some analysts remained puzzled by the dollar's strong
showing.
   ``From an economic point of view, there's really not all that
much fundamentally to support the dollar,'' said Jack Barbanel, a
senior vice president at Gruntal & Co.
   He noted, however, that a Commerce Department report that
personal income rose a modest 0.3 percent in May supported the
contention that inflation is in check.
   Traders shrugged off rumors of central bank intervention to stem
the dollar's advance, and the currency pushed beyond the sharp
gains it posted earlier Friday in European trading.
   Overseas, active buying by U.S. banks helped push the dollar
past the psychologically important barrier of 1.80 West German
marks late in European trading, despite midday dollar sales by the
West German central bank.
   ``People were expecting a downward correction, and when it
didn't materialize, the dollar went higher,'' said Robert Bauer, a
senior dealer at Commerzbank AG in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 1.15 Japanese yen to a closing 129.70 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 130.05 yen. In New York
the dollar posted further gains, finishing at 130.53 yen, up from
128.62 yen on Thursday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7430 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7565 late Thursday. In
New York a pound cost $1.7270, cheaper than Thursday's $1.7552.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.8155 West German marks, up from 1.7850;
1.5030 Swiss francs, up from 1.4763; 6.1110 French francs, up from
6.0050; 1,344.00 Italian lire, up from 1,323.88, and 1.2033
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2022.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8010 West German marks, up from 1.7855; 1.4945 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4800; 6.0635 French francs, up from 6.0245;
2.0305 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0145; 1,330.37 Italian lire, up
from 1,326.50, and 1.2050 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2030.
   Gold prices fell. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold closed
at $443 per troy ounce, down from $447.70 late Thursday.
   In London gold fell to a late bid price of $442.90 a troy ounce,
down from late Thursday's $448.75. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold
closed at a bid $443.50, down from $448.50. Earlier, the metal
closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $448.55, down from $449.78.
   Silver on New York's Comex fell to $6.800 a troy ounce from
$6.967 on Thursday. In London the metal was trading at a late bid
price of $6.84 a troy ounce, down from Thursday's $7.02.
</TEXT>
