<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-GroupofEight     06-24 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Group of Eight,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers to Discuss Economics At Weekend Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAXACA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of Mexico, Brazil,
Argentina, Venezuela, Colombia, Peru and Uruguay planned to spend
the weekend discussing ways to integrate Latin America's economies.
   The agenda for the two-day meeting also included the problem of
drug trafficking and ways of improving cooperation in technical,
educational and cultural areas.
   Only seven foreign ministers in the so-called Group of Eight
were attending the meeting in this state capital 300 miles south of
Mexico City.
   Panama was suspended in February because of the political crisis
precipitated by the U.S. drug-trafficking indictment against its
military ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The sensitive issue of Panama's standing will be taken up Monday
at a separate meeting in Mexico City, officials said. The group has
also deferred its discussion about the slow progress of a regional
peace plan for Central America until Monday.
   Officials of several regional economic and development
organizations were at the Oaxaca meeting to ``exchange points of
view about schemes for coordinating the process of integration,''
the Mexican Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
   The statement said the foreign ministers would also discuss the
recent economic summit of the major industrialized nations in
Toronto.

</TEXT>
