<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ContinentalLoss     06-24 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Loss,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Airlines Sees Second-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines said Friday it expected to
report a second-quarter loss because of a $131 million upward
revision in estimated expenses for foreign currency fluctuations
and passenger scheduling foulups.
   Continental said in a statement that the revised estimate would
be identified separately in the second-quarter earnings report of
its parent firm, Texas Air Corp.
   The Houston-based airline said its estimates for categories such
as ticketing errors and currency fluctuations were short by $67
million, while estimates for reaccommodation costs for transporting
ticketholders on other airlines was off by $64 million.
   ``These accounts are really unearned revenue,'' spokesman Bruce
Hicks said. ``When we collect for tickets, until flights are flown,
it is unearned revenue and an air traffic liability.
   ``The number always is an estimate. We noticed a decline in that
account very recently and did a thorough review and in last few
days determined the magnitude of this.''
   The airline said that like other carriers, it conducts an annual
verification of such accounts, but made the review earlier than
normal because the accounts had been declining in recent months.
   Hicks said the changes in estimates would have no impact on
current or future cash levels of Continental and that the airline
expects to be profitable for the last half of 1988.
</TEXT>
