<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PaylessCashways     06-24 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Payless Cashways,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Payless Management Offers $875 Million for Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top management of Payless Cashways Inc.
offered to acquire the building materials company for $875 million
in an apparent effort to discourage unwanted attention from New
York investor Asher B. Adelman.
   A group headed by Payless chairman David Stanley offered to pay
$26 a share for the company's 33.6 million shares of common stock
outstanding.
   The management offer pre-empts any attempt at making a bid by
Edelman, who has been building a stake in Payless and has said he
might be interested in bidding for the nation's third-largest
building materials retailer.
   Stanley, who is also chief executive, and other members of
management acknowledged two weeks ago they were considering a
buyout.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Payless Cashways rose
$2.62{ a share to $25.62{. It was one of the 10 most-active issues.
   Edelman amassed his stake with Sutherland Lumber-Southwest Inc.
of Kansas City, a privately owned Payless competitor that operates
about 86 building materials stores in Midwest and Southern states.
   At one point the Edelman group held about 9.9 percent of
Payless's outstanding shares but has recently been reducing its
holdings, which now account for about 8.1 percent of the company's
shares.
   Perry Sutherland, an executive in Sutherland Lumber, said the
group was still interested in acquiring Payless.
   The Payless management group said it has received commitments to
finance the entire offer, which would be structured as a leveraged
buyout. In a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy a
company and then pay off the debt with the target company's cash
flow or the sale of its assets.
   The group headed by Stanley owned less than 2 percent of the
company stock at the time of the last proxy statement on Feb. 25.
   Payless said a special committee of independent directors formed
to consider takover proposals would evaluate the proposal.
   Payless serves the home improvement, maintenance and repair
market with 200 retail stores in 26 states.
   Other managers involved in the offer include Larry P. Kunz,
president and chief operating officer, and Melvin Cohen and Harold
Cohen, co-chairmen of Somerville Lumber and Supply Inc., a Payless
subsidiary.
   The Edelman group had said in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission that it would consider selling Payless
operations as ``going concerns'' in many regions of the country.
   Bruce Benteman, a research analyst at the securities firm Wealth
Monitors Inc., said he didn't expect Edelman to make a serious
counteroffer for Payless. Benteman said Edelman had probably sold
off more Payless stock since the last report.
</TEXT>
