<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GEContract     06-24 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GE Contract,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Workers at Indiana Plant May Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,800 workers at General
Electric Corp.'s plant here may be headed to the picket line if
their union's local and national negotiators don't reach a contract
settlement soon.
   Representatives of the company and the dozen labor unions which
represent GE's 67,000 union employees have been meeting in New York
since June 17 trying to negotiate a national contract. The current
contract expires at midnight Sunday.
   A bargaining team from the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers Local 2249 has been trying to negotiate a local
contract for workers. But, those negotiations have been postponed
until next week because the union's president is involved in
national negotations in New York.
   Most of GE's unionized workers are covered by the national
contract. However, the electrical workers union operates
independently, which means that salary and benefits settlements are
based on those reached in national negotiations, but are not
formally bound by national contracts. Work rules and other local
issues are negotiated separately as part of the local contract.
   A telephone taped message for unionized GE employees from the
national negotiating committee Friday said negotiations were
stalemated and urged workers to prepare for a possible strike.
   ``So far, bargaining progress is non-existent,'' the recording
said. ``There is a real possibility we will be forced to strike.
Members are urged to prepare for a job action, and make sure
management knows you are militant.''
   However, a clause in the existing contract requires the union to
give the company 10 days notice before calling a strike. GE
Bloomington Manager of Employee Relations Mike Horrigan said the
electrical workers local is not technically required to follow the
terms of the national contract, but has always done so.
   GE officials at company headquarters in Fairfield, Conn.,
believe that the differences between the company and the unions can
be resolved.
   ``There are still differences to resolve, but we believe that
both parties will make every effort to work out agreement,'' said
Jack Batty, a GE spokesman.
   ``We still have two days to go, and we'll be negotiating right
up to the deadline. We're still very hopeful that there will be a
satisfactory settlement,'' he said.
   ``We're working toward a Sunday deadline, and the two sides are
meeting continuously,''said Jerry Borstel, a spokesman for the IUE
and the joint union bargaining committee. ``We don't know at this
point what's going to happen, but we do expect to get an offer from
GE on Sunday.
   ``It's important that our members not assume that this thing is
going to be easy or anything like that,'' he said.
   Borstel said job security has been a major issue in the national
negotiations because of a large number of layoffs, cutbacks and
plant shutdowns during the past few years. He said the union also
hopes to win a substantial wage increase for workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880624-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 2313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   06-24 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0526</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income and spending grew
modestly in May, but economists said consumer spending likely will
weaken this summer as wages lag behind inflation.
   The Commerce Department reported Friday that income rose 0.3
percent last month following a 0.1 percent gain in April.
   Meanwhile, personal consumption expenditures, which include
virtually everything except interest on debt, rose a moderate 0.5
percent in May following a 0.4 percent increase in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riverboat business has shriveled as the
worst drought in 50 years slowed traffic on the mighty Mississippi
River.
   Boats and barges were parked along a 40-mile stretch of the
Mississippi around Memphis until Friday when the river near Memphis
was reopened after a three-day shutdown because of low water levels.
   Floating stores, fuel depots and other river businesses depend
on healthy traffic along the river for their survival and some say
the prolonged drought is responsible for a 40 percent drop in
business.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frenzied activity reigns on the floor of the
Chicago Board of Trade, the world's oldest and largest grain
exchange, as one man profits from another's misery during the
latest drought-spurred grain rally.
   The population of the grain trading floor has swelled more than
40 percent to nearly 2,000 in just the past two months, exchange
figures said Friday.
   As the drought withers crops across the Farm Belt, it ignites
big rallies on commodity exchanges, where contracts for future
delivery of grain grow more precious by the day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top management of Payless Cashways Inc.
has offered to acquire the building materials company for $875
million in an apparent effort to discourage unwanted attention from
investor Asher B. Adelman.
   A group headed by Payless chairman David Stanley offered Friday
to pay $26 a share for the company's 33.6 million shares of common
stock outstanding.
   Edelman has been building a stake in Payless and has said he
might be interested in bidding for it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacobs Suchard AG is walking away from the candy
``bar wars'' with a hefty profit after being defeated by Nestle SA
in its takeover battle for British confectioner Rowntree PLC.
   Analysts said Friday that Suchard, a Zurich-based confectioner
and coffee company, may now turn its attention to another takeover
target after selling its 28.4 percent stake in Rowntree PLC to
Nestle for $1.2 billion.
   Suchard withdrew from the takeover contest after Rowntree
accepted Nestle's offer which would create the second largest
confectioner in the world behind Mars Inc., of the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRAINERD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter
hinted that the administration might be willing to back off its
demand for total elimination of farm subsidies by the end of the
century in favor of a phaseout period.
   Yeutter's statement on Friday followed two days of talks between
the United States and its major trading partners aimed at reducing
protectionist pressures.
</TEXT>
